WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
[Amit Varma]: People often think of economists as people of ideas who have no connection with the real

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:15.860
[Amit Varma]: world. Indeed, we live in times when intellectuals are looked down upon, and we want our leaders

00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:22.000
[Amit Varma]: to be men of action. Our Prime Minister famously once said, quote, hard work is much more powerful

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.720
[Amit Varma]: than Harvard, stop quote. He said this while defending demonetization, by the way, and

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:31.680
[Amit Varma]: we all know how that went down. His statement also assumes that people from Harvard don't

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:37.120
[Amit Varma]: work hard, which is silly. My guest today did his PhD in economics from Harvard, and

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:41.400
[Amit Varma]: I can guarantee you that he has spent more time in the towns and villages of India than

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:46.480
[Amit Varma]: many of our politicians. Karthik Muralidharan once invoked a headline from the Financial

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:52.840
[Amit Varma]: Times to sum up a key value of his, quote, the best economist is one with dirty shoes,

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:57.640
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. Karthik teaches and lives in the US, but has spent 1000s of hours in interior

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:08.000
[Amit Varma]: India, trying to get to the heart of one of our biggest problems, the state of our education.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.200
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:20.000
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.640
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. I keep saying on the show, ideas have consequences.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: We only need to look at Indian education to see how true this is. Our education system

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:35.400
[Amit Varma]: is broken because for decades, our politicians and policymakers have held the wrong ideas

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:40.800
[Amit Varma]: about education. All the conventional wisdom was wrong. And the consequences of that are

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.840
[Amit Varma]: a humanitarian disaster. Hundreds of millions of Indians through the years haven't reached

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.240
[Amit Varma]: anywhere close to their true potential. And it's hard to dispute that this has led to

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:55.920
[Amit Varma]: all our other problems, such as those of poverty and gender being much worse than they otherwise

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:02.380
[Amit Varma]: would be. This is a moral crisis. And it began as a crisis of knowledge. My guest today is

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Karthik Muralidharan, the brilliant economist who has had his boots on the ground for a

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:11.080
[Amit Varma]: couple of decades now. Karthik is the global co-chair of education at the Jameel Poverty

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Action Lab or J-PAL. And he has written more papers on Indian education than anyone else

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:22.040
[Amit Varma]: I know. He has spent thousands of hours all across India, conducting experiments and gathering

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:28.000
[Amit Varma]: evidence for all kinds of theories and interventions. And he advises various state governments in

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
[Amit Varma]: India. It could be argued that these are exciting times for economists, because we are now much

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.840
[Amit Varma]: better at testing our ideas against evidence, a subject for which Karthik's colleagues and

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:42.800
[Amit Varma]: mentors Abhijit Banerjee, Esther Duflo and Michael Kremer won the Nobel Prize for Economics

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:47.800
[Amit Varma]: last year. I had a long conversation with Karthik, of which the first hour, by the way,

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:53.600
[Amit Varma]: is a to and fro on PPE, philosophy, politics and economics, all of which are a part of

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:59.600
[Amit Varma]: our education system. So we get into the weeds of Indian education only after an hour or

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:05.520
[Amit Varma]: so. But I loved every little bit of this conversation, which felt too short to me. Before we get

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:08.320
[Amit Varma]: to this conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:41.400
[Amit Varma]: level of podcasts. I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode. Besides all

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:47.000
[Amit Varma]: the logistics of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.840
[Amit Varma]: technicians, the travel and so on. So well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:57.520
[Amit Varma]: going. And that involves you. My proposition for you is this. For every episode of the

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:02.680
[Amit Varma]: scene and the unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:08.280
[Amit Varma]: you feel it's worth. You can do this by heading over to scene unseen.in slash support and

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:14.000
[Amit Varma]: contributing an amount of your choice. This is not a subscription. The scene and the unseen

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
[Amit Varma]: will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at scene unseen.in. This is just a gesture

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.680
[Amit Varma]: of appreciation. Help keep this thing going. scene unseen.in slash support.

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:33.400
[Amit Varma]: Karthik, welcome to the scene and the unseen. My pleasure. I really look forward to this.

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Karthik, you know, before we get down to the subject at hand, which is a naughty subject

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:41.760
[Amit Varma]: at of education, let's get to the subject of your education by which I don't mean your

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:48.960
[Amit Varma]: formal education per se. But what's your intellectual journey been like? What makes Karthik Muralitharan

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:53.600
[Amit Varma]: who he is? Tell me a little bit about sort of your background and your formative influences.

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:58.560
[Guest]: Yeah, thanks, Amit. I think, you know, like you said, so, you know, mechanically, I grew

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:03.160
[Guest]: up in Ahmedabad. So I'm already kind of a pretty pan Indian by temperament, because

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:07.160
[Guest]: I'm Tamilian. I grew up in Ahmedabad. So I speak Hindi, Gujarati, Tamil. So in that sense,

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:12.040
[Guest]: my influence is a pretty pan Indian. I'm also, you know, my schooling was very idyllic, actually.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:16.480
[Guest]: Ahmedabad was a great city to grow up in. And so I was on a standard engineering track.

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:20.400
[Guest]: My dad was an IIT graduate. And so, you know, that was the default of what you did. But

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:24.120
[Guest]: I think I started getting interested in economics pretty early, because my dad would just bring

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:27.640
[Guest]: home the economist and just kind of leave it around casually. And I probably started

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:32.520
[Guest]: reading it or skimming articles from the age of 12, almost. But I think by the time I was

00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:37.040
[Guest]: 16, is when economic liberalization happens. I've been born in 75. And so that was kind

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:43.440
[Guest]: of, you know, a moment of just getting hooked on to economics, economic policy. And there

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.040
[Guest]: was an interesting tangent as to how I got in economics, which is I was appearing for

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:51.720
[Guest]: this national talent search exam, you know, which is done by the CBSE. And the thing is,

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:55.400
[Guest]: you had there were four natural sciences, physics, chemistry, math, and biology, and

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:59.760
[Guest]: four social sciences, history, civics, geography, and economics. I was studying in Gujarat State

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:03.960
[Guest]: Board, right? And so basically, my physics, chemistry, maths was up to national standards

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:07.960
[Guest]: because of studying for IIT. But my biology was nowhere, like, you know, I looked at this

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:12.520
[Guest]: and boss, is my failure. So, and, you know, I think my dad was okay, listen, why don't

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:15.660
[Guest]: you just pick up one of the social sciences and economics is something you read so much

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:18.840
[Guest]: about anyway, so you could do it. So then I did a crash course and kind of preparing

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:22.280
[Guest]: myself for the exam. So there was a formal part of getting up to economics. And there

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:27.040
[Guest]: was kind of the informal part that was happening with liberalization. But I think the really

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:31.600
[Guest]: big inflection point in my life was when I won the scholarship at 16 to go to Singapore.

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:35.520
[Guest]: And so I did my last two years of high school in Singapore. And the main academic reason

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:41.040
[Guest]: I went was this was 91, the opportunity to mix and match across subjects, which is possible

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:45.160
[Guest]: now, but which wasn't possible then, right? So I did British A levels of math, physics,

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:49.880
[Guest]: chemistry, so kept all the engineering options open, but did economics as a fourth subject.

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:54.200
[Guest]: And I think those two years in Singapore were really the most life changing experience in

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:58.480
[Guest]: terms of not just the academic study of economics, where I had a fantastic teacher, but also

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:02.320
[Guest]: just studying the Singapore economy and recognizing that, you know, here was a place that was

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:08.400
[Guest]: poorer than India. 25 years ago, I got there in 91, late 91. And, you know, 65 is when

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:12.160
[Guest]: Singapore became independent. And then, you know, you just kind of get obsessed with the

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:17.280
[Guest]: importance of good economic policy and the centrality of effective policy in lifting

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:20.880
[Guest]: millions of people out of poverty and giving them a good quality of life. So in fact, you

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:25.560
[Guest]: know, Bob Lucas, who won the Nobel Prize in 95, he has this famous paper in 1988 called

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:29.560
[Guest]: On the Mechanics of Economic Development, where he starts by saying that once you think

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:34.840
[Guest]: about the disparities in living standards across countries and think about what policies

00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:39.440
[Guest]: and India and Indonesia might adopt that might allow them to grow faster. And when you think

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.160
[Guest]: about the staggering consequences of that for human welfare, it becomes impossible to

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:47.160
[Guest]: think about anything else. So in a way, I was living Bob Lucas's quote in my head well

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:50.920
[Guest]: before I ever read the paper. And, you know, so that's how I got hooked on economics. And

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:54.480
[Guest]: then I think, you know, the Singapore years were pretty crucial, because I left home,

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:57.640
[Guest]: I was in the hostel. So it's one of those things where, you know, when you get homesick

00:07:57.640 --> 00:08:01.960
[Guest]: and miss your family and friends, one way to go is, you know, you kind of just mope.

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:06.760
[Guest]: The other way was to just dive into your work all out. So the marginal kind of intellectual

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:10.600
[Guest]: leap I had in those two years was probably the highest. And then I was just, you know,

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:14.280
[Guest]: super lucky at various stages that, you know, the options that were open after that were

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:18.960
[Guest]: options I wouldn't even have considered coming out of India. So, you know, then my advisors

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.800
[Guest]: and high school teachers were all kind of saying, listen, you should be applying to

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:26.120
[Guest]: the top colleges in the world. And I'm like, really me? And they're like, yes, you know,

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:29.880
[Guest]: we've seen students over the years, and that's where you should be applying. And then, you

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:34.320
[Guest]: know, I've just been incredibly fortunate at various stages, you know, undergrad, I,

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:37.840
[Guest]: you know, had a choice between Oxford and Harvard and went to Harvard, mainly because

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:42.880
[Guest]: of the financial aid. And then, you know, the undergrad influences in economics were

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:47.280
[Guest]: in a partly Amartya Sen, but partly just a whole range, like being a kid in a candy store,

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:51.960
[Guest]: right, of the range of courses and everything you took. So it was quite clear early on that

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:57.560
[Guest]: I would care about academic economics, but with a view to improving policy. And then,

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:00.920
[Guest]: you know, after Harvard, after four years, I had this vestigial regret of having turned

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:04.880
[Guest]: down Oxford for my undergrad. And so I did a one-year master's in Cambridge on a fellowship.

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:09.640
[Guest]: And so that was a fun year. And in fact, I followed Amartya Sen to Trinity, and he won

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:13.600
[Guest]: the Nobel within six weeks of my getting there. But that was a fun year. In fact, you know,

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:19.040
[Guest]: you will appreciate this, given your Crick Info past, right? In fact, it was in 1998-99

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:23.560
[Guest]: in England. So that was the year I, you know, I bought my Cricket World Cup tickets in advance.

00:09:23.560 --> 00:09:27.240
[Guest]: So I followed the Indian cricket team around. That was the year Paz and Bhupati won Wimbledon.

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:30.960
[Guest]: So it was a good year to be in England. So, but anyway, like, you know, I think England

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:34.120
[Guest]: year was fun. But I think the other thing I got from Singapore was a very, very healthy

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:38.800
[Guest]: respect for the private sector, right, which is something that your typical academic economist

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:44.520
[Guest]: or typical kind of government bureaucrat doesn't always have. And so before I went to my PhD,

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:48.600
[Guest]: I really wanted to have a private sector experience. And one of the things I did in college was

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:52.840
[Guest]: I learned Chinese. And so I went back to Singapore, worked in management consulting for a couple

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:58.080
[Guest]: of years, and this is 99-2001, at a time when China has not yet entered the WTO. So most

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:02.360
[Guest]: Fortune 500 companies, Asian headquarters were in Singapore or Hong Kong, and with some

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:07.160
[Guest]: shifting towards Singapore because of Hong Kong getting, you know, the 97 kind of implications

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:11.880
[Guest]: for independent China. So it was a great time to basically just think about how private

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:16.080
[Guest]: capital thinks, right? So the kind of work we were doing was really Pan-Asian strategies,

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:20.280
[Guest]: looking at where do you source your production, where are the markets? So it was an incredibly

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:24.680
[Guest]: valuable two years. But it was also very clear that I was not interested in climbing a corporate

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:29.800
[Guest]: hierarchy per se, as much as taking that understanding of how private capital thinks and applying

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:33.800
[Guest]: that in the public interest, right? And then, you know, I came back to my PhD. And, you

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:37.360
[Guest]: know, since you're a personal, this thing that's not in the, I've had some interesting

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:41.200
[Guest]: detours about like, you know, thinking about different pathways to policy, thinking about

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:44.840
[Guest]: active politics, thinking about things. And then I think multiple mentors and advisors

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:48.280
[Guest]: at various points said, listen, your comparative advantage is always going to be intellectual,

00:10:48.280 --> 00:10:52.880
[Guest]: right? Like, you know, I mean, so go ahead and get the PhD. And, you know, be an academic,

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:57.040
[Guest]: but stay engaged with policy. And that's kind of roughly what I've done. And again, I've

00:10:57.040 --> 00:11:01.560
[Guest]: been super lucky in the sense that I came to my PhD at a time when development economics

00:11:01.560 --> 00:11:06.080
[Guest]: was becoming much more empirical. So if this was in the 80s and 90s, when you were really

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.560
[Guest]: just writing a lot of applied theory models and trying to argue which type of poverty

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: trap was kind of creating poverty, I might have lost interest, right? But it was at a

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.840
[Guest]: time when, you know, you really had to get your shoes dirty, go to the field, understand

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:21.320
[Guest]: what was happening. And I kind of, you know, the RCT movement was happening around that

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:26.240
[Guest]: time. And I was kind of the first wave of the students of this year's Nobel Prize winners,

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:29.960
[Guest]: right? So Michael Kramer was my direct advisor, and Abhijit Nester, you know, they taught

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:36.160
[Guest]: us the PhD development sequence together in my second year in grad school. So and then,

00:11:36.160 --> 00:11:39.800
[Guest]: you know, I think how I got into education. So at heart, I've really been a public, I'm

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:44.680
[Guest]: still a public finance economist, right? So the focus has always been on effectiveness

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:48.800
[Guest]: of policy and for which public finance is like the core policy field that is both in

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:53.120
[Guest]: the revenue side and the expenditure side. And then the interest in education specifically,

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:58.200
[Guest]: I think, came from, you know, partly there's the Sennian influence about belief in human

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:02.440
[Guest]: development and human capital. But, you know, I've always kind of believed in Sennian ends

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:05.880
[Guest]: but disagreed with Senn on means, right? You know, we can come back to that when we talk

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:10.440
[Guest]: about vouchers and how, you know, the Sennian influence itself sometimes would suggest the

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.880
[Guest]: case for more market-based provision of basic services. But anyway, I think, you know, the

00:12:14.880 --> 00:12:19.960
[Guest]: PhD, the RCT movement, you know, is very technocratic, is kind of very, in some ways it's humble,

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:25.280
[Guest]: right? So there's an aspect of methodological hubris where it gets pushed back of saying

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:29.120
[Guest]: it's a gold standard. But it's also at its essence, it's about humility, which is to

00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:33.560
[Guest]: say that we have way more theories than we have data. And at some point, you just need

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:39.000
[Guest]: to subject your theories to real evidence. And so how I got into education was really,

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.760
[Guest]: there was this conference in Imrana in 2001 at the end where I was a first-year PhD student.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:47.920
[Guest]: And this is this, you know, really high-level policy conference of top US economists, Indian

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:51.760
[Guest]: economists, the who's who of the Indian kind of policy establishment were there. And I

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:55.520
[Guest]: was this eager beaver PhD student sitting there taking notes. And there were two entire

00:12:55.520 --> 00:13:00.040
[Guest]: sessions on education. And, you know, the four speakers were literally like the who's

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.640
[Guest]: who, right? There was Abhijit Banerjee, there was Michael Kramer, there was Caroline Hoxby,

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:07.440
[Guest]: and there was Rukmini Banerjee, right, providing a field-based perspective. And, you know,

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:12.200
[Guest]: it just got me hooked in the sense of both how important the topic was and how abysmal

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:17.560
[Guest]: our performance was and the ability and the potential of good research to try and influence

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:23.080
[Guest]: and inform the allocation of public resources to better the common good. The education then

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:27.760
[Guest]: just became the topic into which a lot of these principles, you know, that I ended up

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:31.680
[Guest]: working on. So anyway, so, you know, and then there's the specific research projects I started

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:36.520
[Guest]: doing. My first major study was this All India study on teacher and doctor absenteeism in

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:41.520
[Guest]: the public sector. And very simple descriptive work, not fancy RCT, right? All we did was

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:45.760
[Guest]: make surprise visits to over 1,500 schools across the country. And that was when I got

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:49.560
[Guest]: my fieldwork experience. You know, so it was a wonderful, wonderful experience just seeing

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:54.480
[Guest]: rural India, seeing the schools, seeing the reality, and then just crafting survey instruments

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:59.640
[Guest]: to just learn what was going on. And I think, you know, having them documented facts on

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:03.360
[Guest]: teacher absence and just how much, given the salaries are the biggest component of the

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:08.840
[Guest]: budget, just how much fiscal leakage you get just from that one line item. And then, you

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:13.560
[Guest]: know, part of I think where I have been, the policy motivation for what I do always shows

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:17.640
[Guest]: in the sense that I care about the academic paper, but the motivation is always that how

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:21.880
[Guest]: does this research help us understand, improve understanding for policy. And then over the

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:26.320
[Guest]: years, we've had some fantastic collaborations, particularly in Andhra Pradesh. This is the,

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:30.520
[Guest]: you know, undivided Andhra Pradesh where we set up a series of long term studies on both

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:35.000
[Guest]: randomized trials, as well as longitudinal follow-up of kids. And we've learned an enormous

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.760
[Guest]: amount from that research. So, you know, which I'll talk more about on the call. And then

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:42.760
[Guest]: I think in terms of the policy engagement, you know, I've always been fortunate in the

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:47.640
[Guest]: sense of having exposure to conferences and access to the technocratic leadership in the

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:50.720
[Guest]: country, right? So, you know, whether it's the chief economic advisors, whether it's

00:14:50.720 --> 00:14:54.040
[Guest]: the planning commission, senior folks, people like Dr. Monte Carlo Valle have been like,

00:14:54.040 --> 00:14:58.400
[Guest]: you know, long term mentors and influences. And so in that sense, there were windows to

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:04.000
[Guest]: then provide inputs based on policy. And then around 2012, when I was frankly very frustrated

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.720
[Guest]: with the RTE, which I, you know, which I really think set us back in multiple ways, right?

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:13.160
[Guest]: It's kind of a classic example of good intentions that are counterproductive. And we can talk

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:17.580
[Guest]: more about that. I remember just being very, very frustrated at how policy was not reflecting

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:21.480
[Guest]: any of the evidence. And I think Dr. Aluwalia told me, he said, listen, you know, you write

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:25.120
[Guest]: these great papers that get published in the top journals, like, you know, and we might

00:15:25.120 --> 00:15:29.120
[Guest]: at best come to a seminar and clap our hands and say, good job. But in the end, the policy

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:33.880
[Guest]: is still written by people who are essentially bureaucrats and who don't understand the research.

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:36.960
[Guest]: So if you want to start having impact, you need to roll up your sleeves and kind of,

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:40.360
[Guest]: you know, get involved a bit more. And so then he invited me to write a background paper

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:44.520
[Guest]: to the 12th Five-Year Plan. And then a lot of the language in that paper ended up making

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:48.520
[Guest]: it to the Five-Year Plan. And then after that, you know, I think he again said, listen, you

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:51.920
[Guest]: know, it's one thing to put things in a planning document, but now you need to start engaging

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:56.720
[Guest]: much more in terms of making this happen. And so then, you know, both with MHRD, where

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:01.000
[Guest]: we've done some workshops, and then over time, you know, where I spend most of my policy

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.200
[Guest]: time, frankly, is with the states, right? Because 90% of service delivery functions

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:10.480
[Guest]: are with state governments. And so I continue to work across a range of states, testing

00:16:10.480 --> 00:16:15.160
[Guest]: a bunch of, you know, continuing to do research, but continuing to also synthesize. So I think

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:18.360
[Guest]: one of the things, again, that Dr. Aluwalia, I think, said to me, which, you know, maybe

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:22.840
[Guest]: not in the exact words, but the spirit, which I say is, you know, is like, you need to learn

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:27.120
[Guest]: to segment your brain into the researcher who says that I know nothing, because you

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:32.200
[Guest]: realize how little you know. And so the academic, this thing is always about fine tuning our

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:37.040
[Guest]: understanding on relatively narrow areas of uncertainty. But in the policy space, it's

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:40.760
[Guest]: like, whether you have research evidence or not, we are still making decisions. And so

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:44.600
[Guest]: you need to then be comfortable with saying, we don't have all the answers, but here is

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:48.560
[Guest]: the best I would recommend based on what we know. And so, you know, that's kind of then

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:52.480
[Guest]: being the spirit of my policy writing, you know, so I wrote that 12-plan paper. And then

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:55.760
[Guest]: for the new education policy, which we'll talk about, you know, I've provided extensive

00:16:55.760 --> 00:17:00.120
[Guest]: set of comments in writing. And the good news is many of those things have been incorporated

00:17:00.120 --> 00:17:03.960
[Guest]: like, you know, in the NEP. But the note of caution is that many of that language was

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:08.120
[Guest]: also in the 12-5-year plan. And so then we'll come back and talk about implementation and

00:17:08.120 --> 00:17:11.960
[Guest]: what it's going to take to take some of these ideas to action. But yeah, hopefully that

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:15.720
[Guest]: gives you some sense of the personal aspect behind this, right? Which is, you know, another

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:21.400
[Guest]: kind of way I think about this is in the nonprofit sector, you have tons of very motivated nonprofits

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:25.600
[Guest]: trying to improve education, trying to improve development outcomes, right? But the 800-pound

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:29.720
[Guest]: gorilla in the room is the government. And so the government spends over 300,000 crores

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:34.360
[Guest]: a year in education. And so if you can improve the effectiveness of that by 1%, right, that's

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:38.960
[Guest]: basically bigger than the CSR budget and education of almost any kind of, you know, entity that's

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:43.880
[Guest]: running schools or providing scholarships. And so it's a very, very hard beast to move,

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:48.760
[Guest]: but the returns to improving effectiveness of government expenditure is massive. And

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:50.440
[Guest]: that's, that's what I spend my time on.

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:54.080
[Amit Varma]: That's extremely fascinating. Now, before we get down to the nitty gritties of talking

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:59.120
[Amit Varma]: about your experience and of Indian education and your insights from it, a few threads to

00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:02.760
[Amit Varma]: unpack. Number one, I thought if someone from Oxford listens to this, they're going to get

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:06.720
[Amit Varma]: really pissed off because you basically said, Hey, I missed out on Oxford. So I went to

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:15.160
[Amit Varma]: Cambridge for a master's. Leaving that aside, I also found this particularly fascinating

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:20.040
[Amit Varma]: what Dr. Aluwalia told you about policy that whereas you may, as an academic, you approach

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:24.360
[Amit Varma]: something with extreme humility, and you're trying to work on one small margin of something,

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:28.440
[Amit Varma]: but as a policy person, you have to have a clear direction which you're showing. And

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:31.760
[Amit Varma]: that seems to me to be a lot like, you know, what Harry Truman once said when he was president

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:36.160
[Amit Varma]: about give me a one handed economist, because all his economists kept saying on the one

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:40.680
[Amit Varma]: hand this on the other hand. And I was also sort of fascinated. And this is something

00:18:40.680 --> 00:18:45.080
[Amit Varma]: that this is a thread I come across in the personal journeys of many of my guests, which

00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:50.320
[Amit Varma]: is a role of serendipity and chance, like you've spoken about how you'd have the economist

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:54.920
[Amit Varma]: lying around at home. And in those days, economist was far better than it is today, though it's

00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:59.600
[Amit Varma]: still, you know, a model of clear writing on complex subjects. So I can imagine, you

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:03.560
[Amit Varma]: know, the influence that would have had going to Singapore. I'm sure you've thought about

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:07.480
[Amit Varma]: where you might have been if not for sort of all of these, the thread that I want to

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:12.640
[Amit Varma]: examine a little bit further before we actually start talking about education is what you

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:18.560
[Amit Varma]: said about your disagreement with Sen on means and ends. And I think this is where, for example,

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:22.560
[Amit Varma]: someone like Mahatma Gandhi diverged from a lot of the other leaders of our independence

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:28.600
[Amit Varma]: movement where Gandhi was always all about no matter what the ends are, the means matter.

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:33.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, we sort of came into this republic with a mindset of that these are our noble

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:38.680
[Amit Varma]: goals. These are our ends. And the means are inevitably state coercion. And I can see this

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:43.280
[Amit Varma]: playing out at two levels where the first part of my question is that when you start

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:46.880
[Amit Varma]: examining this, and some of your early training was to be an engineer, but at the same time,

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:51.120
[Amit Varma]: you've seen the power of free markets in Singapore, and you've read The Economist, but how do

00:19:51.120 --> 00:19:55.120
[Amit Varma]: you sort of handle this dichotomy between means and ends and keep telling yourself that

00:19:55.120 --> 00:19:59.160
[Amit Varma]: listen, you know, whatever beautiful policy I may recommend it is after all the heavy

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:03.700
[Amit Varma]: hand of the state, which often has to carry it out. And that mindset, of course, is changing.

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:07.640
[Amit Varma]: And the second part, which I'll explore immediately afterwards, but the second part also is that

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:13.200
[Amit Varma]: then this tacit acceptance that listen, there is going to be a certain amount of state coercion

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:17.960
[Amit Varma]: involved here. So let's at least make sure that it is effective and justified by bringing

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:22.760
[Amit Varma]: experimental methods and RCTs and all of that, which I'll explore shortly. But on this whole

00:20:22.760 --> 00:20:27.960
[Amit Varma]: broader question, how has your thinking on means and ends, you know, specific because

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:33.480
[Amit Varma]: you after all deal in a field where there is significant amount of state presence and

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:37.120
[Amit Varma]: state presence is equal to state coercion, you know, all of this money that is being

00:20:37.120 --> 00:20:41.960
[Amit Varma]: spent on education is after all, coming from somewhere. So how has your thinking sort of

00:20:41.960 --> 00:20:46.080
[Amit Varma]: evolved on this? And, you know, and can you elaborate a bit on your differences with the

00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:47.640
[Amit Varma]: Sanyan view as you put it?

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:51.800
[Guest]: Yeah, so and I think, you know, this is, you know, I'm just starting to see why the conversations

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:54.960
[Guest]: are so much fun than lectures, right? Because you can follow tangents, follow nooks and

00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:59.680
[Guest]: crannies. So remind me because of your cricket forepast to tell you one very important cricket

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:03.760
[Guest]: joke, not just a joke, a cricket true story in my life, but that has to do with my year

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.840
[Guest]: in Cambridge, because you mentioned Oxford in Cambridge, right? But yeah, so I think

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:10.040
[Guest]: the Oxford-Cambridge joke notwithstanding. So I think, you know, coming back to Sanyan,

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:15.520
[Guest]: I think the Sanyan moral point of view, that development at the end of the day is not just

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:21.120
[Guest]: about GDP, right? But it is about enhancing human capabilities, and that health and education

00:21:21.120 --> 00:21:25.480
[Guest]: are a core component of that. You know, I think that's a very simple and important and

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:30.360
[Guest]: deep point, right? And I think if you'll allow me a tangent, see a little bit of the Sanyan

00:21:30.360 --> 00:21:35.520
[Guest]: worldview is, I think, being borne out right now as we speak, okay? So when I teach my

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:39.640
[Guest]: undergraduate class on development economics, one of the things I talk about is, you know,

00:21:39.640 --> 00:21:44.200
[Guest]: you can measure countries' welfare and prosperity by GDP per capita, which is a standard thing,

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:47.840
[Guest]: or you can measure it by the Sanyan Human Development Index, which the UNDP, you know,

00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:51.480
[Guest]: follows. And the basic difference is that the Human Development Index has only a one-third

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:55.080
[Guest]: weight on income, it has a one-third weight on health, one-third weight on education,

00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:59.560
[Guest]: okay? Now, what's interesting is if you rank countries around the world by GDP per capita,

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:04.520
[Guest]: or if you rank them by HDI, the rankings are remarkably similar, okay? So there is very

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:08.680
[Guest]: little difference. And so the only exceptions you get, there'll be some countries like Saudi

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:14.040
[Guest]: Arabia that are much worse off in HDI than income because, you know, simply accidentally

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:17.680
[Guest]: finding oil under you doesn't make you develop if, you know, half your population can't go

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:22.480
[Guest]: to school. Now, and conversely, I think the Sanyan examples of Vietnam and Kerala and

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:26.360
[Guest]: others would be that here are places that outperform, right, like on human development

00:22:26.360 --> 00:22:30.800
[Guest]: compared to income. And I think where I would say there's a slight vindication of the Sanyan

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:35.880
[Guest]: view in our current COVID crisis is that if you look at which are the societies that have

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:41.240
[Guest]: outperformed dramatically relative to GDP per capita, it is the societies that are in

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:45.360
[Guest]: fact higher HDI. It's all relative because obviously better income helps with everything,

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:50.400
[Guest]: right? So anyway, so I think there is a deeper point there that, you know, education and

00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:55.800
[Guest]: health are, you know, somewhat kind of broader enablers of society, right? And one of the

00:22:55.800 --> 00:22:59.080
[Guest]: philosophical tensions in education, which again, I'll come back to in the end, there's

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:02.960
[Guest]: too many, you know, because you see it, but I'm bringing it now because, you know, I know

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:06.320
[Guest]: you're kind of a classical liberal, right? Like, you know, I mean, and, you know, and

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:10.960
[Guest]: I have many of those same instincts. But here is the fundamental tension, right? The fundamental

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:16.480
[Guest]: tension is, I think many of us probably have an ethical worldview that says that, you know,

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:20.960
[Guest]: people should be allowed to keep the majority of what they work for. And so the coercion

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:25.720
[Guest]: of the state in that sense, measured by say taxation, right, should be kept low. Okay.

00:23:25.720 --> 00:23:30.720
[Guest]: But I think a lot of us would also share a worldview that says that the role of the genetic

00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:36.000
[Guest]: lottery in life outcomes should be minimized to the extent possible. So to, you know, to

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.800
[Guest]: kind of come up with an analogy, which again, I use in my undergrad class is to say, you

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:44.760
[Guest]: know, when you look at the field of life as a soccer field, and you say this is an uneven

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:49.320
[Guest]: playing field, the problem with socialism, communism is you say it's uneven, and therefore,

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:53.160
[Guest]: the game should be a draw. But if the game is a draw, there's no incentive to play. And

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:56.320
[Guest]: there's no spectators, there's no economy, there's nothing. And so then, you know, it's

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:00.760
[Guest]: kind of you shrink all activity, right? So what we would like to do is we would like

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:05.120
[Guest]: to level but if the game is so uneven, right, then there's no game, right? I mean, so what

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:08.840
[Guest]: you would like to do is level that playing field as much as possible, and then saying

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:13.760
[Guest]: now go play, right, you know, now go play and let the natural kind of, you know, talents

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:17.640
[Guest]: and effort and everything emerge so that you then get to keep the fruit of your labor,

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:20.920
[Guest]: right? And the reason I'm making this tangent is because it deeply then has to go with what

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:24.040
[Guest]: is the role of the state? What is cohesion? What is this thing? And so, but I think the

00:24:24.040 --> 00:24:29.400
[Guest]: fundamental tension here is that at one level, we say that we want people to be able to keep

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:33.680
[Guest]: the fruit of their labor. At another level, you say that we would like to keep a level

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:38.360
[Guest]: playing field and prevent the intergenerational or not prevent or at least mitigate the amount

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:42.400
[Guest]: of intergenerational transmission inequality. The problem is that the thing that people

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:47.080
[Guest]: seem to want to do the most with their money is propagate their advantage to their children.

00:24:47.080 --> 00:24:51.400
[Guest]: And so if you look at what people do in terms of schooling, etc. So I think the role of

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:56.960
[Guest]: the state in the basic services of health and education, I think is therefore much more,

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:01.360
[Guest]: you know, warranted in terms of providing that kind of level playing field. So then

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:05.160
[Guest]: I think there's the tactical question of how do you achieve this? And I think that's where

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:08.320
[Guest]: there's this slight divergence with Sen, right? Like, you know, where the original Senian

00:25:08.320 --> 00:25:12.480
[Guest]: view is that, listen, the countries that have delivered, that have outperformed the human

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:16.800
[Guest]: development relative to incomes have been like the Keralas, the Vietnams, the Cubas,

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:20.540
[Guest]: that have all had like heavy state involvement, or even China, or even the East Asian miracle

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:25.000
[Guest]: in some ways, like, you know, did, was built on very heavy state investment in education.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:29.320
[Guest]: Okay, so, you know, and I know, and we'll come back and talk about vouchers and markets

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:33.200
[Guest]: and stuff like that. But I think the one very compelling argument that the anti-voucher

00:25:33.200 --> 00:25:37.840
[Guest]: crowd has is to say that, listen, no country has ever managed to achieve universal education

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:42.360
[Guest]: at scale without public provision. And this is true even of East Asia. Okay. Now, that

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:48.960
[Guest]: being said, I think, in many ways, India needs to chart its own path based on our lived reality.

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:52.360
[Guest]: And this is a topic of, you know, in many ways, like I said, I'm working on my first

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:55.920
[Guest]: book, which will be out next year. So there's many, many things that we'll come back to

00:25:55.920 --> 00:26:00.080
[Guest]: later. But to keep the focus on what you said about the means and ends and sense, where

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:04.240
[Guest]: I say there's a little bit of a cognitive disconnect in Sen's own results versus his

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:08.320
[Guest]: views on, say, vouchers, okay, comes from the fact that if you look at one of his most

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:12.640
[Guest]: powerful ideas on famines, that people historically thought that famines were because of collapse

00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:17.440
[Guest]: of food production. Okay. And what he showed was that it's not the collapse of food production

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:23.160
[Guest]: per se, it is the collapse of purchasing power, right? So typically, when you have a famine,

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:27.120
[Guest]: there is food nearby, and you know, you can buy the food. So sitting in Bombay, you don't

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:30.840
[Guest]: starve just because Bombay doesn't grow its food, right? You buy the food from places

00:26:30.840 --> 00:26:35.320
[Guest]: that grow the food, right? And so similarly, like the problem with the famine is not that

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:39.080
[Guest]: the food production collapses, it's because the daily wage labor collapses, because there's

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:43.320
[Guest]: no harvest, there's no work, that incomes collapse. And it's because incomes collapse

00:26:43.320 --> 00:26:48.240
[Guest]: that you have starvation and famines, right? So the entire idea of Enrega, or the idea

00:26:48.240 --> 00:26:53.820
[Guest]: of an employment guarantee scheme as a better means of social protection, rather than publicly

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:58.680
[Guest]: provided inputs, comes in a way from Sen's insight that it's the purchasing power that's

00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:02.280
[Guest]: the problem, as opposed to the lack of supply that the market will take care of supply if

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:07.160
[Guest]: you provide the purchasing power. So if you take that logic to education, then the case

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:11.320
[Guest]: for, you know, voucher-based financing and saying, let kind of the market provide and

00:27:11.320 --> 00:27:15.880
[Guest]: let the state come in by kind of providing the purchasing power, I think is quite compelling.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:19.440
[Guest]: But as I'll, again, we'll get to in more detail, when we talk about private schooling, it's

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:23.920
[Guest]: much more complicated than that. And where the market analogy kind of breaks down in

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:29.400
[Guest]: schooling is what we forget, is that schooling is a club good, where schools define themselves

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:33.560
[Guest]: as much by who they exclude as who they include, right? So schools are not trying to maximize

00:27:33.560 --> 00:27:38.200
[Guest]: market share, right? So if you look at Harvard over the years, right, and I'm a product of

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:41.320
[Guest]: Harvard, Harvard undergrad, Harvard PhD, 10 years there, but I've now spent 11 years as

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:45.120
[Guest]: a faculty member at the University of California. And, you know, and at a moral level, I feel

00:27:45.120 --> 00:27:49.120
[Guest]: so much happier here, right? I mean, and that's because the Harvard objective function, the

00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:54.240
[Guest]: endowment has grown 10 times, but the enrollment has not increased at all in 70 years, right?

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:58.840
[Guest]: It's because it's fundamentally a club. It's like, how do I identify a bunch of smart,

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:02.440
[Guest]: privileged kids and give them even more resources? Whereas the University of California model,

00:28:02.440 --> 00:28:06.520
[Guest]: because it's a public university, is saying that how do I maximize the number of people

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:11.080
[Guest]: educated and how do I maximize the integral of human capital times the people as opposed

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:15.400
[Guest]: to just maximize prestige, right? So it gives you one sense of why the simple market analogy

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:20.760
[Guest]: breaks down. But that being said, there are creative ways of leveraging the kind of the

00:28:20.760 --> 00:28:24.400
[Guest]: dynamism and incentive compatibility of the market in the public interest, which I'll,

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:27.720
[Guest]: you know, which I'll talk more about. But I think the main caveat I'm making is that

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:31.480
[Guest]: it needs to be much more nuanced. I think, you know, and all of us in education go through

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:35.480
[Guest]: this phase, including myself about 12 years ago of kind of, you know, you hear the idea

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:39.300
[Guest]: of school vouchers and it seems magical. And I think there's a lot of potential in that.

00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:43.080
[Guest]: But I think it's a much more complex subject than other market analogies, which we'll come

00:28:43.080 --> 00:28:47.520
[Amit Varma]: to later. I am not, by the way, a votary of either school vouchers, and I'm not against

00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:53.320
[Amit Varma]: public schooling either. Let me kind of clarify a couple of points. Number one, when I mentioned

00:28:53.320 --> 00:28:58.300
[Amit Varma]: coercion, one aspect of coercion, of course, is that whatever the government does is funded

00:28:58.300 --> 00:29:01.960
[Amit Varma]: by violence because it is taking money from people. But the other aspect, the important

00:29:01.960 --> 00:29:08.120
[Amit Varma]: aspect is that it interferes in people solving their own problems. What are markets? Markets

00:29:08.120 --> 00:29:12.480
[Amit Varma]: are the mechanism through which society solves its own problems. You need something, I give

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:16.760
[Amit Varma]: it to you. It's a positive sum game, both of us benefit. That's how we all grow. You

00:29:16.760 --> 00:29:21.280
[Amit Varma]: know, and that's the kind of coercion that I actually object to far more that when people

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:25.960
[Amit Varma]: can help solve each other's problems, the state gets in the way. And we've seen that

00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:30.880
[Amit Varma]: especially, you know, in the context of education, where, for example, it's good to have a goal

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:35.160
[Amit Varma]: that these are our goals, everyone should have this level of education, ever, you know,

00:29:35.160 --> 00:29:39.080
[Amit Varma]: we should have a level playing field, we should do something about the genetic lottery. I

00:29:39.080 --> 00:29:44.320
[Amit Varma]: agree with every little bit of that. I have no caveats with that goal. My issue is, what

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:48.760
[Amit Varma]: are the processes through which we achieve that goal? Not just what is the ends, but

00:29:48.760 --> 00:29:53.520
[Amit Varma]: what are the means? And what are the means not in a moral sense of all coercion is morally

00:29:53.520 --> 00:30:00.960
[Amit Varma]: bad, but also the means in an instrumental sense of what will help take us towards that

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:05.920
[Amit Varma]: goal the best. And, you know, one of the most fundamental things that seems to have gone

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:11.040
[Amit Varma]: wrong here is that I think India has, and I'll ask you to elaborate on this at length

00:30:11.040 --> 00:30:15.880
[Amit Varma]: after this, but I think India has adopted with good intentions, the sort of wrong means

00:30:15.880 --> 00:30:20.480
[Amit Varma]: where we, you know, prevent society from solving its own problems. For example, I'll quote

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:24.760
[Amit Varma]: from something that you have written, where you wrote, quote, it is worth recollecting

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:29.560
[Amit Varma]: that shortages, waiting lists and site payments were common in many sectors, including telephones,

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:34.120
[Amit Varma]: computers and cars in the mid 1980s. The most important lesson for India from the successful

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:39.160
[Amit Varma]: economic liberalization in the early 1990s, is that the key to expanding access, increasing

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:44.960
[Amit Varma]: quality and reducing costs in sectors ranging from electronics to transport was a reduction

00:30:44.960 --> 00:30:50.840
[Amit Varma]: of barriers to the entry of private providers, and the resulting increases in choices for

00:30:50.840 --> 00:30:54.920
[Amit Varma]: consumers and the competition among producers. It is perhaps no accident that the greatest

00:30:54.920 --> 00:30:59.640
[Amit Varma]: challenges for the Indian economy are in sectors like agriculture and education that have not

00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:03.320
[Amit Varma]: seen similar reforms, stop quote. And when I read these words, which I read today, when

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:07.600
[Amit Varma]: I read that paper that you sent me, I was like, come to my arms, because for years,

00:31:07.600 --> 00:31:10.920
[Amit Varma]: and I'm like a year older than you. And for years, I've been telling people about how

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:15.560
[Amit Varma]: when I grew up in the 1980s, you had to wait five years to get a telephone unless you were

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:19.440
[Amit Varma]: a privileged kid like me, but you had to otherwise wait five years to get a telephone, airline

00:31:19.440 --> 00:31:24.400
[Amit Varma]: tickets were so expensive, blah, blah, blah, you open those out, you allowed society to

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:29.560
[Amit Varma]: solve its own problems, you allowed markets, you took away that element of coercion, and

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:34.680
[Amit Varma]: boom, magic, you know, today, no one considers those areas a problem. And the government

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:40.000
[Amit Varma]: provision is not an issue. But what has happened with education is that we didn't allow the

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.480
[Amit Varma]: private sector a full reign, a lot of it coming from that early mindset, which, you know,

00:31:44.480 --> 00:31:49.680
[Amit Varma]: we can get into about how for profit schools are still not allowed. And, you know, because

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:54.400
[Amit Varma]: of that, these areas which are so important, which you you could argue, like education

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:59.440
[Amit Varma]: and agriculture, as you pointed out, are so crucial to the well being of our people forget

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:04.200
[Amit Varma]: our development as a nation, which is a broad concept. But just to the material and physical

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:08.840
[Amit Varma]: well being of our nation have been kind of ignored because of this mindset. So I would

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:13.120
[Amit Varma]: actually say that, you know, choosing the wrong means can take you further away from

00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:17.320
[Amit Varma]: your ends, even though it seems intuitive that, hey, we have a problem, let bring the

00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:20.000
[Amit Varma]: state in and the state will kind of solve it.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:24.520
[Guest]: No, I couldn't agree more. And again, you know, I'm starting to, these are different

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:27.760
[Guest]: themes, which I'm talking about in this book, which I mentioned, right. But I think one

00:32:27.760 --> 00:32:32.960
[Guest]: simple source of confusion, I think, by the way, I agree completely. And since you quoted

00:32:32.960 --> 00:32:37.640
[Guest]: me back to myself, I can't disagree, right? Like, I mean, but, but no, I think the key

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:42.200
[Guest]: to solving most of India's problems really is expanding supply, right? You know, that

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:46.080
[Guest]: we are a short, so where we are a shortage based economy, because of regulation is where

00:32:46.080 --> 00:32:50.600
[Guest]: we have a bulk of problems, right? So I think so there, we are completely in agreement.

00:32:50.600 --> 00:32:54.200
[Guest]: I think what makes this whole issue so complicated is the government plays three very different

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:59.080
[Guest]: roles in the ecosystem, right? The government is a policymaker, the government is a regulator,

00:32:59.080 --> 00:33:03.120
[Guest]: the government is also a provider, right? Now, the problem, most of the schizophrenia

00:33:03.120 --> 00:33:06.720
[Guest]: with regard to how the government approaches the private sector comes from the fact that

00:33:06.720 --> 00:33:11.080
[Guest]: the role of the private sector is actually dramatically different in these three functions

00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:15.560
[Guest]: of the government, right? So for the government as a policymaker, the private sector is an

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:20.760
[Guest]: ally, right? Because as a policymaker, you care about how do I get the best outcomes,

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:25.000
[Guest]: right, for the society, right? Because as a policymaker, your role is to maximize aggregate

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:29.480
[Guest]: kind of welfare, right? Now, as a reg, so if the private sector can deliver it better,

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:33.080
[Guest]: then on the margin, you want the private sector to do it, right? So as a policymaker, you're

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:37.560
[Guest]: kind of the private sector as an ally, because it gives you more supply, it gives you more

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:42.760
[Guest]: diversity of options, it gives you, you know, just more options to play with, right? Now,

00:33:42.760 --> 00:33:47.040
[Guest]: as a regulator, the private sector is an equal, right? You need to treat the public and private

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:50.920
[Guest]: equally and not privilege one versus the other, so that it's a level playing field. And again,

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:54.960
[Guest]: here, you know, we don't quite do it. But then as a provider, the private sector is

00:33:54.960 --> 00:33:58.520
[Guest]: your competitor, okay, because then you're competing for the same market share, right?

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:02.440
[Guest]: So I think part of the problem here is that if you look at the structure of a government

00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:07.840
[Guest]: education department, the majority of kind of the budget, as well as the personnel are

00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:14.000
[Guest]: dedicated to government as providers, right? And so therefore, government as provider automatically

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:19.840
[Guest]: is the lens through which we look at the policymaking, the regulatory function as well. And in that,

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:23.760
[Guest]: as a result, we end up doing untold damage, right? Like, you know, by restricting private

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:27.240
[Guest]: entry, because government as provider doesn't want the competition, though government as

00:34:27.240 --> 00:34:31.200
[Guest]: policymaker, right, you know, should absolutely want that. And it's the same issue in aviation,

00:34:31.200 --> 00:34:35.560
[Guest]: right? So I think, you know, again, speaking of Singapore, I just talk about as examples

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:40.120
[Guest]: in my Indian economy class about the distortions that come from, you know, government as provider

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:43.640
[Guest]: getting in the way of what's in the public interest of government is regulated, right?

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:47.800
[Guest]: And I think Air India is an even more direct example of that, right? Where, you know, a

00:34:47.800 --> 00:34:51.520
[Guest]: country as small as Singapore gets more tourists in a year than all of India, right? I mean,

00:34:51.520 --> 00:34:55.640
[Guest]: this is a manmade island, like, you know, that has to create these theme parks for tourism.

00:34:55.640 --> 00:34:59.440
[Guest]: And here we are this kind of, you know, millennia old civilization that doesn't get the same

00:34:59.440 --> 00:35:03.600
[Guest]: number of tourists. And like the big, one big reason for that is Singapore's open skies

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:07.480
[Guest]: policy. So anybody can fly in, anybody can fly out, pick up passengers, drop passengers

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:12.480
[Guest]: and people come there. And whereas here for decades, our aviation policy is essentially

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:16.960
[Guest]: being still focused on bilaterals and kind of reciprocity for Air India. And so trying

00:35:16.960 --> 00:35:21.920
[Guest]: to therefore protect Air India, like it has over the years dramatically cut short, you

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:26.520
[Guest]: know, India's global integration in terms of transport. So anyway, so I think that part

00:35:26.520 --> 00:35:31.120
[Guest]: of the confusion here comes, as I couldn't agree more, the government is this incredibly

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:35.280
[Guest]: heavy handed beast. And, you know, we can come back to what the policy framework should

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:40.120
[Guest]: be. And I think the challenge again, you know, is when the issue is so complex, that maybe

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:44.080
[Guest]: what we should do is we should first kind of segment and discuss on the evidence and

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:48.320
[Guest]: what we know, because understanding itself is difficult enough. And then kind of say

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:53.800
[Guest]: now based on what we understand, how would we craft a set of policy responses that are

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:58.560
[Guest]: both consistent with the evidence, consistent with the principles, but also that there is

00:35:58.560 --> 00:36:02.600
[Guest]: a political way to make this happen, right? And then we'll come back to the various political

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:05.840
[Guest]: constraints, right? Like, you know, between rent seeking, and sometimes it's not just

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:10.120
[Guest]: rent seeking, it's just good, it's just bad ideas, right? I mean, that take over, and

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:13.680
[Guest]: that are very, very hard to get rid of. So, but hopefully, you know, that clarifies a

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:18.240
[Guest]: bit in terms of the private sector. But yeah, I haven't given you answers yet. I've just

00:36:18.240 --> 00:36:20.360
[Guest]: tried to, you know, clarify what the issues are.

00:36:20.360 --> 00:36:26.200
[Amit Varma]: No, I think you're showing academic humility there rather than the certainty of a policy

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:27.200
[Amit Varma]: scholar to use Dr. Aluwalia's binary.

00:36:27.200 --> 00:36:32.720
[Guest]: To be fair, it's not even the policy scholar, right? Like, you know, it's the consultants

00:36:32.720 --> 00:36:36.200
[Guest]: with flashy PowerPoints that I'm most scared about, right? So one thing I say is, you know,

00:36:36.200 --> 00:36:44.760
[Guest]: consultants have confidence, academics have confidence intervals, right? You know, so

00:36:44.760 --> 00:36:48.240
[Amit Varma]: That's so beautifully put. No, I know what I will also want to therefore clarify to the

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:53.320
[Amit Varma]: listeners, I think the last part that I didn't get over is that for all my sense that the

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:57.920
[Amit Varma]: government should not in any way, stop society from solving its own problems for something

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:02.120
[Amit Varma]: like education. I'm not against public schools or public education at all. I'm saying let

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:06.160
[Amit Varma]: a thousand flowers flourish, whatever works works, we'll find out what works, and which

00:37:06.160 --> 00:37:12.600
[Amit Varma]: is a different matter. So let's kind of actually turn to the subject at hand after these delightful

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:18.880
[Amit Varma]: digressions and talk about education itself. Give me a sort of a broad overview, not just

00:37:18.880 --> 00:37:24.320
[Amit Varma]: in terms of where things stand today, or where things stood before the NEP. But just over

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:29.320
[Amit Varma]: the decades, what has been wrong with public schooling per se, number one, which you've,

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:33.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, seen and examined and written about at a very granular level. And before that,

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:38.360
[Amit Varma]: what do you think other mindset issues which were the problem like one mindset issue, which

00:37:38.360 --> 00:37:42.800
[Amit Varma]: I think you would agree with, but that's like a separate issue is, of course, for profit

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:47.560
[Amit Varma]: issue that, you know, Nehru once famously said to JRD Tata, quote, do not talk to me

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:52.600
[Amit Varma]: of profit, it is a dirty word, stop quote, you know, little realizing that, like to me,

00:37:52.600 --> 00:37:55.960
[Amit Varma]: profit is a driver of benevolence, because the only way you can make a profit is by providing

00:37:55.960 --> 00:38:01.600
[Amit Varma]: value to someone else's life. But leaving that mindset part aside, just at that broader

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:07.440
[Amit Varma]: sort of conceptual level, where do you think we went wrong? When after independence, where

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:10.720
[Amit Varma]: we put our whole education system and our public schooling in place?

00:38:10.720 --> 00:38:14.320
[Guest]: Sorry, I mean, you know, I guess this is the challenge. So even before I get there, I want

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:17.480
[Guest]: to follow up on what you said about profit being a dirty word, right? See, and I think,

00:38:17.480 --> 00:38:22.400
[Guest]: so again, it's useful to kind of connect the models in the markets for a second, right.

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:29.040
[Guest]: So and I think, and I share your I share your deep kind of belief that the libertarian reason

00:38:29.040 --> 00:38:33.360
[Guest]: for why you believe in markets so much, the moral case for markets, right, is that no

00:38:33.360 --> 00:38:37.520
[Guest]: transaction can take place unless both sides want it, right. So, you know, if there's no

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:41.200
[Guest]: pressure on you to buy, right, there's no pressure on me to sell. So I will only sell

00:38:41.200 --> 00:38:44.920
[Guest]: if I make a profit, you will only buy if your consumer surplus is positive, right. So and

00:38:44.920 --> 00:38:49.040
[Guest]: that's an incredibly valuable disciplining device for resource allocation across the

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:53.400
[Guest]: economy, right. Now, the only problem with that, and why that problem becomes especially

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: first order in India, is that, see, I think the economic approach to policy analysis as

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:02.920
[Guest]: per a to improvement, right, which is our both sides better off, right, I think is a

00:39:02.920 --> 00:39:08.840
[Guest]: very powerful framing, but it completely ignores the justice or lack thereof of the original

00:39:08.840 --> 00:39:14.600
[Guest]: position, right. So it takes the initial position as given, and doesn't question, right, like,

00:39:14.600 --> 00:39:19.800
[Guest]: what is the moral basis of that initial? So, in a world where you have the level of abject

00:39:19.800 --> 00:39:24.600
[Guest]: poverty that you have, right, the market solution for the most part, essentially is to leave

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:30.080
[Guest]: those people out completely, right. So one way to say this is that democracy is one person,

00:39:30.080 --> 00:39:34.560
[Guest]: one vote, right, whereas the market is one rupee, one vote, one dollar, one vote, right.

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:39.520
[Guest]: So how much purchasing power you have in the market, so market is an amazing thing, except

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:43.000
[Guest]: that it doesn't care for you if you don't have purchasing power, right. So to take example,

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:46.360
[Guest]: say, pharmaceutical research, right, like, you know, we spend more money kind of on anti

00:39:46.360 --> 00:39:49.760
[Guest]: wrinkle cream research in the US, like, you know, then you would on tropical diseases

00:39:49.760 --> 00:39:53.800
[Guest]: put together, not because it doesn't affect more people, but because there's no money

00:39:53.800 --> 00:39:58.680
[Guest]: to be made, right. So in that sense, the so the power of the market is the incentive compatibility

00:39:58.680 --> 00:40:04.720
[Guest]: of the transaction, the blind spot is the fact that, you know, effectively, it's $1,

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:09.080
[Guest]: one vote. And so, you know, I think a lot of, you know, what I would call left libertarian,

00:40:09.080 --> 00:40:12.720
[Guest]: right, which is broadly how I think of myself, which is to say, I believe in individual liberty,

00:40:12.720 --> 00:40:17.160
[Guest]: I believe in kind of, you know, minimizing the heavy handedness of the state. But I also

00:40:17.160 --> 00:40:22.520
[Guest]: believe in to the extent possible, reducing the effects of the genetic lottery, so to

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:26.720
[Guest]: speak, right, by providing more purchasing power and dignity to the poor that then gives

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:30.480
[Guest]: them a chance to compete in this market, right. So I think, but the point I'm making is that,

00:40:30.480 --> 00:40:34.040
[Guest]: so and this is again, it's a theme I discussed in my interview with Arvind Subramanian five

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:37.040
[Guest]: years ago, and something that will form a big part of my book is that, see, what makes

00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:42.340
[Guest]: India an outlier in human history, right, is that we are the only kind of country that

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:46.480
[Guest]: had universal adult franchise and democracy is such a low level of per capita income,

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:51.200
[Guest]: right. And so what democracy before development has meant for India is that if you look at

00:40:51.200 --> 00:40:55.560
[Guest]: income distributions, in general, income distributions are right skewed, right, which means the median

00:40:55.560 --> 00:41:00.240
[Guest]: income is typically below the mean. So in kind of a simple democracy, the median voter

00:41:00.240 --> 00:41:05.320
[Guest]: is always going to want more redistribution, right. So most of today's rich countries built

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:09.480
[Guest]: their welfare states after becoming rich, right. But India, so the core question in

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:14.560
[Guest]: public finance is how do you allocate taxpayer money between public goods that create productivity

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:19.120
[Guest]: versus redistribution, and democracy before development in India has basically meant that

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:23.960
[Guest]: that scale has always skewed much more towards redistribution rather than public goods, right.

00:41:23.960 --> 00:41:29.080
[Guest]: Now, so all of that, I think still, it's a preface to say that given our kind of unique

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:34.600
[Guest]: history as a country, right, it is impossible to get away from the massive, by when I say

00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:38.920
[Guest]: political demand, I mean, popular demand, right, I mean, of kind of public involvement,

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:42.240
[Guest]: right, which is what kind of shapes my thinking as to say that the public involvement is kind

00:41:42.240 --> 00:41:47.280
[Guest]: of a given. So then how do you optimally allocate or optimally direct that urge for public?

00:41:47.280 --> 00:41:51.160
[Guest]: Now, the other place where I massively agree with you in terms of letting people solve

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:56.920
[Guest]: their own problems is that one way to, I think, let democracy deliver better services is to

00:41:56.920 --> 00:42:01.840
[Guest]: decentralize a lot, lot more, right, because I think where democracy is kind of failed,

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:06.320
[Guest]: India is not in the idea of democracy, but in that the level of aggregation is so high,

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:09.880
[Guest]: that you're expressing your preferences over so many dimensions of what you care about

00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:14.760
[Guest]: as a citizen in one vote, that decentralizing is a way to kind of unbundle the vote, and

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:19.360
[Guest]: then allow your local vote to focus much more on issues of service delivery, and build,

00:42:19.360 --> 00:42:22.360
[Guest]: you know, democratic accountability. So sorry, you know, but I think this is the time, you

00:42:22.360 --> 00:42:25.520
[Guest]: know, you raise things, and then I have to get to those tagets, answer that, but that's

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:28.280
[Amit Varma]: fun. And then, you know,

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:32.880
[Amit Varma]: these are very much the kind of conversations I enjoy. And when you spoke about decentralization,

00:42:32.880 --> 00:42:38.240
[Amit Varma]: that was another moment of come to my arms, Karthik, you know, sort of get back to the

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:42.680
[Amit Varma]: earlier sort of points that you raise where I kind of agree with everything you said,

00:42:42.680 --> 00:42:47.160
[Amit Varma]: but let me tell you, sort of the margins at which I would add my little two pence, I think,

00:42:47.160 --> 00:42:50.480
[Amit Varma]: when Nehru said what he said about profit being a dirty word, I think he meant it in

00:42:50.480 --> 00:42:56.600
[Amit Varma]: the sense of not in the nuanced sense that you're speaking of it, but more in, because

00:42:56.600 --> 00:43:00.880
[Amit Varma]: he had a zero sum vision of the world, that he assumed that if someone is making a profit,

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:04.080
[Amit Varma]: someone is getting exploited. And that's, of course, fundamentally not true. That's

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:08.600
[Amit Varma]: one of the way the world works. And yet, that is a mindset, which a lot of Indians have

00:43:08.600 --> 00:43:14.120
[Amit Varma]: even today, which is why a lot of populism will focus on redistribution and in the popular

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:18.080
[Amit Varma]: narrative, you know, which is rational, and there's a reason why that is so, but that

00:43:18.080 --> 00:43:22.680
[Amit Varma]: isn't necessarily correct. The other thing that I'd like to sort of go into is, and again,

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:25.640
[Amit Varma]: that's another point that I keep making that, you know, a lot of the countries which became

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:30.920
[Amit Varma]: welfare states did so after, you know, they became prosperous, and there is something

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:35.480
[Amit Varma]: to be noted there. And if you attempt to become a welfare state before you become prosperous,

00:43:35.480 --> 00:43:39.040
[Amit Varma]: what happens, and I had, you know, written a piece while back, which I'll link from the

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:41.900
[Amit Varma]: show notes. In fact, I'll link a lot of your stuff from the show notes. So my listeners

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:47.120
[Amit Varma]: should kindly check that out for, you know, videos of Karthik's talk with Arvind as he

00:43:47.120 --> 00:43:51.900
[Amit Varma]: mentioned and various other links. But anyway, so this piece I wrote a few months ago was

00:43:51.900 --> 00:43:56.920
[Amit Varma]: about how Indians should be obsessed about poverty, getting rid of poverty, and not with

00:43:56.920 --> 00:44:01.080
[Amit Varma]: inequality. And to me, the two are very different things, and people don't get it. And they

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:04.240
[Amit Varma]: appear the same when you look at the world in a zero sum way that if someone is getting

00:44:04.240 --> 00:44:08.400
[Amit Varma]: richer, someone else must be getting poorer. So if inequality increases, that means poverty

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:12.600
[Amit Varma]: is increasing, but actually, that's not the case at all. And actually, as we've seen since

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:18.120
[Amit Varma]: India's liberalization, or even since the 80s, that as poverty has reduced, inequality

00:44:18.120 --> 00:44:22.840
[Amit Varma]: has gone up, they often in a developing country like India, I think they often go in opposite

00:44:22.840 --> 00:44:26.360
[Amit Varma]: directions, because everybody's getting better off at the same time, but the rich are getting

00:44:26.360 --> 00:44:29.860
[Amit Varma]: better off faster, because they're able to achieve scale and put their money to use and

00:44:29.860 --> 00:44:34.200
[Amit Varma]: all of that. But what I would focus on instead is what the philosopher Harry Frankfurt calls

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:39.400
[Amit Varma]: the doctrine of sufficiency, which is Frankfurt's view is that when we look at humanity, what

00:44:39.400 --> 00:44:43.720
[Amit Varma]: we should focus on is not the differences between the rich and the poor, but how poor

00:44:43.720 --> 00:44:48.600
[Amit Varma]: the poor are in absolute terms, and how he defines a doctrine of sufficiency. And obviously,

00:44:48.600 --> 00:44:52.980
[Amit Varma]: I'm saying this from memory, so I won't get the exact words, but how he essentially defines

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:59.320
[Amit Varma]: it is that you figure out a measure of what a person needs to live with basic human dignity.

00:44:59.320 --> 00:45:04.720
[Amit Varma]: And you define that as sufficiency and that is what you aim for. And for Indians, especially,

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:10.360
[Amit Varma]: I think many of us English speaking elites have, you know, picked up this fashion from

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:13.880
[Amit Varma]: abroad that we can talk about inequality and all of that, but I don't think is relevant

00:45:13.880 --> 00:45:18.160
[Amit Varma]: to us because you can solve inequality with redistribution, you can make everybody equally

00:45:18.160 --> 00:45:23.880
[Amit Varma]: poor. But if you want to solve poverty, then you have to acknowledge the positive someness

00:45:23.880 --> 00:45:28.360
[Amit Varma]: of human interactions and the centrality of profit to that and work with that in mind.

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:32.800
[Amit Varma]: So where I, you know, agree with what you said about the original position, that, you

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:36.760
[Amit Varma]: know, it is not enough to say that if I interact, say with someone who is much less privileged

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:41.000
[Amit Varma]: than me, that doesn't solve the problem of privilege, right? It doesn't solve the problem

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:47.680
[Amit Varma]: that he's relatively poor, and I am much better off. But I am saying that I'm wondering if

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:51.360
[Amit Varma]: that's a problem to solve. The problem to solve is that he is not well off in absolute

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:57.960
[Amit Varma]: terms. And by transacting with me, he gets a little better off with that transaction.

00:45:57.960 --> 00:46:02.400
[Amit Varma]: And what we then think about as a benevolence of the state in practice never really works

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:03.640
[Guest]: out that way, as we have seen.

00:46:03.640 --> 00:46:06.880
[Guest]: Correct. So I think, you know, so let me, you know, let me agree with that, but then

00:46:06.880 --> 00:46:10.400
[Guest]: add two additional important points of nuance, right? So I think, you know, so where I agree

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:16.080
[Guest]: with that completely is that, you know, and this is in fact consistent even with the view

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:21.720
[Guest]: of Rawls, right? And Rawls is generally considered, you know, much more of a social democrat philosopher

00:46:21.720 --> 00:46:26.560
[Guest]: by focusing on the welfare of the poorest. And even though Rawls would say that inequality

00:46:26.560 --> 00:46:30.920
[Guest]: is good to the extent that it actually makes the worst off better off, right? So if it's

00:46:30.920 --> 00:46:35.640
[Guest]: the inequality that gets the innovation and gets kind of the, you know, the new enterprises

00:46:35.640 --> 00:46:39.360
[Guest]: that are delivering outcomes at scale that help the poorest, absolutely. I think, you

00:46:39.360 --> 00:46:42.560
[Guest]: know, that's wonderful. And I couldn't agree more with you that for a country like India,

00:46:42.560 --> 00:46:46.280
[Guest]: you should focus much more on absolute poverty rather than inequality. I think the two caveats

00:46:46.280 --> 00:46:47.280
[Guest]: are the following.

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:52.640
[Guest]: The first is that where the inequality like intrinsically matters is the consequences

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:57.480
[Guest]: of the corrosion of the democratic process, right? I mean, and that's because essentially,

00:46:57.480 --> 00:47:01.720
[Guest]: you know, what is the state? The state is also kind of allocating policies and largesse,

00:47:01.720 --> 00:47:06.120
[Guest]: right? So if inequality gets to the point where essentially elites capture the government,

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:10.560
[Guest]: right, then you kind of get, and there's tons of work just showing how you kind of decay

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:14.280
[Guest]: institutions decay. And Raghuram Rajan has this wonderful, his first famous book, right,

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:18.120
[Guest]: was Saving Capitalism from the Capitalists, right? So, and this is true even in economics,

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:21.640
[Guest]: right? What we idealize about the market, this is something I learned very early, right?

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:26.000
[Guest]: Which is what as economists we idealize about the market is the ideal of free competition

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:29.720
[Guest]: that, you know, the competition is what forces people to be accountable. But then when I

00:47:29.720 --> 00:47:32.960
[Guest]: went, became a consultant, the first thing you're trying to do as a consultant is minimize

00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:37.440
[Guest]: your competition, right? So is how do you define and how do you get either legislative

00:47:37.440 --> 00:47:40.680
[Guest]: barriers to entry, patent barriers to entry, different kinds of barriers to entry. So,

00:47:40.680 --> 00:47:44.600
[Guest]: you know, and we just see again and again and again, that that inequality can capture

00:47:44.600 --> 00:47:47.840
[Guest]: the political process, right? So that's, I think, one important caveat.

00:47:47.840 --> 00:47:51.320
[Guest]: The second caveat, which is, I think, more subtle, going back to what Nehru said, is

00:47:51.320 --> 00:47:56.480
[Guest]: that, see, it is absolutely true in a place like India, that if you look at a feudal history,

00:47:56.480 --> 00:48:00.720
[Guest]: right, that the feudal history is built on exploitation in the sense that, and this is

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:03.800
[Guest]: something that modern economics hasn't dealt with enough, but we're now starting to see

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:09.060
[Guest]: a bunch of very careful micro-founded work, right? You know, that how much of the attention

00:48:09.060 --> 00:48:13.760
[Guest]: of the capitalist class was spent in reducing the outside options, right? So going back

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:18.880
[Guest]: to is reducing the outside options of workers. And so what appears like free market, yes,

00:48:18.880 --> 00:48:23.760
[Guest]: it is free market, but I am essentially constricting your outside options so much that you have

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:27.760
[Guest]: no option but to accept this very low wage, right? And I think the best example of this

00:48:27.760 --> 00:48:32.720
[Guest]: is really seen in my own changing thinking on Enriga, right? So, you know, when Enriga

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:37.080
[Guest]: was first announced, I was a skeptic, right? I was a skeptic, and I'm on the record, as

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:40.720
[Guest]: with many neoclassical economists, saying that, listen, this is going to boost wages

00:48:40.720 --> 00:48:45.360
[Guest]: without boosting productivity, and this is just a bad, overall bad idea, right? And in

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:49.400
[Guest]: fact, the rhetoric around it was bad and continues to be bad now in the context of the migrant

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:53.240
[Guest]: crisis when people say, oh, we want to prevent migration, which is, again, getting it completely

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:57.160
[Guest]: upside down because it's urbanization that's kind of the engine of development. But to

00:48:57.160 --> 00:49:00.840
[Guest]: leaving that aside, right, when we did this massive large-scale randomized controlled

00:49:00.840 --> 00:49:05.880
[Guest]: trial in Andhra Pradesh on the effect of improving Enriga implementation, right? The results just

00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest]: blew our mind, right? And what we found was that not only did it improve wages, it actually

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:15.760
[Guest]: improved employment and incomes across the board. And because what was happening was

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:20.240
[Guest]: we also find very robust evidence of monopsony, right, of essentially, you know, when you

00:49:20.240 --> 00:49:25.480
[Guest]: have a few large landowners who can kind of ration employment and suppress the wage, that

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:28.800
[Guest]: improving the outside option and improving the bargaining power of the workers, which

00:49:28.800 --> 00:49:33.440
[Guest]: is what Enriga does, right, is not only kind of improving their welfare, but improving

00:49:33.440 --> 00:49:38.400
[Guest]: – it's not only equity, but also efficiency, right? So, I think my goal right now is like

00:49:38.400 --> 00:49:43.080
[Guest]: to focus on the holy grail of policies that improve both equity and efficiency. And there

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:48.000
[Guest]: are, in fact, a class of anti-poverty programs that, you know, that while we might call it

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:52.480
[Guest]: as just, this is another welfare program, if they're well-designed, can in fact be

00:49:52.480 --> 00:49:56.280
[Guest]: efficiency-enhancing as well, okay? So, you know, we are already like, you know, an hour

00:49:56.280 --> 00:49:59.640
[Guest]: where – and we can see that we can talk about so many things that – but these threads

00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: are all connected, right? The threads are all connected because how we approach anti-poverty

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:07.640
[Guest]: affects how we approach education, affects how we approach health. And this is this fundamental

00:50:07.640 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: tension between the state and the market, right, which is, you know, the democratic

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:15.640
[Guest]: ideal is one person, one vote. The way the market allocates resources is one dollar,

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:21.080
[Guest]: one vote, okay? Now, to the extent that that dollar that the person commands in the market

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:25.680
[Guest]: reflects essentially effort and returns to that effort that is expanding the common good,

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:30.120
[Guest]: we don't grudge that, right? But to the extent that that reflects accidents of birth, I mean,

00:50:30.120 --> 00:50:33.600
[Guest]: that is something that we do want to come in on. So, anyway, I think, you know, philosophical

00:50:33.600 --> 00:50:37.200
[Guest]: things aside, in the end, I think this is why, you know, there's a reason why the original

00:50:37.200 --> 00:50:41.600
[Guest]: public policy degree in the world, going back to Oxford, was PPE at Oxford, right? It was

00:50:41.600 --> 00:50:44.600
[Guest]: philosophy, politics, and economics because, you know, it's the philosophy that taught

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:48.320
[Guest]: you what kind of society you wanted. It's the politics, like, you know, that said, how

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:52.560
[Guest]: do you kind of come up with a positive sum game, right? Like, you know, given the competing

00:50:52.560 --> 00:50:56.920
[Guest]: interest in society. And then it's the economics that says, boss, you always have less resources

00:50:56.920 --> 00:51:00.560
[Guest]: than what you have demands for. And so, how do we optimize the limited resource envelope

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:04.760
[Guest]: we have? And, you know, I think where I've spent more of my time on is on the last one,

00:51:04.760 --> 00:51:08.480
[Guest]: right? Because you can argue the first two, kind of, till the cows come home. But the

00:51:08.480 --> 00:51:13.520
[Guest]: point where I want to focus more attention on is, given any set of ethical objectives,

00:51:13.520 --> 00:51:18.320
[Guest]: given any set of policy objectives, there is so much inefficiency in how we do it, okay?

00:51:18.320 --> 00:51:22.040
[Guest]: That if we can try to squeeze out some of that inefficiency out of the system, right,

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:25.520
[Guest]: you know, you will actually deliver substantial improvements over the status quo, right? Which

00:51:25.520 --> 00:51:29.240
[Guest]: is kind of where I focus more of my time. And so maybe that's a good segue to then start

00:51:29.240 --> 00:51:33.240
[Guest]: talking about, you know, education itself and, you know, where we are in terms of our

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:36.960
[Guest]: journey as a country and the evidence of the cost effectiveness of how we are spending

00:51:36.960 --> 00:51:38.560
[Amit Varma]: our scarce public money on education.

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:43.200
[Amit Varma]: That's so insightful. And I'm glad you mentioned the PPE because it is one of my failures that

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:49.840
[Amit Varma]: I cannot talk about E without talking about PNP. And yeah, before we go in for a commercial

00:51:49.840 --> 00:51:53.080
[Amit Varma]: break and after that, we promise our listeners, we'll talk about education. But before we

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:57.720
[Amit Varma]: go in for that, a couple of asides where, you know, I won't disagree with anything Karthik

00:51:57.720 --> 00:52:02.080
[Amit Varma]: said, but a couple of asides where having spoken about E, in fact, two E's, education

00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:07.000
[Amit Varma]: and economics, I'll also, you know, drop some philosopher names, which is give some perspective

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:11.480
[Amit Varma]: on what did Karthik mean when he spoke about Rawls. So John Rawls in the early 70s, wrote

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:15.920
[Amit Varma]: this very influential book called the theory of justice. And the principal idea behind

00:52:15.920 --> 00:52:21.360
[Amit Varma]: the theory of justice is what he calls a veil of ignorance. So imagine that all of us are

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:24.640
[Amit Varma]: behind this veil of ignorance where, you know, before we are born, where we don't know what

00:52:24.640 --> 00:52:29.480
[Amit Varma]: our, you know, a position in the world will be, what would we want society to be like,

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:35.400
[Amit Varma]: and people often use this thought experiment to, you know, imagine a sort of a socialistic

00:52:35.400 --> 00:52:39.360
[Amit Varma]: world. But a lot of libertarians actually like Rawls and see this as a justification

00:52:39.360 --> 00:52:43.360
[Amit Varma]: for libertarian thinking. Because the way I would come at it from my classical liberal

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:48.720
[Amit Varma]: position is that if I knew the ways the world worked, if I understood the rules of economics,

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:53.000
[Amit Varma]: the power of incentives of scarcity, what human nature is like, then from behind the

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:58.060
[Amit Varma]: veil of ignorance, I would want a world with minimal coercion, where individual autonomy

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:02.280
[Amit Varma]: is respected, not in the sense that there is no state and no coercion at all. So I'm

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:07.040
[Amit Varma]: not one of those. But and what I often recommend that, you know, there are two books people

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:11.760
[Amit Varma]: should read together. One is Rawls theory of justice, which is a masterpiece and also

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:16.880
[Amit Varma]: anarchy state in utopia by Robert Nozick, which was in a sense a response to Rawls,

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:20.720
[Amit Varma]: and talks about why we don't need the state at all, which is just at an intellectual level,

00:53:20.720 --> 00:53:26.040
[Amit Varma]: whether you agree or not, I think just reading it is a fascinating experience. And you should

00:53:26.040 --> 00:53:30.600
[Amit Varma]: definitely do it. The other sort of point I wanted to get at is that, you know, I also

00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:35.240
[Amit Varma]: do this weekly economics podcast with my friend Vivek called called econ central. And we recorded

00:53:35.240 --> 00:53:39.200
[Amit Varma]: an episode of that yesterday, we are recording this episode on Wednesday, August 5, that

00:53:39.200 --> 00:53:43.080
