00:57:27.800 --> 00:57:31.520
[Amit Varma]: not just at a granular level, and you've, of course, examined various different aspects

00:57:31.520 --> 00:57:36.360
[Amit Varma]: of it. But even to begin with, perhaps at a broader level of the mindset towards it.

00:57:36.360 --> 00:57:40.760
[Guest]: Yeah, so this is this is great and look forward to just getting diving into the into the core

00:57:40.760 --> 00:57:45.400
[Guest]: topic of the day. So if you look at education policy for 70 years after independence, right,

00:57:45.400 --> 00:57:51.080
[Guest]: I think the first couple of decades can be characterized by, you know, essentially neglect

00:57:51.080 --> 00:57:56.280
[Guest]: of primary education. Okay, so there was definitely investments in tertiary education with a view

00:57:56.280 --> 00:58:01.400
[Guest]: that this is important for building a technically trained labor force that would help India

00:58:01.400 --> 00:58:06.080
[Guest]: make the, you know, do the technological adoption needed for adopting technology. And Nehru

00:58:06.080 --> 00:58:09.960
[Guest]: in that sense was kind of, you know, as a state led modernist, and therefore, that certainly

00:58:09.960 --> 00:58:14.680
[Guest]: wanted the ability to absorb the technology. But that original orientation of the Indian

00:58:14.680 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: education system still casts a very long shadow, right, on the modern Indian economy today,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:24.280
[Guest]: right. So if you come back to why is it that our economy is not able to compete with, say,

00:58:24.280 --> 00:58:29.200
[Guest]: China or East Asia in labor intensive manufacturing, it's because the lack of primary education

00:58:29.200 --> 00:58:33.760
[Guest]: and the lack of foundational skills kind of hurts us in the mass market. Whereas the nature

00:58:33.760 --> 00:58:39.160
[Guest]: where India does really well, is actually in much more technically sophisticated manufacturing,

00:58:39.160 --> 00:58:44.560
[Guest]: right, which is consistent with our investment tertiary education. But I think, you know,

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:49.200
[Guest]: where we certainly did start making a course correction in the early 90s, you know, so

00:58:49.200 --> 00:58:53.640
[Guest]: you had these waves of programs, it was first out Operation Blackboard, then there was Sarvashiksha

00:58:53.640 --> 00:58:56.520
[Guest]: Abhiyan, then, you know, you had the right to education, now you have the new education

00:58:56.520 --> 00:59:00.680
[Guest]: policy. And over the past 25 years, I think, certainly, or 30 years, there's certainly

00:59:00.680 --> 00:59:04.720
[Guest]: been a substantial pivot in terms of focusing on school education. So I'm focusing first

00:59:04.720 --> 00:59:09.240
[Guest]: on the good news. Okay, so at an enrollment level, and if you just look at net enrollment

00:59:09.240 --> 00:59:14.800
[Guest]: rate and completion, is that between 1991 and 2011 censuses, you know, there's a sharp

00:59:14.800 --> 00:59:19.680
[Guest]: increase in enrollment, if you look at the fraction of children aged 7 to 14, who are

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:25.040
[Guest]: in school, or at least enrolled in school, that number is now over 95%. And one consequence

00:59:25.040 --> 00:59:30.520
[Guest]: of that increase in enrollment is also a sharp reduction in different dimensions of socioeconomic

00:59:30.520 --> 00:59:34.960
[Guest]: inequality with regard to access to education, right, because you don't get to 95% without

00:59:34.960 --> 00:59:39.680
[Guest]: basically getting almost everybody there. So the glass half full story is the success

00:59:39.680 --> 00:59:44.640
[Guest]: in terms of enrollment, right. So you've seen massive increases in spending, increases in

00:59:44.640 --> 00:59:48.800
[Guest]: school construction, increases in recruiting teachers, increases in, you know, building

00:59:48.800 --> 00:59:52.880
[Guest]: toilets, building compound walls, building school facilities, providing midday meals.

00:59:52.880 --> 00:59:57.320
[Guest]: So there has been an enormous increase in expenditure on education, okay, relative to

00:59:57.320 --> 01:00:01.340
[Guest]: what it was before. And, you know, you do have positive results in terms of enrollment.

01:00:01.340 --> 01:00:04.920
[Guest]: And it's not even to say that that doesn't give you any learning, because the counterfactual

01:00:04.920 --> 01:00:09.520
[Guest]: of no schooling is clearly going to produce lower learning, okay. But the glass half empty

01:00:09.520 --> 01:00:14.400
[Guest]: part of the story is that despite these massive investments of not just money, but also time,

01:00:14.400 --> 01:00:19.160
[Guest]: right, the opportunity cost of time is not zero, including for children, is that the

01:00:19.160 --> 01:00:25.120
[Guest]: translation of all of this spending into outcomes has been remarkably poor, okay. And so this,

01:00:25.120 --> 01:00:28.640
[Guest]: here, I'm talking mainly about the public education system, right. So and then there's

01:00:28.640 --> 01:00:32.680
[Guest]: the parallel piece that's going on. And so and we'll talk more about the research and

01:00:32.680 --> 01:00:38.200
[Guest]: evidence on specific reasons for why the quality of expenditure in education has been so poor.

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:42.960
[Guest]: But, you know, basically, it comes down to weak governance, okay, and suboptimal pedagogy.

01:00:42.960 --> 01:00:47.880
[Guest]: And I'll talk about both of those points in a moment. But one manifestation of the weakness

01:00:47.880 --> 01:00:52.080
[Guest]: of the public education system is kind of the widespread exit to fee charging private

01:00:52.080 --> 01:00:57.200
[Guest]: options, right. And basically, alongside this increase in public education, public investment,

01:00:57.200 --> 01:01:01.520
[Guest]: you're also seeing a steady increase in the market share of private schools where, you

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:05.480
[Guest]: know, even in rural India, it's about 30%. In urban India, it's probably 70%. I think

01:01:05.480 --> 01:01:09.800
[Guest]: recent estimates suggest that at an all India level, you're talking close to 50% of children

01:01:09.800 --> 01:01:14.400
[Guest]: are enrolled in private schools, okay. And this is, at one level, it's an enormous indictment

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:19.000
[Guest]: of our public expenditure in education, because the exit to private schooling is not happening

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:22.960
[Guest]: as a response to shrinking government spending, right. It's happening despite increase in

01:01:22.960 --> 01:01:27.760
[Guest]: government spending. So, you know, so one way to think about kind of the value destruction

01:01:27.760 --> 01:01:34.080
[Guest]: in terms of the low return on investment, or not ROI, but low quality of expenditure,

01:01:34.080 --> 01:01:37.240
[Guest]: those are two different terms, because the ROI can still be positive, but you could do

01:01:37.240 --> 01:01:42.600
[Guest]: much, much better, okay. The, is the fact that, because if people are voting with their

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:45.520
[Guest]: feet on the private school, one way to ask this question is, what does it say about the

01:01:45.520 --> 01:01:49.160
[Guest]: quality of your product that you can't even give it away for free, okay, which is, and

01:01:49.160 --> 01:01:52.160
[Guest]: you can't even give it away at a negative price, right, because the price of public

01:01:52.160 --> 01:01:55.560
[Guest]: education is negative, because you're providing midday meals, you're providing a bunch of

01:01:55.560 --> 01:02:00.240
[Guest]: other inputs. So, the business as usual is not working, right. So, so at a big picture

01:02:00.240 --> 01:02:04.400
[Guest]: facts level, expenditure has gone up, enrollment has gone up, school completion has gone up,

01:02:04.400 --> 01:02:08.880
[Guest]: and dropouts have gone down. And on input based measures, we're doing really, you know,

01:02:08.880 --> 01:02:12.920
[Guest]: on every input based measure, it looks like the school system has improved, till you get

01:02:12.920 --> 01:02:16.880
[Guest]: to this vexing question of learning outcomes. And that's when, you know, the emperor really

01:02:16.880 --> 01:02:21.320
[Guest]: has no clothes. And so I can now talk a little bit more about the detailed research on each

01:02:21.320 --> 01:02:25.160
[Guest]: of the factors in each of the reasons. But you know, if you want to comment a little

01:02:25.160 --> 01:02:28.360
[Guest]: bit on this big picture, that's fine. Or I can go into the research itself.

01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:31.480
[Amit Varma]: No, the big picture thing is very worrying. Because as you've pointed out, even though

01:02:31.480 --> 01:02:35.360
[Amit Varma]: enrollments have gone up in the last couple of decades, outcomes have actually gone down.

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:38.760
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, it's telling that it's not improved, you know, at least not at least

01:02:38.760 --> 01:02:44.560
[Amit Varma]: not improved. And what is also sort of depressing is that despite the fact that there are that

01:02:44.560 --> 01:02:47.640
[Amit Varma]: government schools are not just free, they're actually giving you stuff in terms of midday

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:52.360
[Amit Varma]: meals and all of that. So they're better than free. But poor parents, not just the rich

01:02:52.360 --> 01:02:56.680
[Amit Varma]: who can afford elite private schools, but poor parents still tend to spend significant

01:02:56.680 --> 01:03:01.120
[Amit Varma]: chunks of their income sending their kids to private schools instead. And there is this

01:03:01.120 --> 01:03:05.720
[Amit Varma]: misconception that private schools necessarily means a Bishop cotton and a St. John's and

01:03:05.720 --> 01:03:10.160
[Amit Varma]: elite private schools, but most private schools are little budget private schools operating

01:03:10.160 --> 01:03:14.240
[Amit Varma]: out of holes in the walls. But I want to turn to private schools later after we sort of

01:03:14.240 --> 01:03:19.040
[Amit Varma]: start talking about public schools. One broad thing that I'd like you to elaborate on which

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:25.560
[Amit Varma]: I found incredibly insightful in your writings was when you pointed out that one fundamental

01:03:25.560 --> 01:03:31.960
[Amit Varma]: way in which the Indian education system falls behind others is that the education system

01:03:31.960 --> 01:03:35.400
[Amit Varma]: can basically fulfill two functions, which are human development, where you actually

01:03:35.400 --> 01:03:41.720
[Amit Varma]: increase the skills of the kids, or sorting. And we have focused on sorting, we are focused

01:03:41.720 --> 01:03:45.800
[Amit Varma]: on filtration, rather than education. Can you elaborate a bit on this?

01:03:45.800 --> 01:03:50.320
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think and maybe, maybe it kind of, you know, makes sense to come to this

01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:54.480
[Amit Varma]: after I quickly discuss the results, right? The research, let's go for that becomes an

01:03:54.480 --> 01:03:58.680
[Guest]: interpretive lens of making sense of why we are where we are, right? Like, you know, so

01:03:58.680 --> 01:04:03.560
[Guest]: let me, you know, so the first part is, so obviously, let me just give you the details

01:04:03.560 --> 01:04:08.200
[Guest]: a little bit of insight, right into why all of the spending is not translating into outcomes.

01:04:08.200 --> 01:04:12.400
[Guest]: Okay. And then, you know, so if you look at where the budget goes, the majority of the

01:04:12.400 --> 01:04:17.160
[Guest]: budget goes in four line items, okay, so by far the biggest is teacher salaries, right?

01:04:17.160 --> 01:04:21.760
[Guest]: And then there's also money that gets spent on school infrastructure and building toilets

01:04:21.760 --> 01:04:26.240
[Guest]: and compound walls and providing books and computers and resources and stuff like that.

01:04:26.240 --> 01:04:30.520
[Guest]: Then there's money spent on student inputs of say, midday meals and school grants and

01:04:30.520 --> 01:04:34.120
[Guest]: stuff like that. And then, you know, you also spend a fair bit of money on teacher training,

01:04:34.120 --> 01:04:38.240
[Guest]: and other kind of quality upgradation kind of investments, right? Now, the bad news is

01:04:38.240 --> 01:04:42.360
[Guest]: that none of these four things, for the most part, seem to have much impact on learning

01:04:42.360 --> 01:04:46.920
[Guest]: outcomes. And let me just explain why. Okay, so first of all, I don't know if your listeners

01:04:46.920 --> 01:04:50.520
[Guest]: want a little bit of a detour into kind of research methodology, but maybe I will not

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:54.080
[Guest]: do that here. And, you know, you can point people to other sources where I've written

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:57.920
[Guest]: about RCPs and research methodology, you know, but maybe it's worth taking just two or three

01:04:57.920 --> 01:05:02.760
[Guest]: minutes, right, which is, and it's also something about the nature of research more generally,

01:05:02.760 --> 01:05:07.480
[Guest]: is that the problem with research is that actually bad research is worse than no research,

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:12.040
[Guest]: okay, and that because it kind of crowds out people's attention by creating more confusion,

01:05:12.040 --> 01:05:17.120
[Guest]: okay. So, you can get very, very misleading results, right, if you don't account for the

01:05:17.120 --> 01:05:23.720
[Guest]: fact that correlation is not causation. And often you have to, you know, you need well-identified

01:05:23.720 --> 01:05:27.720
[Guest]: research strategies that give you credible control groups against which you can be sure

01:05:27.720 --> 01:05:30.960
[Guest]: that you're, in fact, evaluating the effect of the policy that you say you are, okay.

01:05:30.960 --> 01:05:35.800
[Guest]: So, to take a two-minute detour on research methodology, let's just take the midday meal

01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:40.040
[Guest]: program, right. So, this is something we spend thousands of crores on on a year. And if a

01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:43.640
[Guest]: finance minister would ask the education minister saying, we spend all of this money on this

01:05:43.640 --> 01:05:47.880
[Guest]: program, can you tell me what the impact has been? The education department actually has

01:05:47.880 --> 01:05:51.000
[Guest]: no way of answering that question, right, because they haven't necessarily thought about

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:55.120
[Guest]: the outcomes or measured the outcomes. Now, even if you measure the outcomes and saying

01:05:55.120 --> 01:06:01.040
[Guest]: in 2003, I have some baseline indicators of, say, you know, of attendance, of nutrition

01:06:01.040 --> 01:06:04.840
[Guest]: and of learning outcomes, and you say, okay, let me measure this five years later or 10

01:06:04.840 --> 01:06:08.600
[Guest]: years later after the midday meal and see how much it has improved, okay. Now, the problem

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:12.320
[Guest]: with that comparison is that there are hundreds of other things changing at the same time,

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:16.080
[Guest]: okay. So, you've got general economic growth, parental incomes are increasing, attitudes

01:06:16.080 --> 01:06:19.800
[Guest]: are changing. So, maybe you got those improvements without your program at all, okay, which is

01:06:19.800 --> 01:06:24.640
[Guest]: kind of why you need a credible control group. And part of the reason, you know, the main

01:06:24.640 --> 01:06:29.640
[Guest]: reason for this year's Nobel Prize in economics was kind of the bringing of experimental methods

01:06:29.640 --> 01:06:34.560
[Guest]: from clinical trials into the evaluation of social policies. And a lot of the work I do,

01:06:34.560 --> 01:06:38.240
[Guest]: you know, as you said in the introduction, I am the global chair of education for J-PAL.

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:43.040
[Guest]: And so, oversee the entire, or not oversee, but at least provide, you know, help channel

01:06:43.040 --> 01:06:47.060
[Guest]: the insights from all of the research happening around the world into kind of updating our

01:06:47.060 --> 01:06:51.520
[Guest]: syntheses about knowledge and education research, right. So, the research summaries I'm going

01:06:51.520 --> 01:06:56.480
[Guest]: to give you are based on high quality work. And so, coming to school infrastructure, you

01:06:56.480 --> 01:07:00.280
[Guest]: know, so having a school relative to not having a school definitely matters, okay. It matters

01:07:00.280 --> 01:07:03.440
[Guest]: for enrollment, it matters for learning outcomes. If the counterfactual is no schooling, there's

01:07:03.440 --> 01:07:07.240
[Guest]: no question that schooling matters. But if you then look at the budgets that we're spending

01:07:07.240 --> 01:07:11.360
[Guest]: on upgrading classrooms and building toilets and compound walls and all of that kind of

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:15.160
[Guest]: stuff, for the most part, or libraries, computer labs, you know, none of these things seem

01:07:15.160 --> 01:07:19.740
[Guest]: to matter, okay. And I think we can get into the reasons for this. But the broad and simple

01:07:19.740 --> 01:07:24.200
[Guest]: answer is that I think there's three possible things, okay. So, one is that all of these

01:07:24.200 --> 01:07:29.380
[Guest]: infrastructure can help make education a better consumption experience, but it may not actually

01:07:29.380 --> 01:07:32.920
[Guest]: be what matters for teaching and learning, which is for learning, which is what happens

01:07:32.920 --> 01:07:36.760
[Guest]: inside the classroom, right. So, one slight tangent, but which is very related to this.

01:07:36.760 --> 01:07:41.480
[Guest]: There's this wonderful paper looking at German higher education after World War II, okay,

01:07:41.480 --> 01:07:46.000
[Guest]: and tries to study the relative importance of physical capital versus human capital in

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:50.920
[Guest]: education, okay. So, it's a paper that looks at allied bombings during World War II created

01:07:50.920 --> 01:07:55.080
[Guest]: quasi-random variation in physical capital destruction, because some universities lost

01:07:55.080 --> 01:07:59.560
[Guest]: their buildings completely, okay. Whereas the universities that had a higher fraction

01:07:59.560 --> 01:08:03.480
[Guest]: of Jewish faculty had a much bigger loss of their intellectual capital, right, because

01:08:03.480 --> 01:08:07.400
[Guest]: these people, you know, they were either shunted to camps or they migrated to the U.S. And

01:08:07.400 --> 01:08:11.120
[Guest]: so, what the study shows is that 10 years after World War II, that the universities

01:08:11.120 --> 01:08:16.280
[Guest]: that had lost their physical capital had completely recovered. Whereas 50 years after, the universities

01:08:16.280 --> 01:08:20.240
[Guest]: that lost their scientists and faculty had still not recovered, okay. And so, what that

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:24.200
[Guest]: tells you is like, and this is relevant to India's, you know, expansion of higher education

01:08:24.200 --> 01:08:27.640
[Guest]: today that we keep talking about buildings, right, but we don't have the faculty. Till

01:08:27.640 --> 01:08:31.640
[Guest]: you have kind of top class faculty, this is not going to translate into higher quality

01:08:31.640 --> 01:08:36.160
[Guest]: education. So, you could say the same thing about schools where the buildings may be nice

01:08:36.160 --> 01:08:41.000
[Guest]: to have, necessary, but by no means sufficient for getting learning outcomes. And then there's

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:44.440
[Guest]: other things that could be going on, but at a big picture, I'm not going to say don't

01:08:44.440 --> 01:08:47.920
[Guest]: build schools. I'm just going to say that the evidence suggests that it may be an enabling

01:08:47.920 --> 01:08:51.600
[Guest]: condition, but it's certainly not sufficient to get you learning outcomes.

01:08:51.600 --> 01:08:55.320
[Guest]: Now, the harder part then is teachers. If you look at where we spend most of our money,

01:08:55.320 --> 01:08:58.880
[Guest]: so you say, okay, maybe it's not buildings, maybe it's teacher quality, right? And here

01:08:58.880 --> 01:09:03.360
[Guest]: again, the news is very depressing. It's depressing because if you look at, say, teacher training,

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:07.360
[Guest]: which everybody says you need to train teachers and teacher training will improve outcomes,

01:09:07.360 --> 01:09:12.400
[Guest]: is there's not a single study in India that finds any meaningful correlation between possessing

01:09:12.400 --> 01:09:17.600
[Guest]: a teacher training credential and your effectiveness in the classroom as measured by, you know,

01:09:17.600 --> 01:09:22.000
[Guest]: improvement in student learning. So, again, as an aside, some of the best insights we

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:26.320
[Guest]: have gotten onto public sector labor markets in terms of research has come from the education

01:09:26.320 --> 01:09:30.680
[Guest]: sector. And that's because measuring public sector worker productivity is very, very difficult

01:09:30.680 --> 01:09:35.520
[Guest]: because it's multidimensional and you're working in teams. Whereas teachers are a class of

01:09:35.520 --> 01:09:39.480
[Guest]: public sector employee where if I measure the learning levels of students before the

01:09:39.480 --> 01:09:43.000
[Guest]: school year and measure it at the end of the year, and I know which teacher is assigned

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:47.120
[Guest]: to which student, you can actually measure productivity as effectiveness at improving

01:09:47.120 --> 01:09:50.560
[Guest]: learning outcomes. Okay. So, there's a lot we learn about public sector labor markets

01:09:50.560 --> 01:09:55.040
[Guest]: in general, but specifically, you know, using methods like that, this value added analysis,

01:09:55.040 --> 01:09:59.080
[Guest]: we find there is really no evidence, not in my studies, not in any other studies. And

01:09:59.080 --> 01:10:03.400
[Guest]: so, again, what's going on? Okay. So, why? And this is very depressing to me as an educator,

01:10:03.400 --> 01:10:07.240
[Guest]: right? Because I believe in training, I believe in education, that's what I do. And to then

01:10:07.240 --> 01:10:10.720
[Guest]: see the results that none of this seems to matter. Okay. So, and again, there's three

01:10:10.720 --> 01:10:15.880
[Guest]: broad explanations. The first is, remember that what we are pushing is a teaching credential

01:10:15.880 --> 01:10:19.920
[Guest]: as opposed to any effectiveness at teaching. Okay. So, a bunch of these credentials are

01:10:19.920 --> 01:10:24.480
[Guest]: probably just fake, given that we have, you know, an entire industry, a cottage industry

01:10:24.480 --> 01:10:28.640
[Guest]: of kind of, you know, diploma mills, and then it's not surprising it has no effect. But

01:10:28.640 --> 01:10:32.920
[Guest]: I think a deeper problem is, even if you look at the legitimate teacher training programs,

01:10:32.920 --> 01:10:37.880
[Guest]: if you were to go look at the content analysis of their curriculum, right, most of the curriculum

01:10:37.880 --> 01:10:42.280
[Guest]: of teacher education programs focuses on history, theory, sociology, psychology, philosophy

01:10:42.280 --> 01:10:47.760
[Guest]: of education, and very little on actual pedagogical practice of how do you teach. Okay. And one

01:10:47.760 --> 01:10:51.480
[Guest]: of the reasons for this is that education schools themselves tend to be occupied by

01:10:51.480 --> 01:10:55.600
[Guest]: PhDs who have PhDs in their disciplines. And so, they want to propagate their disciplines

01:10:55.600 --> 01:10:59.160
[Guest]: in the context of education, as opposed to get their hands dirty with the actual job

01:10:59.160 --> 01:11:03.600
[Guest]: of learning how to teach, which is a practical skill. Okay. So, the practical orientation

01:11:03.600 --> 01:11:07.400
[Guest]: is kind of non-existent. And if you look at the better teacher training programs around

01:11:07.400 --> 01:11:10.720
[Guest]: the world, they have things that are, you know, more practicum based. And I'll come

01:11:10.720 --> 01:11:16.040
[Guest]: back to that in one of my policy recommendations. And then the third problem is that even if

01:11:16.040 --> 01:11:20.920
[Guest]: the teacher training credential were to give you some meaningful knowledge, in a de facto

01:11:20.920 --> 01:11:25.080
[Guest]: setting in a government classroom where there's zero motivation and accountability for outcomes,

01:11:25.080 --> 01:11:29.000
[Guest]: you don't use that knowledge, right? Like, so that knowledge may not translate into practice.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:34.280
[Guest]: And the way we know this, what you see is that the same teacher training program that

01:11:34.280 --> 01:11:37.720
[Guest]: is found to be highly effective in private schools, when you do that training program

01:11:37.720 --> 01:11:41.240
[Guest]: in a government school, ends up having no effect. And I can give you links to the research

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:46.780
[Guest]: on this. And conversely, when you do performance based bonuses for teachers in the public schools,

01:11:46.780 --> 01:11:51.440
[Guest]: what you'll find is that in the business as usual setting, teacher training has no effect.

01:11:51.440 --> 01:11:56.760
[Guest]: But in the incentive schools, the better trained teachers do much better. Okay. And so, what

01:11:56.760 --> 01:12:00.680
[Guest]: that tells you is that the training gives you the capacity to do be better if you were

01:12:00.680 --> 01:12:06.080
[Guest]: to choose to exercise that capacity, right? So, quality is kind of knowledge times effort,

01:12:06.080 --> 01:12:10.140
[Guest]: right? And if effort is low, then the knowledge doesn't matter. And this is something that

01:12:10.140 --> 01:12:14.240
[Guest]: shows up even in my research on health, right? When we can have maybe a separate show on

01:12:14.240 --> 01:12:17.800
[Guest]: the even greater crisis that's our healthcare systems, okay? But the fundamental point is

01:12:17.800 --> 01:12:21.280
[Guest]: the same. And this will show up when we get to the private schools also. At the private

01:12:21.280 --> 01:12:25.000
[Guest]: school, teachers are less qualified, but they make up for their lower knowledge with much

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:28.640
[Guest]: higher levels of effort, okay? And so, in the public system, the teachers are much more

01:12:28.640 --> 01:12:32.840
[Guest]: qualified, but the effort levels are low, which therefore limit the transmission of

01:12:32.840 --> 01:12:36.600
[Guest]: that knowledge into better outcome, right? So, that's the training for you. So, now think

01:12:36.600 --> 01:12:40.760
[Guest]: about it, right? Because the entire building block of our right to education, of kind of

01:12:40.760 --> 01:12:44.520
[Guest]: these legislations and going back to the heavy hand of the state and regulating in terms

01:12:44.520 --> 01:12:48.720
[Guest]: of credentials, and all the research shows that those credentials have zero impact on

01:12:48.720 --> 01:12:52.760
[Guest]: learning outcomes, okay? So, the whole system is pushing in some ways for the meaningless

01:12:52.760 --> 01:12:56.400
[Guest]: credential. So, we can come back to that later, okay? And then the third part of business

01:12:56.400 --> 01:13:02.400
[Guest]: as usual is kind of reducing pupil-teacher ratio, reducing class size. And this is by

01:13:02.400 --> 01:13:05.560
[Guest]: far the most expensive thing that we spend our money on, right? So, if you look at the

01:13:05.560 --> 01:13:10.040
[Guest]: Right to Education Act, we need to move PTR from 40 to 1 to 30 to 1, which roughly cost

01:13:10.040 --> 01:13:15.400
[Guest]: an extra 25,000 crores a year in terms of additional teacher hiring, okay? Now, the

01:13:15.400 --> 01:13:20.080
[Guest]: effects here are not zero. The effects, you do have some positive effect on learning outcomes,

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:24.120
[Guest]: but the magnitudes are very, very small, and they're so small that the investment per se

01:13:24.120 --> 01:13:28.200
[Guest]: does not appear to be very cost effective, okay? And now, what are the reasons for why

01:13:28.200 --> 01:13:34.300
[Guest]: the reduced PTR may not be having an impact? It's again, if you look at the data more carefully,

01:13:34.300 --> 01:13:39.200
[Guest]: what you'll see is that where class size matters the most is when children are very, very young,

01:13:39.200 --> 01:13:42.640
[Guest]: okay? So, when you're really young and you need small group attention because children

01:13:42.640 --> 01:13:46.720
[Guest]: can't even sit in one place. So, one way to think about this is think about university

01:13:46.720 --> 01:13:51.040
[Guest]: education. As a professor, I can lecture to 100 students or lecture to 200, okay? Now,

01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:55.260
[Guest]: how much better is the quality of education when it's 100? Maybe it's slightly better.

01:13:55.260 --> 01:13:58.960
[Guest]: Maybe there's a little bit more discussion relative to 200. But the question is, is it

01:13:58.960 --> 01:14:02.520
[Guest]: twice as much better? Because that's what it's going to cost you, right? Like you need

01:14:02.520 --> 01:14:06.760
[Guest]: to cut the class size in half, okay? Or at least some variant of that, right? So, the

01:14:06.760 --> 01:14:10.760
[Guest]: class size reductions matter the most when children are very, very young. There is our

01:14:10.760 --> 01:14:15.800
[Guest]: norms on PTR as done at the elementary school level. And if you go look at the schools often,

01:14:15.800 --> 01:14:18.880
[Guest]: what will happen? The senior teacher will teach class five in a small class and assign

01:14:18.880 --> 01:14:23.400
[Guest]: the junior teacher to the large younger class, okay? So, the PTR reduction at the school

01:14:23.400 --> 01:14:28.520
[Guest]: level is not optimized in terms of how it's used. Then there are other issues of PTR which

01:14:28.520 --> 01:14:32.320
[Guest]: kind of we have to do, and I'll come back to this in the policy recommendations, which

01:14:32.320 --> 01:14:37.280
[Guest]: is one of the problems in India is because we have expanded school construction across

01:14:37.280 --> 01:14:38.280
[Guest]: the board.

01:14:38.280 --> 01:14:43.600
[Guest]: You now have so many subscale schools that you have literally like, you know, over tens

01:14:43.600 --> 01:14:48.040
[Guest]: of thousands of schools that have enrollment of under 20 or 30 students with one or two

01:14:48.040 --> 01:14:52.160
[Guest]: teachers. So, in that setting, then you have multi-grade teaching across five grades. Even

01:14:52.160 --> 01:14:56.240
[Guest]: the PTR reduction doesn't translate as much into learning outcomes. So, again, the point

01:14:56.240 --> 01:15:01.120
[Guest]: I'm making and why all of this is important is that if I were to put 20 experts in education

01:15:01.120 --> 01:15:04.600
[Guest]: and I'll come back to the new education policy later, and I think overall the new education

01:15:04.600 --> 01:15:08.140
[Guest]: policy is a great document, it's a wonderful document, and I'm happy about many things

01:15:08.140 --> 01:15:12.520
[Guest]: about it, but the big kind of blind spot is that there is no discussion of kind of a word

01:15:12.520 --> 01:15:16.160
[Guest]: that is considered dirty among educationists, which is cost-effectiveness, okay? Like, which

01:15:16.160 --> 01:15:19.920
[Guest]: is, you know, when you have a bunch of things to do and you have limited resources, you

01:15:19.920 --> 01:15:24.520
[Guest]: need a way to prioritize this, and typically what ends up happening is you spend your money

01:15:24.520 --> 01:15:29.040
[Guest]: on what looks like all the components of an education system, but many of them are actually

01:15:29.040 --> 01:15:32.960
[Guest]: not the most important things and you're spending tons of money on things that don't matter.

01:15:32.960 --> 01:15:38.360
[Guest]: And what gets even worse, see, PTR reductions are still okay, but perhaps, like, the most

01:15:38.360 --> 01:15:43.720
[Guest]: inefficient part of our education system is the fact that teachers' salaries are so high,

01:15:43.720 --> 01:15:48.880
[Guest]: okay, and relative to either the market or private schools or kind of other, you know,

01:15:48.880 --> 01:15:54.520
[Guest]: multiple metrics of what the outside wage for the human capital that's as public school

01:15:54.520 --> 01:15:59.400
[Guest]: teachers is, is we've now got large-scale studies showing you that even unconditional

01:15:59.400 --> 01:16:03.960
[Guest]: doubling of teacher salaries gives you zero impact on learning outcomes, okay? And so

01:16:03.960 --> 01:16:08.480
[Guest]: given that the bulk of our budget, once you kind of take your pay commission recommendations,

01:16:08.480 --> 01:16:12.880
[Guest]: that absorbs 60, 70, 80% of the education budget. So when you look at our education

01:16:12.880 --> 01:16:16.760
[Guest]: budget is going up, most of that is just being absorbed by salaries, right? I mean, and those

01:16:16.760 --> 01:16:21.340
[Guest]: salaries are not translating into outcomes because we have a binding constraint to both

01:16:21.340 --> 01:16:25.360
[Guest]: governance and pedagogy, right? So the story in terms of the business as usual is very

01:16:25.360 --> 01:16:28.880
[Guest]: depressing because, and most of what the government does. And then the last thing is kind of midday

01:16:28.880 --> 01:16:33.040
[Guest]: meals and other kinds of inputs where, again, the effects are positive, but they are very,

01:16:33.040 --> 01:16:38.400
[Guest]: very modest, okay? So, and one reason is what we see in multiple studies is when the government

01:16:38.400 --> 01:16:42.360
[Guest]: provides a bunch of inputs, books and meals and stuff like that, you actually see a little

01:16:42.360 --> 01:16:46.000
[Guest]: bit of substitution in the household, right? Because the household then offsets its own

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:49.760
[Guest]: expenditure. So this is not to say that the household did not benefit from the expenditure

01:16:49.760 --> 01:16:53.960
[Guest]: because they save money, but it doesn't stick where you send it, right? Because money and

01:16:53.960 --> 01:16:59.120
[Guest]: resources are fungible, okay? So the bottom line is that you can get this even from looking

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:02.600
[Guest]: at the big picture, that expenditure has gone up and learning outcomes are flat. And then

01:17:02.600 --> 01:17:06.200
[Guest]: if you start looking at this component by component, you'll kind of see that each of

01:17:06.200 --> 01:17:11.440
[Guest]: these big expenditure categories are not really having much of an impact, okay? Now, this

01:17:11.440 --> 01:17:14.640
[Guest]: can be very depressing. This can be very depressing because you say, boss, like, you know, this

01:17:14.640 --> 01:17:19.680
[Guest]: is what I spend all my time on. Is there any hope here? And on an optimistic note, I think

01:17:19.680 --> 01:17:25.400
[Guest]: there are two very robust classes of interventions in public schooling that have time and again

01:17:25.400 --> 01:17:30.080
[Guest]: been found to be effective and found to be massively cost effective, right? So, and the

01:17:30.080 --> 01:17:34.460
[Guest]: first and basic thing is just governance, right? That our public school system is incredibly

01:17:34.460 --> 01:17:38.920
[Guest]: weakly governed. And, you know, my best known study is still the study I did 15 years ago

01:17:38.920 --> 01:17:44.080
[Guest]: or 17 years ago, just measuring teacher absence, right? That on any given day, about 25% of

01:17:44.080 --> 01:17:47.320
[Guest]: teachers are absent. And, you know, some people have gone and quibbled and said, no, it's

01:17:47.320 --> 01:17:51.200
[Guest]: lower than that. But actually, you have to include the times when you make a surprise

01:17:51.200 --> 01:17:54.720
[Guest]: visit and the school is closed because there's nobody there, right? Like, you know, and I

01:17:54.720 --> 01:17:59.000
[Guest]: think some studies have not included that as absence. So, you know, but the true numbers

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:04.400
[Guest]: are about 25%. Then we went back in about 2010 and measured in the same villages. And

01:18:04.400 --> 01:18:09.240
[Guest]: what you found was that on every input based measure, the number of toilets has gone up,

01:18:09.240 --> 01:18:13.560
[Guest]: number of electricity connections, compound walls, every input based measure of quality

01:18:13.560 --> 01:18:19.560
[Guest]: has improved. But the absence had reduced by only about 2%. And in fact, in more recent

01:18:19.560 --> 01:18:22.880
[Guest]: ongoing work in specific states like Madhya Pradesh, you know, if anything, the absence

01:18:22.880 --> 01:18:26.440
[Guest]: looks like it's continuing to go up. Okay, so that's a problem that's just not changed.

01:18:26.440 --> 01:18:32.560
[Guest]: So, to give you a sense, the fiscal cost of teacher absence alone at 2010 salaries we

01:18:32.560 --> 01:18:36.960
[Guest]: estimated was about 10,000 crores a year. Okay, that's just one line item of kind of

01:18:36.960 --> 01:18:41.280
[Guest]: just money down the drain. And given the increase in salaries right now, that's probably even

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:45.920
[Guest]: higher. Now, this is not to say, therefore, that you should not hire teachers or the like.

01:18:45.920 --> 01:18:50.960
[Guest]: The key point we make is that what's missing is the governance layer, right? So, the most

01:18:50.960 --> 01:18:55.760
[Guest]: robust finding in our earlier work is that the biggest predictor of lower absence is

01:18:55.760 --> 01:19:00.400
[Guest]: just has there been any monitoring visit made to your school, okay, that has any superior

01:19:00.400 --> 01:19:04.560
[Guest]: officer visited your school once in the last three months. And what you see is that there's

01:19:04.560 --> 01:19:09.480
[Guest]: kind of staggering vacancies at the level of the block education officer and even the

01:19:09.480 --> 01:19:14.000
[Guest]: tenure of a district education officer in our data as average of about one year. Okay,

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:18.840
[Guest]: so these guys come, they go, and we can discuss all the pathologies of public sector personnel

01:19:18.840 --> 01:19:23.320
[Guest]: management later, right? But the bottom line is that the public sector personnel management

01:19:23.320 --> 01:19:28.680
[Guest]: is just incredibly weak. And if you manage, we have multiple studies from different kinds

01:19:28.680 --> 01:19:33.880
[Guest]: of governance interventions ranging from better monitoring to even slight amounts of time

01:19:33.880 --> 01:19:37.160
[Guest]: paid to measures of performance and learning outcomes. And we can come back to whether

01:19:37.160 --> 01:19:41.080
[Guest]: we have the state capacity to implement that. So, one of the reasons I have not even recommended

01:19:41.080 --> 01:19:44.520
[Guest]: that even though I did the study in performance pay, I've not recommended we scale it up because

01:19:44.520 --> 01:19:48.000
[Guest]: I don't have the confidence that we have the capacity to implement that, right? But the

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:52.360
[Guest]: reason that study is important is more as a proof of concept of how much slack there

01:19:52.360 --> 01:19:57.280
[Guest]: is in the effort of a typical teacher, that even 3% of pay that is linked to performance

01:19:57.280 --> 01:20:01.840
[Guest]: with nothing else can give you dramatic improvements in performance, right? So, the default level

01:20:01.840 --> 01:20:05.920
[Guest]: of slack is very, very high, okay? So, the first class of interventions is governance.

01:20:05.920 --> 01:20:09.820
[Guest]: But there's another variant of this where you see where study after study after study

01:20:09.820 --> 01:20:15.600
[Guest]: finds that locally hired contract teachers, right, who are hired typically at the village

01:20:15.600 --> 01:20:21.040
[Guest]: level who have 10th or 12th pass kind of credentials, no formal teacher training, and who are paid

01:20:21.040 --> 01:20:25.920
[Guest]: one-fifth to one-tenth of what a government school teacher is paid, is at least as effective,

01:20:25.920 --> 01:20:30.200
[Guest]: if not more effective at improving primary school learning outcomes, okay? So, and so

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:34.080
[Guest]: what that tells you is that the training and the salary is neither necessary nor sufficient,

01:20:34.080 --> 01:20:38.280
[Guest]: right? So, where most of your resources are going right now is saying I want trained teachers

01:20:38.280 --> 01:20:43.200
[Guest]: and I want highly paid teachers, but neither of those things seem to matter relative to

01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:47.080
[Guest]: kind of are you there and are you in fact teaching at where the students are, which

01:20:47.080 --> 01:20:51.400
[Guest]: I'll come back to in a moment, okay? Now, so one part of the problem is governance.

01:20:51.400 --> 01:20:54.800
[Guest]: But now for a moment, you know, people, teacher unions and others will often kind of, you

01:20:54.800 --> 01:20:57.980
[Guest]: know, really get upset at me. They'll say like, you know, your studies on teacher absence

01:20:57.980 --> 01:21:02.400
[Guest]: have been, you know, a real setback for teacher morale, setback for this thing. And I'm like,

01:21:02.400 --> 01:21:06.560
[Guest]: you know, the problem is not the fact that I'm calling out the 25% who are absent. It's

01:21:06.560 --> 01:21:10.120
[Guest]: that those who are absent are shedding a bad light on those of you who are sincere, okay?

01:21:10.120 --> 01:21:13.320
[Guest]: Because there are a bunch of sincere teachers, okay? So, this is not to paint all public

01:21:13.320 --> 01:21:17.320
[Guest]: school teachers with a bad brush. There are many, many, many incredibly sincere teachers,

01:21:17.320 --> 01:21:21.360
[Guest]: right? Who overcome a lot of hardship, go travel to remote areas, are very committed

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:26.160
[Guest]: to their students and try to do a lot, okay? So, this is not meant to paint teachers like

01:21:26.160 --> 01:21:30.440
[Guest]: broadly with a bad brush, right? So, now let's look at the second part, which is let's look

01:21:30.440 --> 01:21:35.760
[Guest]: at a highly motivated teacher, okay? And this is, in a way, an even bigger problem. Because

01:21:35.760 --> 01:21:40.360
[Guest]: if you look at what does a highly motivated teacher do, a good teacher defines his or

01:21:40.360 --> 01:21:45.680
[Guest]: her goodness by, have I completed the entire portion, okay? So, you take the textbook,

01:21:45.680 --> 01:21:49.240
[Guest]: you convert the textbook into lesson plans, and you say each week, you know, you're very

01:21:49.240 --> 01:21:52.520
[Guest]: diligent. You say, this is my class lesson plan. I will teach, I will do the homework,

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:56.680
[Guest]: I'll discuss the exercises, I'll do all of this, okay? Now, the problem, and this is

01:21:56.680 --> 01:22:00.880
[Guest]: the elephant in the room that pretty much like, you know, people just haven't recognized,

01:22:00.880 --> 01:22:06.240
[Guest]: is that what has happened is that because your curricular standards are set at a time

01:22:06.240 --> 01:22:10.600
[Guest]: when the fraction of people who are going to schooling was relatively small, okay? That

01:22:10.600 --> 01:22:15.200
[Guest]: these curricular standards are, in fact, very, very high. And you have tens of millions of

01:22:15.200 --> 01:22:19.800
[Guest]: first generation learners who are entering the schooling system without the LKG, UKG

01:22:19.800 --> 01:22:23.800
[Guest]: that most elite kids have. And so, they fall behind the curriculum. They fall behind the

01:22:23.800 --> 01:22:28.160
[Guest]: curriculum so fast that if you get to class three, and if you don't have foundational

01:22:28.160 --> 01:22:32.560
[Guest]: literacy and numeracy, at that point, you could be sitting in the class. And even though

01:22:32.560 --> 01:22:36.360
[Guest]: the teacher is very sincerely teaching, right? Like, you know, it's just not making sense,

01:22:36.360 --> 01:22:40.000
[Guest]: right? It's like, you know, what the engineering college or the single set bouncer guy, right?

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:43.600
[Guest]: Like, I mean, to use a cricket analogy, right? And this is, I guess, the one place where

01:22:43.600 --> 01:22:47.080
[Guest]: a podcast is limited relative to, you know, videos, but maybe you can even just put a

01:22:47.080 --> 01:22:50.400
[Guest]: link to this one picture, you know, which I've put in a bunch of my articles, which

01:22:50.400 --> 01:22:54.880
[Guest]: I think is the single most important picture for understanding education in India is this

01:22:54.880 --> 01:23:00.480
[Guest]: picture that, and assuming you kind of put a link to this, that shows that on the x-axis,

01:23:00.480 --> 01:23:05.760
[Guest]: if you have students by grade enrolled in, and in the y-axis, you have the grade appropriate

01:23:05.760 --> 01:23:09.040
[Guest]: standard. If the children are on the grade appropriate standard, they would be on the

01:23:09.040 --> 01:23:14.320
[Guest]: 45 degree blue line, okay? But in practice, the true learning level is about half of that,

01:23:14.320 --> 01:23:17.880
[Guest]: okay? So, the progress that's being made is about half of the curriculum. But what is

01:23:17.880 --> 01:23:22.760
[Guest]: even more, I think, problematic is the enormous variation in learning level within a given

01:23:22.760 --> 01:23:26.920
[Guest]: classroom, okay? So, if you look at that picture, you'll see that, and this is partly a result

01:23:26.920 --> 01:23:31.760
[Guest]: of the no detention policy and another case of good intentions kind of backfiring. But

01:23:31.760 --> 01:23:35.080
[Guest]: because you have promoted children through regardless of learning levels, you end up

01:23:35.080 --> 01:23:39.720
[Guest]: in a situation in a class six or seven or eight where you have children at second standard

01:23:39.720 --> 01:23:43.280
[Guest]: level, third standard level, fourth standard level, fifth, sixth, and seventh, right? So,

01:23:43.280 --> 01:23:47.480
[Guest]: it is like humanly impossible for a teacher to cater to that kind of variation in a classroom.

01:23:47.480 --> 01:23:51.120
[Guest]: So, the teacher defaults to completing the syllabus and the curriculum. And so, what

01:23:51.120 --> 01:23:54.960
[Guest]: happens is that children are going through the motions of sitting in school, learning

01:23:54.960 --> 01:23:59.720
[Guest]: nothing, and that's because the system has already left them behind, okay? And the one,

01:23:59.720 --> 01:24:18.680
[Guest]: you know, very powerful way of just seeing this point is, you know,

01:24:18.680 --> 01:24:35.560
[Guest]: you

01:24:35.560 --> 01:24:52.560
[Guest]: You are sitting there in the class, I will suddenly come and ask you what I said now, you won't understand a word, then what will I do, there will be a child next to me, that child will understand, I will look at that child and say, look, I will stop this child and say, okay, you solve the problem I said, then it will do, then I will look at you and say, idiot, why don't you study like him, right?

01:24:52.560 --> 01:25:13.560
[Guest]: So, what have I just done to you, right? I have given you 45 seconds in the shoes of an Indian child in a typical Indian classroom, right, which is that, and this is that sense of helplessness that you feel sitting in that classroom, where you feel that this is beyond me, is basically the lived reality of the majority of our children day to day in our school system.

01:25:13.560 --> 01:25:22.560
[Guest]: And that's because, essentially, and this then brings me back to the filtration and sorting, okay, which is, how do you make sense of this education system?

01:25:22.560 --> 01:25:36.560
[Guest]: So, once you understand that this is the binding constraint, there is also now tons of evidence, and in fact, this is a big part of the work that was cited in the Nobel Prize awarded last year, which Esther and Abhijit in partnership with Pratham and Rukmini Banerjee and others have done a series of studies,

01:25:36.560 --> 01:25:45.560
[Guest]: they just show that, you know, if you don't need highly qualified teachers, you can have volunteers with a 10th standard education, but all that they're doing is teaching at the right level.

01:25:45.560 --> 01:25:52.560
[Guest]: If a child is not able to read letters, you teach them letters. If you can't read words, you teach words. If you can't read sentences, you teach sentences.

01:25:52.560 --> 01:26:01.560
[Guest]: And you kind of build the scaffolding and meet the child where they are and teach, as opposed to kind of going lockstep with the curriculum, because this is what I need to do.

01:26:01.560 --> 01:26:10.560
[Guest]: And now, you know, we have tons of evidence that if you manage to kind of teach at the right level, that that becomes highly, highly effective and cost effective, okay?

01:26:10.560 --> 01:26:16.560
[Guest]: So, if you take this kind of overall picture on the public education system and say, how do you make sense of this?

01:26:16.560 --> 01:26:25.560
[Guest]: It's useful to then take a step back and realize that education systems have historically served three very different functions in society, right?

01:26:25.560 --> 01:26:31.560
[Guest]: There is a part of this which is about creating, teaching skills and teaching, you know, actual content.

01:26:31.560 --> 01:26:35.560
[Guest]: And you can call that the human development or human capital function of education, right?

01:26:35.560 --> 01:26:43.560
[Guest]: But the other function that education has served historically is it's also served a sorting and screening function of identifying who is smart,

01:26:43.560 --> 01:26:50.560
[Guest]: so that you can then allocate the people who are smart into positions of higher education, positions of leadership.

01:26:50.560 --> 01:26:57.560
[Guest]: And because, you know, you want your kind of highest ability citizens in positions of responsibility that affect kind of the larger group.

01:26:57.560 --> 01:27:01.560
[Guest]: Now, don't get me wrong, right? There is nothing wrong in sorting per se, right?

01:27:01.560 --> 01:27:11.560
[Guest]: Every society needs sorting, whether it's kind of, you know, whether it's Europe, whether it's China, every society finds a way to identify its most talented and direct them to positions of responsibility.

01:27:11.560 --> 01:27:19.560
[Guest]: And that would actually be consistent with the Rawlsian view, because you want your scientists and your, you know, people who are doing things that have broader social impact to be of the highest quality, right?

01:27:19.560 --> 01:27:22.560
[Guest]: The problem is not the sorting per se.

01:27:22.560 --> 01:27:30.560
[Guest]: The problem is that because you obsess on sorting, that if you're not going to meet that cutoff, then the system basically abandons you, right?

01:27:30.560 --> 01:27:36.560
[Guest]: And so when you're below that, effectively, you know, the only thing that the system cares about is are you passing this exam?

01:27:36.560 --> 01:27:42.560
[Guest]: OK, so which is why the best way to make sense of the Indian education system is that we are not an education system.

01:27:42.560 --> 01:27:44.560
[Guest]: We are fundamentally a filtration system, right?

01:27:44.560 --> 01:27:51.560
[Guest]: So if you look at the IITs, you know, people will say, look at our IITs, you know, and when I talk in the US, people often are very stupefied, right?

01:27:51.560 --> 01:27:54.560
[Guest]: Because they'll say, I thought India had the best education system in the world.

01:27:54.560 --> 01:28:00.560
[Guest]: You guys produced the CEO of Microsoft, the CEO of Google, the CEO of IBM, you know, the chancellor of my university, UCSD.

01:28:00.560 --> 01:28:05.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, they all went to IIT, the former provost, they all, you know, and then I tell them that, you know, that's right.

01:28:05.560 --> 01:28:11.560
[Guest]: But the magic of the IIT in some ways is that you maintain the stringency of the selection process.

01:28:11.560 --> 01:28:19.560
[Guest]: And so if I manage to select the top 0.001 percent of a billion percent distribution, I could put those kids in a circus and they will still do fantastic things.

01:28:19.560 --> 01:28:23.560
[Guest]: Right. So what we have is and this is true of the IIS, it's true of everything.

01:28:23.560 --> 01:28:29.560
[Guest]: Right. I mean, it's true that we have this selection focused education and exam system.

01:28:29.560 --> 01:28:31.560
[Guest]: And that's what drives everything. Right.

01:28:31.560 --> 01:28:37.560
[Guest]: It drives everything to the point that then if you're a student that's behind the exams, what do you do?

01:28:37.560 --> 01:28:43.560
[Guest]: You don't try to learn concepts. You try to say, how do I cram every past exam paper to give myself some shot at passing this exam?

01:28:43.560 --> 01:28:53.560
[Guest]: And which is why you then get this phenomenon of completely unemployable graduates, because they have crammed their way into something without any understanding of what's going on and famously captured in three idiots.

01:28:53.560 --> 01:28:58.560
[Guest]: So I think the point, the reason this is important is that people rail against the exam based system.

01:28:58.560 --> 01:29:10.560
[Guest]: But sometimes that can also give you very counterproductive, like, you know, well-intentioned, but backfiring kind of approaches like, you know, with, I think, Kapil Sibal and Aarti tried to do of saying, let's get rid of board exams.

01:29:10.560 --> 01:29:17.560
[Guest]: OK, but that is actually a mistake because getting rid of board exams doesn't get rid of the fact that society still wants the sorting.

01:29:17.560 --> 01:29:20.560
[Guest]: And so the rich will find other ways to signal. Right.

01:29:20.560 --> 01:29:27.560
[Guest]: Like, I mean, they'll take IBs, they'll take other fancy boards, they'll take, you know, other they'll take horse riding and find other ways to show that they're smart.

01:29:27.560 --> 01:29:30.560
[Guest]: And for the poor, in fact, your board exam is the only option.

01:29:30.560 --> 01:29:33.560
[Guest]: OK, so by taking that out, you've actually made it even harder.

01:29:33.560 --> 01:29:53.560
[Guest]: So that's, again, an example of why you need to not just kind of, you know, identify the symptom and go after it, but identify what are the deeper structural factors of the education system that give rise to these two very conflicting pressures where the human development paradigm is something that says, regardless of where you are, I want you to be better than where you were yesterday.

01:29:53.560 --> 01:29:56.560
[Guest]: Right. Which is what we want our education system to be doing.

01:29:56.560 --> 01:30:00.560
[Guest]: Whereas the ranking and sorting paradigm is all about, like, can I get past this hurdle?

01:30:00.560 --> 01:30:15.560
[Guest]: So I think my larger point, and this is something I mentioned in my, you know, both the paper that I wrote for the volume that Abhijit Banerjee and Raghuram Rajan and Geeta Gopinath and Mir Sharma edited, as well as those were very much in my comments to the committee on the new education policy,

01:30:15.560 --> 01:30:28.560
[Guest]: is that the fundamental challenge for us is how do we move our education system from a filtration system to a human development system that's able to add human capital to children at every part of the distribution and allow you to be better than where you were yesterday,

01:30:28.560 --> 01:30:34.560
[Guest]: as opposed to kind of chasing this ranking system, because that's a zero-sum game.

01:30:34.560 --> 01:30:36.560
[Guest]: Rank, by definition, is zero-sum, right?

01:30:36.560 --> 01:30:39.560
[Guest]: You know, and you then create the pressure without creating the education.

01:30:39.560 --> 01:30:46.560
[Guest]: So, you know, I've said a lot there, so let me just take a pause and, you know, let you come in on what you would like me to elaborate on.

01:30:46.560 --> 01:30:49.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, I've been listening with rapt fascination.

01:30:49.560 --> 01:30:50.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm a running temptation, Jay.

01:30:50.560 --> 01:30:53.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm your bungalow, but it's okay.

01:30:53.560 --> 01:31:02.560
[Amit Varma]: I won't burden my readers with a minute of bungalow after your minute of Tamil, which was most charming, by the way, if I was a student in your class, that would have been the high point of my class.

01:31:02.560 --> 01:31:03.560
[Amit Varma]: So what are you talking about?

01:31:03.560 --> 01:31:09.560
[Amit Varma]: But let me unpack some of what you just said, and you can tell me if I understood it correctly and if I'm summarizing it okay.

01:31:09.560 --> 01:31:13.560
[Amit Varma]: Number one, I want to go back to the slight detour you took, which I don't think is a detour.

01:31:13.560 --> 01:31:17.560
[Amit Varma]: I think in many ways is central if we want to get ahead, which is the role of research.

01:31:17.560 --> 01:31:25.560
[Amit Varma]: Where, I mean, something that you have spoken about in the past, of course, is the difficulty of research in social science, where there are so many variables.

01:31:25.560 --> 01:31:38.560
[Amit Varma]: My guest Shruti Rajgopalan once put this very well when she said that, you know, in the hard sciences, let's say, if you want to, you know, test the proposition about whether putting a coin in a body of water will displace water or not.

01:31:38.560 --> 01:31:43.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, you can take a jug of water, put it there, you can measure where it is, put the coin in and you can measure it again.

01:31:43.560 --> 01:31:50.560
[Amit Varma]: But in the social sciences, you're basically there's a swimming pool with a hundred people swimming inside and splashing inside and you're throwing a coin in there.

01:31:50.560 --> 01:32:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And then you're trying to come up with, you know, was this an effective intervention? And, and, you know, like you said, that, you know, bad studies, which can, you know, put mistake correlation for causation can often sort of go wrong there.

01:32:04.560 --> 01:32:15.560
[Amit Varma]: And what has sort of begun to happen in the last 20 years and why your three esteemed friends and teachers got the Nobel Prize was talking about randomized control trials and how even within the social sciences,

01:32:15.560 --> 01:32:20.560
[Amit Varma]: there is a role for doing well-designed studies, which can throw light on certain things.

01:32:20.560 --> 01:32:24.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, I was struck by a couple of those studies, which you cited in your papers, like number one.

01:32:24.560 --> 01:32:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing about many of these studies is that they threaten conventional wisdom.

01:32:30.560 --> 01:32:34.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, what happens if you, if social science research is all muddy and you can't get any conclusions?

01:32:34.560 --> 01:32:41.560
[Amit Varma]: Conventional wisdom tends to propagate itself and, you know, become hardwired into the way we think about education.

01:32:41.560 --> 01:32:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And you pointed to a couple of studies, which actually challenged conventional wisdom.

01:32:45.560 --> 01:32:51.560
[Amit Varma]: One was there was conventional wisdom that one laptop per child would actually improve learning outcomes for children and all of that.

01:32:51.560 --> 01:32:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And it just seemed so intuitive and obvious that no one really bothered to test it until someone did test it in Peru, as you pointed out.

01:32:58.560 --> 01:33:03.560
[Amit Varma]: And they found that it had absolutely no impact, which is counterintuitive, but there you are.

01:33:03.560 --> 01:33:10.560
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, you referred to the study in Indonesia, where teacher salaries were doubled and no impact at all on outcomes.

01:33:10.560 --> 01:33:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, why is this important? What is important here, which I kind of want to stress and I think is an enormous point that you made,

01:33:18.560 --> 01:33:25.560
[Amit Varma]: is that it is not to say that giving a laptop to every child is not desirable or that paying teachers well is not desirable.

01:33:25.560 --> 01:33:29.560
[Amit Varma]: It is to say that our resources are limited. There are limited things that we can do with them.

01:33:29.560 --> 01:33:36.560
[Amit Varma]: There is a scarcity of resources. And especially because this task is so mission critical, because we need to educate our children.

01:33:36.560 --> 01:33:43.560
[Amit Varma]: It has a moral dimension. Therefore, we need to focus on how best we can use the limited money available to us.

01:33:43.560 --> 01:33:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And the central, the sort of core thinking of the Indian state over the decades of this has been a focus on inputs,

01:33:51.560 --> 01:33:55.560
[Amit Varma]: like even the RTE, which we can discuss in detail when we get to private schools.

01:33:55.560 --> 01:34:00.560
[Amit Varma]: But even there, the focus is on inputs. How much are we paying teachers?

01:34:00.560 --> 01:34:03.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, how are the buildings? How many toilets are there? Is there a playground?

01:34:03.560 --> 01:34:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And as you have pointed out in a phrase, which I found very telling, these are neither necessary nor sufficient.

01:34:09.560 --> 01:34:16.560
[Amit Varma]: And the research shows that. So it is no longer a question of coming from a particular ideology, say, you know,

01:34:16.560 --> 01:34:22.560
[Amit Varma]: a socialist ideology versus an anarchist ideology or whatever, and saying that, no, this is bad, that is wrong.

01:34:22.560 --> 01:34:28.560
[Amit Varma]: But what you are doing is you're saying that, one, these things matter. And two, now we can measure these things.

01:34:28.560 --> 01:34:36.560
[Amit Varma]: So let's measure them. And let's sort of design interventions accordingly, because we have limited amount of money to play with.

01:34:36.560 --> 01:34:40.560
[Amit Varma]: So we need to know what works and what doesn't work. And I think that's a profoundly important point,

01:34:40.560 --> 01:34:44.560
[Amit Varma]: because when we think of state action, we often take a lot of things for granted.

01:34:44.560 --> 01:34:50.560
[Amit Varma]: We assume that the money is unlimited. And, you know, we also assume that just increasing imports,

01:34:50.560 --> 01:34:55.560
[Amit Varma]: or everybody will talk about how we should spend a greater percentage of GDP on education.

01:34:55.560 --> 01:35:00.560
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, spending more is not enough. What are you spending it on? What are the outcomes you're getting?

01:35:00.560 --> 01:35:04.560
[Amit Varma]: Those are extremely important, as you've pointed out. And the other point that you made,

01:35:04.560 --> 01:35:09.560
[Amit Varma]: and in fact, that graph, if listeners go to cnunc.in, on the show notes of the episode page,

01:35:09.560 --> 01:35:13.560
[Amit Varma]: I'll actually reproduce the graph, because it is a very powerful graph.

01:35:13.560 --> 01:35:18.560
[Amit Varma]: And what the graph basically shows is two things, that number one, you know,

01:35:18.560 --> 01:35:21.560
[Amit Varma]: we are not meeting the outcomes that we should be meeting.

01:35:21.560 --> 01:35:26.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, one recent example of this that you've given from Pratham's annual status of education report,

01:35:26.560 --> 01:35:31.560
[Amit Varma]: what is called ASER report is, I'll quote from your, something that you've written, where you said,

01:35:31.560 --> 01:35:35.560
[Amit Varma]: quote, data from Pratham's annual status of education report shows that A,

01:35:35.560 --> 01:35:40.560
[Amit Varma]: half the children in rural India cannot read at a second grade level after five years of schooling.

01:35:40.560 --> 01:35:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And B, the large increases in education spending in this period have not led to meaningful improvements in these outcomes.

01:35:47.560 --> 01:35:51.560
[Amit Varma]: And people can look at inputs and say that, hey, we spend so much more,

01:35:51.560 --> 01:35:54.560
[Amit Varma]: we are doing something about education, but not if you don't focus on outcomes.

01:35:54.560 --> 01:35:59.560
[Amit Varma]: And your graph is powerful because not only does it not show that we are nowhere near those outcomes,

01:35:59.560 --> 01:36:05.560
[Amit Varma]: like a fifth standard kid doesn't have anywhere near the fifth standard proficiency that you should have.

01:36:05.560 --> 01:36:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But I was very interested in just that visual depiction of the range of outcomes in that fifth standard,

01:36:12.560 --> 01:36:17.560
[Amit Varma]: where if on a scale of 1 to 10, 10 is that you are where a fifth standard kid should be,

01:36:17.560 --> 01:36:19.560
[Amit Varma]: and 1 is, you know, nothing at all.

01:36:19.560 --> 01:36:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And that there are just a massive number of people all the way between 10 and 1, even at 1, 2, 3, 4.

01:36:25.560 --> 01:36:31.560
[Amit Varma]: And that also explains to me that other big puzzle for which I entirely blame the state,

01:36:31.560 --> 01:36:38.560
[Amit Varma]: which is that there is this really bewildering gap between supply and demand when it comes to the workforce.

01:36:38.560 --> 01:36:41.560
[Amit Varma]: In the sense that, yes, of course, there is a jobs crisis in India,

01:36:41.560 --> 01:36:46.560
[Amit Varma]: but it is also true that most of the people who get an education there do not have any skills.

01:36:46.560 --> 01:36:51.560
[Amit Varma]: They are useless. Why is that gap there? Is this not a problem we need to solve?

01:36:51.560 --> 01:36:55.560
[Amit Varma]: You forget the people who don't get educated, the people who are finishing their 10th,

01:36:55.560 --> 01:37:00.560
[Amit Varma]: who are getting graduate degrees, postgraduate degrees, have no skills.

01:37:00.560 --> 01:37:05.560
[Amit Varma]: They are unemployable. And, you know, what you said about the way the whole system works,

01:37:05.560 --> 01:37:10.560
[Amit Varma]: the emphasis on rote learning, and the fact that, you know, in that fifth standard class,

01:37:10.560 --> 01:37:14.560
[Amit Varma]: the guys who are on 10 or 9, they are okay, they'll understand what the teacher is saying.

01:37:14.560 --> 01:37:19.560
[Amit Varma]: The guys who are at 1 or 2, they are like a kid listening to something in a foreign language,

01:37:19.560 --> 01:37:22.560
[Amit Varma]: or Tamil or Bengali, if they don't know those languages.

01:37:22.560 --> 01:37:26.560
[Amit Varma]: So it is a great sort of tragedy that we have to address,

01:37:26.560 --> 01:37:30.560
[Amit Varma]: which you so eloquently explained just now and in all of these papers.

01:37:30.560 --> 01:37:35.560
[Amit Varma]: So two questions. One, is there recognition of this within the policymaking world?

01:37:35.560 --> 01:37:42.560
[Amit Varma]: And number two, what are the kind of ways that you have recommended that we can actually improve the system?

01:37:42.560 --> 01:37:49.560
[Amit Varma]: Given, number one, the core issue that, you know, we are optimized for filtration rather than education.

01:37:49.560 --> 01:37:52.560
[Amit Varma]: We are sorting instead of teaching all the kids left behind.

01:37:52.560 --> 01:37:56.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this is almost most child's left behind, right? You would call this.

01:37:56.560 --> 01:38:01.560
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, we are optimizing wrong, we are optimizing for sorting versus human development.

01:38:01.560 --> 01:38:02.560
[Amit Varma]: How can we correct that?

01:38:02.560 --> 01:38:07.560
[Amit Varma]: And number two, how do we change the mindset where inputs are considered so extremely important,

01:38:07.560 --> 01:38:09.560
[Amit Varma]: but like you pointed out, they're not.

01:38:09.560 --> 01:38:13.560
[Amit Varma]: Private schools who pay their teachers one-fifth or one-tenth, you know, do so much better.

01:38:13.560 --> 01:38:17.560
[Amit Varma]: And the other big point I'd make there, of course, is that the difference is not private or public.

01:38:17.560 --> 01:38:20.560
[Amit Varma]: The difference is in incentives, you know.

01:38:20.560 --> 01:38:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And that's also something policymakers perhaps don't consider enough.

01:38:25.560 --> 01:38:28.560
[Amit Varma]: So I think I've asked you too many questions.

01:38:28.560 --> 01:38:32.560
[Guest]: No, no, I mean, I think like, you know, this is, you know, we could easily go for six hours

01:38:32.560 --> 01:38:35.560
[Guest]: and break a record of like, you know, the longest show you've done.

01:38:35.560 --> 01:38:40.560
[Guest]: So, yeah, let me just, I think, agree with and reinforce a couple of the important points you made, right?

01:38:40.560 --> 01:38:42.560
[Guest]: When you talk about the role of the research.

01:38:42.560 --> 01:38:46.560
[Guest]: And I said this in my op-ed, you know, commemorating the Nobel Prize and going back to the private sector.

01:38:46.560 --> 01:38:52.560
[Guest]: See, as an economist, I don't worry so much about how Toyota produces its cars or how Maruti produces its cars.

01:38:52.560 --> 01:38:59.560
[Guest]: And the reason is that you face market prices for your inputs and you face market prices on them on the product side, right?

01:38:59.560 --> 01:39:05.560
[Guest]: Which means that if you are inefficient, right, on either how you're sourcing or kind of how you're pricing

01:39:05.560 --> 01:39:08.560
[Guest]: or how you're able to compete in the market, you'll be competed out of business.

01:39:08.560 --> 01:39:12.560
[Guest]: OK, so, you know, so there's a natural selection process by which you have to be efficient.

01:39:12.560 --> 01:39:15.560
[Guest]: And the efficiency is rewarded in terms of profitability.

01:39:15.560 --> 01:39:21.560
[Guest]: Right. So and there is something just relentlessly beautiful about the private sector and scale where, you know,

01:39:21.560 --> 01:39:24.560
[Guest]: if a McDonald's manage, it's easy, it's pilloried for being cookie cutter.

01:39:24.560 --> 01:39:29.560
[Guest]: But if you manage to improve, like, you know, the time efficiency of a process by two seconds

01:39:29.560 --> 01:39:33.560
[Guest]: and multiply that by the number of burgers or number of fries you serve, right?

01:39:33.560 --> 01:39:35.560
[Guest]: I mean, the implication of that for the bottom line is enormous.

01:39:35.560 --> 01:39:40.560
[Guest]: OK, so a Toyota has a Kaizen like approach to management, which is to say continuous improvement.

01:39:40.560 --> 01:39:44.560
[Guest]: And let's keep on finding out epsilon ways in which you can improve things.

01:39:44.560 --> 01:39:48.560
[Guest]: And that multiplied by the sheer scale of what you do is going to give you big returns. Right.

01:39:48.560 --> 01:39:54.560
[Guest]: Now, the fundamental problem in the public sector is that you can spend other people's money badly for a very long time.

01:39:54.560 --> 01:39:59.560
[Guest]: Right. Because there is no market test. And so essentially, what do you spend on?

01:39:59.560 --> 01:40:04.560
[Guest]: You know, the bureaucrat's goal is typically how do I minimize my kind of.

01:40:04.560 --> 01:40:10.560
[Guest]: So even the best intention bureaucrat has, you know, has limitations in terms of time horizon,

01:40:10.560 --> 01:40:14.560
[Guest]: has limitations in terms of the technical knowledge and capacity that's available on these things,

01:40:14.560 --> 01:40:18.560
[Guest]: and is also responding mainly to the pressure groups around.

01:40:18.560 --> 01:40:22.560
[Guest]: And so it's a it's a basic function of the politics of what is visible.

01:40:22.560 --> 01:40:25.560
[Guest]: Right. That you end up focusing on imports because the inputs are visible.

01:40:25.560 --> 01:40:30.560
[Guest]: You can have a school building. You can have a politician go cut a ribbon and saying, like,

01:40:30.560 --> 01:40:34.560
[Guest]: look, we have built a school for you and, you know, and coming to laptops. Right.

01:40:34.560 --> 01:40:38.560
[Guest]: So it's actually when I give I have this whole paper on technology education, in fact, which is in the AER,

01:40:38.560 --> 01:40:43.560
[Guest]: which kind of highlights and I'll just build on that example a little bit and then come back to the

01:40:43.560 --> 01:40:47.560
[Guest]: the politics point, right, which is what we find is that so here are these studies with one laptop

01:40:47.560 --> 01:40:52.560
[Guest]: a child that have zero impact. Right. On the other hand, we've gotten incredibly optimistic results

01:40:52.560 --> 01:40:57.560
[Guest]: from a study we did in Delhi using an Indian developed software called MindSpark. Right.

01:40:57.560 --> 01:41:00.560
[Guest]: And the key is this is a company based in Ahmedabad, now in Bangalore, you know,

01:41:00.560 --> 01:41:05.560
[Guest]: and they have spent 15 years developing a bunch of assessment products and over the years have kind of,

01:41:05.560 --> 01:41:10.560
[Guest]: you know, built this online tech platform. But the key is that because they have millions of data points

01:41:10.560 --> 01:41:15.560
[Guest]: and kids, they are able to calibrate your learning level and customize your instruction to exactly where you are.

01:41:15.560 --> 01:41:20.560
[Guest]: Right. And what we see is that that program gave you stunning improvements that within five months of exposure,

01:41:20.560 --> 01:41:24.560
[Guest]: we saw bigger gains than in other programs over five years. OK.

01:41:24.560 --> 01:41:31.560
[Guest]: And the main reason is that it's because it's able to customize instruction and actually achieve this human development paradigm.

01:41:31.560 --> 01:41:36.560
[Guest]: Right. As opposed to the sorting paradigm. Right. So the good news is that that's incredibly effective.

01:41:36.560 --> 01:41:43.560
[Guest]: The bad news is if you go look at the national ed tech policy, the national ed tech policy is still fundamentally an input and procurement policy.

01:41:43.560 --> 01:41:49.560
[Guest]: Right. It's OK. Everything is based on estimating budgets for how many computers, how many schools, how many this thing.

01:41:49.560 --> 01:41:54.560
[Guest]: And again, you can't blame them because if you go to, you know, whether it's not to pick favorites across states,

01:41:54.560 --> 01:41:59.560
[Guest]: this was true in Tamil Nadu, this was true in UP, that when the chief ministers announced the laptop programs,

01:41:59.560 --> 01:42:02.560
[Guest]: the most important thing they wanted was to put their photo on it. Right.

01:42:02.560 --> 01:42:07.560
[Guest]: So the Tamil Nadu laptop program had Jayalalithaa's photo on it. The UP laptop program is even better.

01:42:07.560 --> 01:42:11.560
[Guest]: It had like, I think, 30 seconds of Samajwadi Party propaganda, like in the login.

01:42:11.560 --> 01:42:15.560
[Guest]: You know, like when you come in, you see, you know, you see Akhilesh Yadav smiling and giving it to you.

01:42:15.560 --> 01:42:18.560
[Guest]: And of course, then there was an aftermarket in getting rid of the software. Right.

01:42:18.560 --> 01:42:23.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, but the point is, but the point is that politics is about what is visible. Right.

01:42:23.560 --> 01:42:27.560
[Guest]: And that's kind of what makes service delivery such a vexing problem. Right.

01:42:27.560 --> 01:42:34.560
[Guest]: That our usual machinery of democratic accountability rewards what is visible and, you know, the seen and the unseen. Right.

01:42:34.560 --> 01:42:39.560
[Guest]: So the seen is the input. The unseen is the outcome. Right. Because you don't measure this.

01:42:39.560 --> 01:42:48.560
[Guest]: And so, which is why in many ways, the most important contribution of research and kind of, you know, public interest work is just good measurement. Right.

01:42:48.560 --> 01:42:53.560
[Guest]: So there's this wonderful example from Rukmini Banerjee. Right. So 15 years, Pratham has been doing this work on learning outcomes.

01:42:53.560 --> 01:42:59.560
[Guest]: And in fact, one of my colleagues, Abhijit Singh, has this beautiful new paper on administrative data integrity. Right.

01:42:59.560 --> 01:43:05.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, where he shows that if you go look at the official measurement of learning outcomes and then do an independent audit of that,

01:43:05.560 --> 01:43:09.560
[Guest]: you'll find that the true learning level is less than half of what is reported in the official data. Right.

01:43:09.560 --> 01:43:13.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, because everybody has an incentive to inflate these outcomes.

01:43:13.560 --> 01:43:18.560
[Guest]: So Rukmini has this great story where I think she I can't remember if she said it in a conference, if she wrote it in an op-ed.

01:43:18.560 --> 01:43:24.560
[Guest]: But, you know, I think she went to a village somewhere. And again, she goes to schools, tests kids, and they can't do anything.

01:43:24.560 --> 01:43:29.560
[Guest]: And she goes to the Gram Pradhan and saying, do you know that your children can't read? And the Pradhan refuses to believe it.

01:43:29.560 --> 01:43:33.560
[Guest]: And then she takes the Pradhan and shows them like, you know, that this is what the learning levels are.

01:43:33.560 --> 01:43:38.560
[Guest]: And then there's an education department functionary or maybe it's a teacher who gets very upset at her.

01:43:38.560 --> 01:43:43.560
[Guest]: And apparently this is wonderful line. He says, Madam, aapko asliyat se itni lagav kyu hai?

01:43:43.560 --> 01:43:54.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, so humaari kahaani chal rahi hai, like, you know, school ban raha hai, like, you know, teacher appointment, bache ja rahe hain.

01:43:54.560 --> 01:43:59.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, I mean, so why do you want to come and puncture this balloon with this pesky thing called reality?

01:43:59.560 --> 01:44:04.560
[Amit Varma]: Let me translate that for the readers. Aapko asliyat se lagav kyu hai means why are you so attached to reality?

01:44:04.560 --> 01:44:14.560
[Guest]: But it kind of then goes back to how some of the most important contributions of research and this thing is just measurement, right?

01:44:14.560 --> 01:44:22.560
[Guest]: That if you kind of, you know, in a world where marketing has kind of taken over substance in so many areas, right, like, you know, that, you know, to insist.

01:44:22.560 --> 01:44:27.560
[Guest]: And, you know, again, when I come to research, come to this thing, you still want to be able to market and present the insights.

01:44:27.560 --> 01:44:32.560
[Guest]: But you need the substance of that first, which is why I spent five years before I come and do any presentation after learning what's going on.

01:44:32.560 --> 01:44:38.560
[Guest]: Right. But, you know, but it just highlights going back to the politics of all of this that has the lesson been learned.

01:44:38.560 --> 01:44:48.560
[Guest]: And I think, you know, when I go to the IAS Academy in Missouri, right, I'll find many, many thoughtful IAS officers will come after my seminars and saying, you know, this was wonderful.

01:44:48.560 --> 01:44:52.560
[Guest]: We agree with everything you said. Like, you know, can you please come and help us do something in our states? Right.

01:44:52.560 --> 01:44:58.560
[Guest]: So there are multiple chief ministers, multiple, you know, education ministers, secretaries who will be motivated and try to do something.

01:44:58.560 --> 01:45:04.560
[Guest]: The problem is, and this is why, you know, I have this whole book, which I'm working on, which I won't even give away the title.

01:45:04.560 --> 01:45:11.560
[Guest]: It'll be out next year. But it's this kind of it's my 20 year arc of kind of trying to improve the Indian state, right, on different aspects.

01:45:11.560 --> 01:45:16.560
[Guest]: But one of the challenges that even the best intentioned people like, you know, will have tenure of two years or three years. Right.

01:45:16.560 --> 01:45:26.560
[Guest]: So which means that the time horizon you have means that even the highest quality bureaucrat can at best create a new scheme, get it funded and get it rolled out.

01:45:26.560 --> 01:45:32.560
[Guest]: So the metric of success that's available is fundamentally an input based metric, right, that you get to show in your time frame.

01:45:32.560 --> 01:45:40.560
[Guest]: Whereas getting these outcomes improved are kind of wicked problems, right, that take a generational investment, five, 10, 15 years.

01:45:40.560 --> 01:45:46.560
[Guest]: And these are just incredibly difficult. In fact, you know, every time I go to MHRD and go to the secretary elementary education's office,

01:45:46.560 --> 01:45:52.560
[Guest]: I kind of have a smile on my face because the first time I went there was 2001 when the education secretary was S.C. Tripathi.

01:45:52.560 --> 01:45:59.560
[Guest]: And then I look at the names on that board. Right. You know, there's been at least 10, if not more names in that period between then and now.

01:45:59.560 --> 01:46:04.560
[Guest]: And whereas, like, you know, those of us who are in the weeds are there thinking about this long term basis.

01:46:04.560 --> 01:46:09.560
[Guest]: So, you know, and so this is a tangent that maybe we should just do a complete second show on this, which is, you know,

01:46:09.560 --> 01:46:14.560
[Guest]: why so much of my policy engagement these days is done with the states. Right.

01:46:14.560 --> 01:46:18.560
[Guest]: And, you know, I've kind of I talk to I've always provided inputs to the planning commission.

01:46:18.560 --> 01:46:26.560
[Guest]: I am an informal honorary advisor at NITI Aayog. But again, in practice, where I find the highest return on investment of time spent is in the states,

01:46:26.560 --> 01:46:29.560
[Guest]: because, you know, education is a state subject and there are states that are trying a bunch of things.

01:46:29.560 --> 01:46:32.560
[Guest]: So let's maybe that's a good pivot to then talk about.

01:46:32.560 --> 01:46:36.560
[Guest]: So I think all I've done here is clarify why these issues are so difficult. Right.

01:46:36.560 --> 01:46:41.560
[Guest]: That it's easy to spend taxpayer money badly, other people's money, like everybody wants to spend other people's money.

01:46:41.560 --> 01:46:44.560
[Guest]: Right. Like, you know, so that then goes back to the coercion,

01:46:44.560 --> 01:46:49.560
[Guest]: which is why I sometimes get nervous when the government talks about raising tax revenue, because I don't want to raise tax revenue

01:46:49.560 --> 01:46:54.560
[Guest]: till I can be assured in the quality of expenditure. But and this is a dominant theme in a lot of my work, where, in fact,

01:46:54.560 --> 01:46:58.560
[Guest]: I think we need more public spending. We need more public kind of provision.

01:46:58.560 --> 01:47:02.560
[Guest]: But the efficiency is so low, like I mean, that I kind of that I wonder, right.

01:47:02.560 --> 01:47:04.560
[Guest]: You know, that often there are more efficient ways.

01:47:04.560 --> 01:47:07.560
[Guest]: And I'll come back and talk about this with a very concrete example of early childhood education.

01:47:07.560 --> 01:47:10.560
[Guest]: So, yeah. So I think my bottom line is I agree with you.

01:47:10.560 --> 01:47:14.560
[Guest]: I've tried to clarify for your listeners two or three additional concepts about why, you know,

01:47:14.560 --> 01:47:17.560
[Guest]: value for money in the public sector is so difficult because you're spending somebody else's money.

01:47:17.560 --> 01:47:21.560
[Guest]: Why the politics of kind of visible the seen and the unseen.

01:47:21.560 --> 01:47:23.560
[Guest]: I'd not even planned that, but it's beautiful. Right.

01:47:23.560 --> 01:47:26.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, because what is seen is the inputs and what is unseen are the outcomes.

01:47:26.560 --> 01:47:30.560
[Guest]: And so, you know, you will naturally focus on what is seen.

01:47:30.560 --> 01:47:38.560
[Guest]: And then the last part is that the issues in terms of the time horizon and the nature of some of the reforms that are needed are so complex

01:47:38.560 --> 01:47:41.560
[Guest]: that they cannot be done just by an education secretary. Right.

01:47:41.560 --> 01:47:45.560
[Guest]: So if you want to change aspects of recruitment, you know, you need coordination with finance,

01:47:45.560 --> 01:47:48.560
[Guest]: you need coordination with other parts. And let me also, since anecdotes are so powerful,

01:47:48.560 --> 01:47:52.560
[Guest]: just like the asliyat se itni lagav kyu hai, let me give you one more true anecdote. Right.

01:47:52.560 --> 01:47:55.560
[Guest]: And I won't give you the year because that will give away the person. Right.

01:47:55.560 --> 01:48:02.560
[Guest]: But, you know, the other problem in government is that individual line departments typically have zero incentive for cost effectiveness.

01:48:02.560 --> 01:48:06.560
[Guest]: Right. Because what they're trying to do is maximize the budgetary allocation that they get.

01:48:06.560 --> 01:48:11.560
[Guest]: And a very senior education department official once looked at some of my work and actually with a straight face said,

01:48:11.560 --> 01:48:17.560
[Guest]: your research is going to hurt education because the finance ministry is going to use your research to cut my budget.

01:48:17.560 --> 01:48:21.560
[Guest]: OK. And because you're showing that we can do this at lower money.

01:48:21.560 --> 01:48:25.560
[Guest]: And I'm like, you know, sir or ma'am, I won't even reveal that. Right.

01:48:25.560 --> 01:48:30.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, that I want to keep your budget the same. If anything, I would like to increase your budget.

01:48:30.560 --> 01:48:35.560
[Guest]: But I cannot in good conscience make that case when there is so much inefficiency in your expenditure. Right.

01:48:35.560 --> 01:48:39.560
[Guest]: So and I want to connect back to a very important point you made, which is, I think,

01:48:39.560 --> 01:48:47.560
[Guest]: one of the source of tension between activists and economists is, you know, the activists kind of there is a large sanctimonious left in this country.

01:48:47.560 --> 01:48:51.560
[Guest]: Right. Like, you know, I mean, that believes that we need the state to do more of everything.

01:48:51.560 --> 01:48:54.560
[Guest]: And think about the economists as being counting scrooges who say like, you know,

01:48:54.560 --> 01:48:56.560
[Guest]: Iske le pesa nahi, uske le pesa nahi. Right.

01:48:56.560 --> 01:49:03.560
[Guest]: But I think the point is that in a world of limited resources, cost effectiveness is not just an economic convenience.

01:49:03.560 --> 01:49:06.560
[Guest]: It's a moral imperative. Right. It's a moral imperative.

01:49:06.560 --> 01:49:11.560
[Guest]: Precisely, like you said, because these problems in terms of human development, whether it's malnutrition,

01:49:11.560 --> 01:49:15.560
[Guest]: whether it's learning outcomes are so pressing that in a world of limited resources,

01:49:15.560 --> 01:49:25.560
[Guest]: it is kind of morally unacceptable to not put cost effectiveness at the center or at least give it a very high weight in how you allocate scarce public resources.

01:49:25.560 --> 01:49:29.560
[Guest]: And, you know, that's kind of a unifying principle that informs a lot of my work.

01:49:29.560 --> 01:49:34.560
[Guest]: And the other thing I sometimes say, and again, you know, I have an entire three hour kind of lecture,

01:49:34.560 --> 01:49:41.560
[Guest]: just an education that I give to the top officials, is, you know, if you look at education outcomes and look at per capita income.

01:49:41.560 --> 01:49:44.560
[Guest]: Now, of course, there's a strong positive correlation. Right.

01:49:44.560 --> 01:49:50.560
[Guest]: But if you look at the countries that are big positive outliers, again, what you learn is that for any given level of per capita income,

01:49:50.560 --> 01:49:55.560
[Guest]: if I can pivot my public expenditure from things that are less cost effective to more cost effective,

01:49:55.560 --> 01:50:00.560
[Guest]: you can deliver much better outcomes at any given level of fiscal and administrative capacity.

01:50:00.560 --> 01:50:04.560
[Guest]: And so, you know, and so let me just say very quickly what I think about the new education policy and then come back to,

01:50:04.560 --> 01:50:06.560
[Guest]: you know, my own views and kind of policy way forward.

01:50:06.560 --> 01:50:11.560
[Guest]: See, I think the new education policy on public schools is for the most part an excellent document.

01:50:11.560 --> 01:50:17.560
[Guest]: I think the process was good. I think they solicited, they had a very, very extensive set of consultations.

01:50:17.560 --> 01:50:20.560
[Guest]: You know, I've gone and met with the chairman, met with the members.

01:50:20.560 --> 01:50:27.560
[Guest]: I have provided extensive written comments. And in fact, a lot of in fact, sometimes I worry that people like, you know, there's a plagiarism risk here.

01:50:27.560 --> 01:50:35.560
[Guest]: Like there's a side story about that, which is I have provided the same set of inputs into the committee and also put that in my, you know, this paper in the Banerjee Rajan book.

01:50:35.560 --> 01:50:40.560
[Guest]: So I think some of the language, including in foundational literacy numeracy, has been taken verbatim, like, you know, from from what I've said.

01:50:40.560 --> 01:50:44.560
[Guest]: So I feel very happy about that. OK, so at that level, I think it's a good document.

01:50:44.560 --> 01:50:47.560
[Guest]: It recognizes the centrality of foundational literacy numeracy.

01:50:47.560 --> 01:50:56.560
[Guest]: And I said this, I said, if you do nothing else as a country in the next five years, then make sure that every child who is today coming to class one is able to be functionally literate and numerate.

01:50:56.560 --> 01:50:59.560
[Guest]: You would have done more for this country as an education system than we've done in 70 years.

01:50:59.560 --> 01:51:10.560
[Guest]: OK, and that's because what my data also shows is that if by class three, if you haven't reached foundational literacy numeracy, that's when there's an inflection point where the additional time in school is almost kind of irrelevant.

01:51:10.560 --> 01:51:17.560
[Guest]: Right. And going back to some of the skilling points, I think it's Manish Sabharwal who once said that the best skilling program for India is a better school education system,

01:51:17.560 --> 01:51:22.560
[Guest]: because by the time you get to skilling and vocation, it's already too late because the building blocks are not there.

01:51:22.560 --> 01:51:30.560
[Guest]: OK, so I think the NEP in that sense is an excellent document in the sense that it is moving away from the input based dogma of the RTE.

01:51:30.560 --> 01:51:37.560
[Guest]: It correctly identifies the priorities. And I think a lot of the ideas in there, I think, are incredibly sensible.

01:51:37.560 --> 01:51:42.560
[Guest]: I think the big blind spot, again, is I'm not seeing enough discussion of cost effectiveness.

01:51:42.560 --> 01:51:47.560
[Guest]: Right. So and there is this kind of general sense, OK, we need 6 percent of GDP to get this.

01:51:47.560 --> 01:51:55.560
[Guest]: And that's maybe like, you know, as with all of these things that are produced by committee, it's because when you are an educationist, you feel that you're kind of, you know,

01:51:55.560 --> 01:52:04.560
[Guest]: it's amazing how much of the international aid community for education of any sector measures their success by resources raised and will not ask about what are the opportunity costs of those funds.

01:52:04.560 --> 01:52:09.560
[Guest]: Right. In other sectors. Right. So it becomes the holy grail, therefore, to come and ask for 6 percent.

01:52:09.560 --> 01:52:14.560
[Guest]: And my own view is given where we are as a country in terms of tax to GDP ratio, we don't have that kind of money.

01:52:14.560 --> 01:52:19.560
[Guest]: And given what we know about how much inefficiency there is in the status quo,

01:52:19.560 --> 01:52:26.560
[Guest]: that I would have liked to see much more emphasis also on just cost effectiveness and how do you deliver these goals in a cost effective way.

01:52:26.560 --> 01:52:31.560
[Guest]: But that's, I think, my main quibble. Now, there's another issue with regard to how you deal with private schools.

01:52:31.560 --> 01:52:36.560
[Guest]: And I'll come to that later. But, you know, as an aspirational document, I think the NEP is excellent.

01:52:36.560 --> 01:52:40.560
[Guest]: I think it says all the right things and there's very little to disagree with it substantively, I think.

01:52:40.560 --> 01:52:44.560
[Guest]: But what it is, what says a lot less on is the how.

01:52:44.560 --> 01:52:52.560
[Guest]: And that how then requires engaging with the nitty gritty of the state that we have with its limited fiscal and administrative resources.

01:52:52.560 --> 01:52:56.560
[Guest]: And then how do you make this happen? Right. So that's kind of my big picture take on the NEP.

01:52:56.560 --> 01:53:02.560
[Guest]: And maybe that's a good point to then segue into maybe four or five or six, depending on time, very specific policy ideas.

01:53:02.560 --> 01:53:04.560
[Amit Varma]: Right. You know, that I feel can be implemented.

01:53:04.560 --> 01:53:08.560
[Amit Varma]: Before we do that, let me quickly, once again, unpack some of this.

01:53:08.560 --> 01:53:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And I'll, of course, come back to the NEP. And I have a couple of further questions on that.

01:53:12.560 --> 01:53:16.560
[Amit Varma]: But you mentioned the sanctimonious left, so to say, the activist versus economist.

01:53:16.560 --> 01:53:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And one of the big mistakes I find the sanctimonious left, so to say, often making is giving importance to intention over outcome.

01:53:25.560 --> 01:53:30.560
[Amit Varma]: If there is a policy which has a good intention, then they just judge it on that and they don't actually see the outcome.

01:53:30.560 --> 01:53:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And the point is, there are many good intention policies which lead to terrible outcomes.

01:53:34.560 --> 01:53:40.560
[Amit Varma]: It's the seen and the unseen. That's what we've, you know, routinely seen over the decades, like the labor laws, for example,

01:53:40.560 --> 01:53:44.560
[Amit Varma]: or like much of what is happening in education, like the Right to Education Act, for example,

01:53:44.560 --> 01:53:48.560
[Amit Varma]: which we can also discuss when we come to private schools.

01:53:48.560 --> 01:53:52.560
[Amit Varma]: And what you were talking about, you know, the bureaucrat saying that, oh, this will harm education,

01:53:52.560 --> 01:54:00.560
[Amit Varma]: because actually it would have harmed his or her budget was very sort of telling for me because it reminded me of Parkinson's Law.

01:54:00.560 --> 01:54:04.560
[Amit Varma]: So Parkinson's Law, C. Northcote Parkinson wrote this book called Parkinson's Law.

01:54:04.560 --> 01:54:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And Parkinson's Law basically is that, you know, a work expands to fill the time available,

01:54:09.560 --> 01:54:12.560
[Amit Varma]: which often explains why I get so little done.

01:54:12.560 --> 01:54:17.560
[Amit Varma]: But the corollary for this for bureaucracies is that bureaucrats just want to maximize their own budgets.

01:54:17.560 --> 01:54:21.560
[Amit Varma]: They don't care about anything. You want to grow your department and the number of people who report to you

01:54:21.560 --> 01:54:25.560
[Amit Varma]: and you want to grow your budgets. And that's the incentive and that's the game.

01:54:25.560 --> 01:54:29.560
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you brought up incentives, one with relevance to the bureaucrats, right?

01:54:29.560 --> 01:54:34.560
[Amit Varma]: If a bureaucrat is to plan ahead, if he's got tenure in a particular department for three years,

01:54:34.560 --> 01:54:36.560
[Amit Varma]: how does he show he has done something?

01:54:36.560 --> 01:54:41.560
[Amit Varma]: He cannot show outcomes because outcomes of good policy will happen 10 years, 15 years down the line

01:54:41.560 --> 01:54:44.560
[Amit Varma]: and cannot be easily attributed to any one policy.

01:54:44.560 --> 01:54:46.560
[Amit Varma]: So what does he show? He shows inputs.

01:54:46.560 --> 01:54:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And these sort of bad incentives then become a problem within the system.

01:54:50.560 --> 01:54:56.560
[Amit Varma]: And I would say, you know, politicians have the same kind of incentives where they are always catering for the next elections.

01:54:56.560 --> 01:55:02.560
[Amit Varma]: So not only are they catering to populist sentiments, which might be devoid of economic logic,

01:55:02.560 --> 01:55:05.560
[Amit Varma]: but they are also catering to short-termism.

01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:10.560
[Amit Varma]: So this kind of long-termism may not really have an impact.

01:55:10.560 --> 01:55:13.560
[Amit Varma]: A couple of quick questions about the NEP since you brought it up.

01:55:13.560 --> 01:55:16.560
[Guest]: Before you do that, you know, because I do want to kind of have one important nuance there.

01:55:16.560 --> 01:55:21.560
[Guest]: Because I think any discussion or comment that we make about the political time horizon

01:55:21.560 --> 01:55:24.560
[Guest]: can easily be interpreted as kind of an indictment of democracy.

01:55:24.560 --> 01:55:27.560
[Guest]: And, you know, I want to make sure that that's not the implication.

01:55:27.560 --> 01:55:30.560
[Guest]: But I think what we need to do a lot more hard work on, and again,

01:55:30.560 --> 01:55:33.560
[Guest]: I have a whole chapter in my book on the political economy of these reforms

01:55:33.560 --> 01:55:36.560
[Guest]: because all the well-intentioned ideas will not happen without thinking through

01:55:36.560 --> 01:55:39.560
[Guest]: how do you make this incentive compatible politically, right?

01:55:39.560 --> 01:55:42.560
[Guest]: So I think, you know, the answer is not to say, and it's very naive to kind of say,

01:55:42.560 --> 01:55:46.560
[Guest]: okay, look at, you know, successful states like China, South Korea, they all kind of develop,

01:55:46.560 --> 01:55:49.560
[Guest]: you know, under stronger leaders with longer time horizons.

01:55:49.560 --> 01:55:52.560
[Guest]: And that would be a big mistake because I think the biggest kind of, you know,

01:55:52.560 --> 01:55:55.560
[Guest]: the biggest disasters have also happened like under strongmen, right?

01:55:55.560 --> 01:55:57.560
[Guest]: You know, and as we've seen around the world.

01:55:57.560 --> 01:56:01.560
[Guest]: So I think the implication of this is not to say, okay, the limitations of democracy

01:56:01.560 --> 01:56:03.560
[Guest]: mean that the politicians are going to focus on inputs.

01:56:03.560 --> 01:56:07.560
[Guest]: The implication is how do you make democracy work better, right?

01:56:07.560 --> 01:56:10.560
[Guest]: And a key part of that, again, goes back to decentralization

01:56:10.560 --> 01:56:15.560
[Guest]: because if you look around the world, education is an incredibly local subject.

01:56:15.560 --> 01:56:19.560
[Guest]: And if you're voting for your local empowered mayor or local thing,

01:56:19.560 --> 01:56:23.560
[Guest]: essentially on your service delivery, then you're making your vote work better

01:56:23.560 --> 01:56:28.560
[Guest]: by kind of unbundling what the vote does so that your vote at the national election

01:56:28.560 --> 01:56:31.560
[Guest]: can be for functions that ideally sit at the level of a federal government,

01:56:31.560 --> 01:56:34.560
[Guest]: you know, issues of national security, issues of, you know,

01:56:34.560 --> 01:56:36.560
[Guest]: overall economic growth and national performance.

01:56:36.560 --> 01:56:38.560
[Guest]: And then there are issues that matter at the state level

01:56:38.560 --> 01:56:40.560
[Guest]: and service delivery should be sitting at the local level.

01:56:40.560 --> 01:56:42.560
[Guest]: So I just wanted to come in because, you know,

01:56:42.560 --> 01:56:46.560
[Guest]: it's very easy to interpret some of these frustrations of political incentives

01:56:46.560 --> 01:56:47.560
[Guest]: as kind of saying frustration of democracy.

01:56:47.560 --> 01:56:49.560
[Guest]: But the answer is not get rid of democracy.

01:56:49.560 --> 01:56:51.560
[Amit Varma]: The answer is make democracy work much better.

01:56:51.560 --> 01:56:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I couldn't agree with you more.

01:56:52.560 --> 01:56:56.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, to give into an authoritarian system is basically to give the state

01:56:56.560 --> 01:56:59.560
[Amit Varma]: endless power and we know what the incentives are there

01:56:59.560 --> 01:57:01.560
[Amit Varma]: and that's not going to end well.

01:57:01.560 --> 01:57:03.560
[Amit Varma]: So it's like someone said, democracy sucks,

01:57:03.560 --> 01:57:06.560
[Amit Varma]: but it's the best of all the bad systems we have available to us.

01:57:06.560 --> 01:57:08.560
[Amit Varma]: So we got to make it work.

01:57:08.560 --> 01:57:10.560
[Amit Varma]: And one way of making it work is to think about incentives.

01:57:10.560 --> 01:57:12.560
[Amit Varma]: Quick question on the NEP before I'll ask you to elaborate

01:57:12.560 --> 01:57:15.560
[Amit Varma]: on what your solutions for public schooling would be.

01:57:15.560 --> 01:57:18.560
[Amit Varma]: And if you have time, I have time and I think my listeners have time.

01:57:18.560 --> 01:57:20.560
[Amit Varma]: So we'd like to hear all of them in detail.

01:57:20.560 --> 01:57:23.560
[Amit Varma]: But before that, a quick question on the NEP.

01:57:23.560 --> 01:57:24.560
[Amit Varma]: A couple of quick questions.

01:57:24.560 --> 01:57:26.560
[Amit Varma]: One is, of course, my pet bugbear that, you know,

01:57:26.560 --> 01:57:30.560
[Amit Varma]: this whole mindset we have against allowing for-profit private schools.

01:57:30.560 --> 01:57:32.560
[Amit Varma]: Does the NEP address that in any way?

01:57:32.560 --> 01:57:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, the bugbear that both of us share,

01:57:34.560 --> 01:57:37.560
[Amit Varma]: but you have worked much more on and elaborated so well,

01:57:37.560 --> 01:57:43.560
[Amit Varma]: that does that sort of mental focus on inputs rather than outcomes?

01:57:43.560 --> 01:57:46.560
[Amit Varma]: Is there a change to that at that broader bird's eye level?

01:57:46.560 --> 01:57:49.560
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think, you know, so let me do the second one first

01:57:49.560 --> 01:57:51.560
[Guest]: and come back to for-profit when we talk about private schools.

01:57:51.560 --> 01:57:54.560
[Guest]: I think on the second point, the NEP does, I think, you know,

01:57:54.560 --> 01:57:56.560
[Guest]: by talking about a national testing agency,

01:57:56.560 --> 01:57:59.560
[Guest]: by talking about measuring learning outcomes at third, fifth, and eighth,

01:57:59.560 --> 01:58:02.560
[Guest]: it's already, I would say, a step function improvement from the RTE, right?

01:58:02.560 --> 01:58:04.560
[Guest]: Like, you know, which tried to kind of move away

01:58:04.560 --> 01:58:06.560
[Guest]: from testing and measurement altogether.

01:58:06.560 --> 01:58:08.560
[Guest]: You know, they had this very utopian idea

01:58:08.560 --> 01:58:10.560
[Guest]: of continuous and comprehensive assessment,

01:58:10.560 --> 01:58:12.560
[Guest]: which, I mean, again, to be fair to the RTE,

01:58:12.560 --> 01:58:15.560
[Guest]: like, you know, some of the ideas were absolutely spot on

01:58:15.560 --> 01:58:17.560
[Guest]: and not inconsistent with what I'm saying, right?

01:58:17.560 --> 01:58:20.560
[Guest]: Because what I'm saying about a human development paradigm,

01:58:20.560 --> 01:58:23.560
[Guest]: there is the sense that exams are fundamentally about sorting

01:58:23.560 --> 01:58:25.560
[Guest]: and that this continuous and comprehensive assessment

01:58:25.560 --> 01:58:28.560
[Guest]: would help better in terms of learning.

01:58:28.560 --> 01:58:30.560
[Guest]: The problem is you still need the exam

01:58:30.560 --> 01:58:34.560
[Guest]: as a way of providing objective feedback to the system, right?

01:58:34.560 --> 01:58:36.560
[Guest]: So it's not – the key is you don't want the test

01:58:36.560 --> 01:58:39.560
[Guest]: to be a test of the student as much as a test of the system, right?

01:58:39.560 --> 01:58:41.560
[Guest]: And that's a very important distinction, right?

01:58:41.560 --> 01:58:43.560
[Guest]: So you're not using the test in third or fifth standard

01:58:43.560 --> 01:58:45.560
[Guest]: to say, actually, I'm failing you, the student, right?

01:58:45.560 --> 01:58:47.560
[Guest]: It's more like saying, if my goal is to make sure

01:58:47.560 --> 01:58:49.560
[Guest]: every one of you pass an absolute standard,

01:58:49.560 --> 01:58:51.560
[Guest]: what do I need to do as a system, right,

01:58:51.560 --> 01:58:53.560
[Guest]: to give you the additional support needed

01:58:53.560 --> 01:58:55.560
[Guest]: to meet those learning objectives?

01:58:55.560 --> 01:58:58.560
[Guest]: So I think in that sense, the NEP is definitely a step

01:58:58.560 --> 01:59:00.560
[Guest]: in the right direction in terms of improving

01:59:00.560 --> 01:59:02.560
[Guest]: the outcome focus, okay?

01:59:02.560 --> 01:59:05.560
[Guest]: And to its credit, I think it's not just talking about

01:59:05.560 --> 01:59:07.560
[Guest]: a blind expansion of inputs.

01:59:07.560 --> 01:59:09.560
[Guest]: So there's many things about the NEP I actually like a lot,

01:59:09.560 --> 01:59:11.560
[Guest]: and it is, I think, a very thoughtful document

01:59:11.560 --> 01:59:12.560
[Guest]: in that regard.

01:59:12.560 --> 01:59:15.560
[Guest]: I think the bigger challenge is that bureaucracies

01:59:15.560 --> 01:59:19.560
[Guest]: are so good at converting goals into inputs, okay?

01:59:19.560 --> 01:59:21.560
[Guest]: And I'll give you an example of this in the context

01:59:21.560 --> 01:59:23.560
[Guest]: of, again, education, right?

01:59:23.560 --> 01:59:25.560
[Guest]: See, one of the things I have argued –

01:59:25.560 --> 01:59:27.560
[Guest]: in fact, the one piece of work I did,

01:59:27.560 --> 01:59:29.560
[Guest]: my political work at DTIO was kind of devised

01:59:29.560 --> 01:59:31.560
[Guest]: this thing called a school education quality index

01:59:31.560 --> 01:59:33.560
[Guest]: where, you know, we would essentially –

01:59:33.560 --> 01:59:35.560
[Guest]: the broader idea here is that high-performing

01:59:35.560 --> 01:59:38.560
[Guest]: organizations are characterized by autonomy

01:59:38.560 --> 01:59:40.560
[Guest]: on process to frontline workers

01:59:40.560 --> 01:59:42.560
[Guest]: with more accountability for outcomes, okay?

01:59:42.560 --> 01:59:44.560
[Guest]: So you say, I'm not going to micromanage how you deliver.

01:59:44.560 --> 01:59:46.560
[Guest]: You know the situation on the ground.

01:59:46.560 --> 01:59:47.560
[Guest]: You deliver, okay?

01:59:47.560 --> 01:59:49.560
[Guest]: But I will hold you accountable for outcomes, right?

01:59:49.560 --> 01:59:52.560
[Guest]: Whereas in government, we do exactly the opposite, right,

01:59:52.560 --> 01:59:54.560
[Guest]: which is we micromanage on process

01:59:54.560 --> 01:59:56.560
[Guest]: with zero accountability for outcome.

01:59:56.560 --> 01:59:58.560
[Guest]: This is seen even in the centrally-sponsored schemes

01:59:58.560 --> 02:00:00.560
[Guest]: of how the government of India interacts with the states, right?

02:00:00.560 --> 02:00:02.560
[Guest]: So because the government of India gives you budgets

02:00:02.560 --> 02:00:04.560
[Guest]: under these centrally-sponsored schemes that often have –

02:00:04.560 --> 02:00:06.560
[Guest]: like I think a former NITIAYOG advisor was telling me

02:00:06.560 --> 02:00:09.560
[Guest]: that in health, there's about 1,500 line items

02:00:09.560 --> 02:00:11.560
[Guest]: under the National Rural Health Mission.

02:00:11.560 --> 02:00:13.560
[Guest]: And so every state every year has to send

02:00:13.560 --> 02:00:15.560
[Guest]: what's called a project implementation plan,

02:00:15.560 --> 02:00:17.560
[Guest]: which is how they are spending against

02:00:17.560 --> 02:00:19.560
[Guest]: each one of those line items.

02:00:19.560 --> 02:00:21.560
[Guest]: So you have an army of consultants preparing these reports

02:00:21.560 --> 02:00:23.560
[Guest]: on one side, an army verifying them on the other.

02:00:23.560 --> 02:00:25.560
[Guest]: And in the end, this is just meaningless paperwork

02:00:25.560 --> 02:00:26.560
[Guest]: on both sides, right?

02:00:26.560 --> 02:00:29.560
[Guest]: So if you could shift some of the focus to saying,

02:00:29.560 --> 02:00:31.560
[Guest]: okay, we're going to provide some more untied funding

02:00:31.560 --> 02:00:33.560
[Guest]: to states to figure out how you're going to do this,

02:00:33.560 --> 02:00:35.560
[Guest]: but hold you accountable for outcomes

02:00:35.560 --> 02:00:37.560
[Guest]: and start tying a little bit of funding

02:00:37.560 --> 02:00:38.560
[Guest]: to improvement in outcomes, right?

02:00:38.560 --> 02:00:40.560
[Guest]: That would be – I think those are –

02:00:40.560 --> 02:00:43.560
[Guest]: that's the next level of the how that is missing in the NAP.

02:00:43.560 --> 02:00:46.560
[Guest]: But the good news is it doesn't tie your hands.

02:00:46.560 --> 02:00:48.560
[Guest]: I think the reason the RTE was such a kind of,

02:00:48.560 --> 02:00:50.560
[Guest]: I would say, negative impact is because it tried

02:00:50.560 --> 02:00:52.560
[Guest]: to micro-specify so much, right?

02:00:52.560 --> 02:00:55.560
[Guest]: That is, policy documents, I think, are more effective,

02:00:55.560 --> 02:00:57.560
[Guest]: particularly national policy documents,

02:00:57.560 --> 02:00:59.560
[Guest]: I think, are better as statements of principles,

02:00:59.560 --> 02:01:01.560
[Guest]: like of what we want to achieve,

02:01:01.560 --> 02:01:03.560
[Guest]: without getting too much into the details.

02:01:03.560 --> 02:01:04.560
[Guest]: So that's both a strength and a weakness.

02:01:04.560 --> 02:01:05.560
[Guest]: I think the weakness is, of course, you say,

02:01:05.560 --> 02:01:06.560
[Guest]: now how are you going to do this?

02:01:06.560 --> 02:01:08.560
[Guest]: Can you apply your thinking to that?

02:01:08.560 --> 02:01:10.560
[Guest]: The strength is by not prescribing one model,

02:01:10.560 --> 02:01:12.560
[Guest]: it allows kind of a thousand flowers

02:01:12.560 --> 02:01:13.560
[Guest]: and state-level thing.

02:01:13.560 --> 02:01:16.560
[Guest]: And so, which is why I think the most important next step

02:01:16.560 --> 02:01:20.560
[Guest]: is how does MHRD translate the NEP into a set of kind

02:01:20.560 --> 02:01:22.560
[Guest]: of programmatic interventions that then translate

02:01:22.560 --> 02:01:23.560
[Guest]: to the states, right?

02:01:23.560 --> 02:01:24.560
[Guest]: So MHRD, for your readers, of course,

02:01:24.560 --> 02:01:25.560
[Guest]: Ministry of Human Resource Development.

02:01:25.560 --> 02:01:27.560
[Guest]: So, but to give you an example, see,

02:01:27.560 --> 02:01:29.560
[Guest]: my view on outcomes is if you look at the three goals

02:01:29.560 --> 02:01:32.560
[Guest]: of education, of access, equity, and quality, right,

02:01:32.560 --> 02:01:34.560
[Guest]: are three very, very sensible goals.

02:01:34.560 --> 02:01:37.560
[Guest]: But my view is that if you measure learning outcomes

02:01:37.560 --> 02:01:39.560
[Guest]: in a systematic way in a census, you know,

02:01:39.560 --> 02:01:41.560
[Guest]: where you're able to do this, that the best thing

02:01:41.560 --> 02:01:44.560
[Guest]: you can do for access is, again, improve foundational literacy

02:01:44.560 --> 02:01:46.560
[Guest]: and numeracy because the drop-offs are happening

02:01:46.560 --> 02:01:48.560
[Guest]: at some level, the drop-out happens at some point

02:01:48.560 --> 02:01:51.560
[Guest]: because the child realizes that going to school

02:01:51.560 --> 02:01:52.560
[Guest]: is pointless, okay?

02:01:52.560 --> 02:01:54.560
[Guest]: Today, there's no child or no parent

02:01:54.560 --> 02:01:56.560
[Guest]: who doesn't want their child to study, right?

02:01:56.560 --> 02:01:58.560
[Guest]: The drop-outs happen because even the most illiterate parent

02:01:58.560 --> 02:02:00.560
[Guest]: recognizes that after four years in the system,

02:02:00.560 --> 02:02:01.560
[Guest]: my child has learned nothing.

02:02:01.560 --> 02:02:02.560
[Guest]: And I remember a field visit of mine,

02:02:02.560 --> 02:02:06.560
[Guest]: now about 10, 15 years ago, we went on a field visit

02:02:06.560 --> 02:02:07.560
[Guest]: to identify drop-out children.

02:02:07.560 --> 02:02:09.560
[Guest]: And we found this one child who was working

02:02:09.560 --> 02:02:11.560
[Guest]: in a motorcycle mechanic shop,

02:02:11.560 --> 02:02:13.560
[Guest]: must have been about 11 years old.

02:02:13.560 --> 02:02:15.560
[Guest]: And, you know, I think there was this big push

02:02:15.560 --> 02:02:16.560
[Guest]: to the parent, like, you know,

02:02:16.560 --> 02:02:18.560
[Guest]: why aren't you sending him to school?

02:02:18.560 --> 02:02:19.560
[Guest]: And, you know, this dad was illiterate,

02:02:19.560 --> 02:02:20.560
[Guest]: but he very, very clearly said, he said,

02:02:20.560 --> 02:02:22.560
[Guest]: listen, I've sent my child to the school for four years

02:02:22.560 --> 02:02:24.560
[Guest]: and I know he has learned nothing.

02:02:24.560 --> 02:02:26.560
[Guest]: He's actually learning something.

02:02:26.560 --> 02:02:28.560
[Guest]: And I'll come back to that when it comes

02:02:28.560 --> 02:02:29.560
[Guest]: to vocational education.

02:02:29.560 --> 02:02:31.560
[Guest]: So, therefore, if you want access,

02:02:31.560 --> 02:02:33.560
[Guest]: promoting foundational literacy and numeracy education

02:02:33.560 --> 02:02:35.560
[Guest]: is going to be your best way to keep kids in school

02:02:35.560 --> 02:02:37.560
[Guest]: because then they'll actually be learning something.

02:02:37.560 --> 02:02:39.560
[Guest]: Equity, again, what you want to do is

02:02:39.560 --> 02:02:41.560
[Guest]: you just want to be monitoring outcomes

02:02:41.560 --> 02:02:44.560
[Guest]: and seeing are you bridging outcome gaps, right?

02:02:44.560 --> 02:02:46.560
[Guest]: Because if you are doing that, then you're actually

02:02:46.560 --> 02:02:47.560
[Guest]: achieving equity.

02:02:47.560 --> 02:02:49.560
[Guest]: And quality by construction would be learning outcomes.

02:02:49.560 --> 02:02:51.560
[Guest]: Now, the beauty is if you then look at how

02:02:51.560 --> 02:02:54.560
[Guest]: an education bureaucracy takes these three goals

02:02:54.560 --> 02:02:56.560
[Guest]: and then spits out programs out of them, right?

02:02:56.560 --> 02:02:59.560
[Guest]: So, access becomes school construction, right?

02:02:59.560 --> 02:03:01.560
[Guest]: Equity becomes, do I have schemes for girls

02:03:01.560 --> 02:03:03.560
[Guest]: and minorities in every underprivileged group?

02:03:03.560 --> 02:03:05.560
[Guest]: So, every department of the government is running

02:03:05.560 --> 02:03:07.560
[Guest]: its own scholarship schemes, like, you know,

02:03:07.560 --> 02:03:08.560
[Guest]: for its narrow slice of the population

02:03:08.560 --> 02:03:10.560
[Guest]: that it's meant to serve.

02:03:10.560 --> 02:03:12.560
[Guest]: And then quality becomes, how much have I

02:03:12.560 --> 02:03:15.560
[Guest]: upgraded facilities and how much have I trained teachers?

02:03:15.560 --> 02:03:16.560
[Guest]: Which, again, we have shown has

02:03:16.560 --> 02:03:17.560
[Guest]: zero correlation with outcome.

02:03:17.560 --> 02:03:20.560
[Guest]: So, in that sense, the RTE was a much poorer

02:03:20.560 --> 02:03:22.560
[Guest]: kind of document because of how much it

02:03:22.560 --> 02:03:23.560
[Guest]: micro-specified these things.

02:03:23.560 --> 02:03:25.560
[Guest]: And the NEP, I feel, is, in that sense,

02:03:25.560 --> 02:03:26.560
[Guest]: a much better document.

02:03:26.560 --> 02:03:29.560
[Guest]: But it can become as bad as the RTE

02:03:29.560 --> 02:03:32.560
[Guest]: if MHRD decides to take it and micro-specify

02:03:32.560 --> 02:03:33.560
[Guest]: a bunch of things.

02:03:33.560 --> 02:03:35.560
[Guest]: So, the key step now is going to be

02:03:35.560 --> 02:03:37.560
[Guest]: how do you design an architecture

02:03:37.560 --> 02:03:39.560
[Guest]: of center-state relations where the center,

02:03:39.560 --> 02:03:41.560
[Guest]: you know, provides the funding and provides

02:03:41.560 --> 02:03:43.560
[Guest]: the technical support as needed, but provides

02:03:43.560 --> 02:03:45.560
[Guest]: more autonomy to states in figuring out

02:03:45.560 --> 02:03:47.560
[Guest]: how they're going to deliver the goals.

02:03:47.560 --> 02:03:48.560
[Guest]: And maybe this should be an entire separate

02:03:48.560 --> 02:03:50.560
[Guest]: topic on Indian federalism, like, you know,

02:03:50.560 --> 02:03:52.560
[Guest]: that we can do, because, yeah, there is

02:03:52.560 --> 02:03:55.560
[Guest]: many, many threads in here.

02:03:55.560 --> 02:03:56.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, so one question that comes to mind

02:03:56.560 --> 02:03:58.560
[Amit Varma]: quickly, and what I'll do is, before we get

02:03:58.560 --> 02:04:00.560
[Amit Varma]: to the rest of the episode, we'll, for the

02:04:00.560 --> 02:04:02.560
[Amit Varma]: first time ever, take a second, another

02:04:02.560 --> 02:04:04.560
[Amit Varma]: commercial break in the show, so you get

02:04:04.560 --> 02:04:05.560
[Amit Varma]: a break as well.

02:04:05.560 --> 02:04:07.560
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to that, one question that

02:04:07.560 --> 02:04:08.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of comes up from this, and this is a

02:04:08.560 --> 02:04:10.560
[Amit Varma]: thought that I've often had whenever

02:04:10.560 --> 02:04:12.560
[Amit Varma]: there's a sea change from one system to

02:04:12.560 --> 02:04:14.560
[Amit Varma]: another. Now, let's say that in education

02:04:14.560 --> 02:04:16.560
[Amit Varma]: there was a state of affairs, and now

02:04:16.560 --> 02:04:18.560
[Amit Varma]: with the NEP, it's the, you know,

02:04:18.560 --> 02:04:20.560
[Amit Varma]: the idea is to move to another state of

02:04:20.560 --> 02:04:22.560
[Amit Varma]: affairs. And my question here is that

02:04:22.560 --> 02:04:25.560
[Amit Varma]: when one then designs a shift like this,

02:04:25.560 --> 02:04:27.560
[Amit Varma]: a new state of affairs, does one take

02:04:27.560 --> 02:04:29.560
[Amit Varma]: into account, number one, the transaction

02:04:29.560 --> 02:04:31.560
[Amit Varma]: cost of shifting from one to the other,

02:04:31.560 --> 02:04:34.560
[Amit Varma]: so to say, and number two, you know,

02:04:34.560 --> 02:04:36.560
[Amit Varma]: whether there is the state capacity and

02:04:36.560 --> 02:04:38.560
[Amit Varma]: the intellectual capacity within the

02:04:38.560 --> 02:04:41.560
[Amit Varma]: state to do that kind of shift, do these

02:04:41.560 --> 02:04:43.560
[Amit Varma]: considerations then have to be part of

02:04:43.560 --> 02:04:45.560
[Amit Varma]: the design? Because as you pointed out,

02:04:45.560 --> 02:04:47.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, if goals can just become these

02:04:47.560 --> 02:04:49.560
[Amit Varma]: inputs, and, you know, because any metric

02:04:49.560 --> 02:04:51.560
[Amit Varma]: that exists can easily be gamed, and the

02:04:51.560 --> 02:04:53.560
[Amit Varma]: whole system can just go to hell very

02:04:53.560 --> 02:04:56.560
[Amit Varma]: fast. So, does the NEP sort of address

02:04:56.560 --> 02:04:58.560
[Amit Varma]: some of this? Is this stuff that people

02:04:58.560 --> 02:05:00.560
[Amit Varma]: like you who are trying to bring about

02:05:00.560 --> 02:05:02.560
[Amit Varma]: broad changes in policy, as well as, of

02:05:02.560 --> 02:05:03.560
[Amit Varma]: course, incremental improvements, but

02:05:03.560 --> 02:05:05.560
[Amit Varma]: also broad changes? Is this something

02:05:05.560 --> 02:05:07.560
[Amit Varma]: that you guys have to keep in mind and

02:05:07.560 --> 02:05:08.560
[Guest]: think about?

02:05:08.560 --> 02:05:10.560
[Guest]: Yeah, and I think, you know, again, so the

02:05:10.560 --> 02:05:11.560
[Guest]: challenge of policy documents for

02:05:11.560 --> 02:05:13.560
[Guest]: countries as large and diverse as India,

02:05:13.560 --> 02:05:14.560
[Guest]: again, you know, we have 1.4 billion

02:05:14.560 --> 02:05:16.560
[Guest]: people. That's more than the entire

02:05:16.560 --> 02:05:17.560
[Guest]: Western Hemisphere put together, right?

02:05:17.560 --> 02:05:19.560
[Guest]: More than North America, Central America,

02:05:19.560 --> 02:05:20.560
[Guest]: South America put together, and you

02:05:20.560 --> 02:05:21.560
[Guest]: don't have, like, a government of the

02:05:21.560 --> 02:05:23.560
[Guest]: Western Hemisphere. We have more people

02:05:23.560 --> 02:05:24.560
[Guest]: than all of Africa put together. You

02:05:24.560 --> 02:05:26.560
[Guest]: don't have a government of Africa, right?

02:05:26.560 --> 02:05:28.560
[Guest]: So, to that extent, the sheer

02:05:28.560 --> 02:05:30.560
[Guest]: heterogeneity of the lived reality of

02:05:30.560 --> 02:05:33.560
[Guest]: Indians is so large that I think trying

02:05:33.560 --> 02:05:35.560
[Guest]: to micro-specify any more would be a

02:05:35.560 --> 02:05:36.560
[Guest]: mistake. So, in that sense, I think the

02:05:36.560 --> 02:05:37.560
[Guest]: NAP has the right balance of kind of

02:05:37.560 --> 02:05:40.560
[Guest]: being essentially a statement of national

02:05:40.560 --> 02:05:41.560
[Guest]: goals. So, what is it that we want to

02:05:41.560 --> 02:05:44.560
[Guest]: achieve? And, you know, providing some

02:05:44.560 --> 02:05:47.560
[Guest]: frameworks for national public goods,

02:05:47.560 --> 02:05:48.560
[Guest]: including, you know, standards,

02:05:48.560 --> 02:05:50.560
[Guest]: accreditation, and stuff like that, and

02:05:50.560 --> 02:05:52.560
[Guest]: hopefully providing a lot more policy

02:05:52.560 --> 02:05:55.560
[Guest]: space for states to do this. And I think

02:05:55.560 --> 02:05:56.560
[Guest]: and the reason that's important is

02:05:56.560 --> 02:05:58.560
[Guest]: because the state capacity itself varies

02:05:58.560 --> 02:06:00.560
[Guest]: so much across Indian states, right? You

02:06:00.560 --> 02:06:01.560
[Guest]: know, and that's why I think we should

02:06:01.560 --> 02:06:02.560
[Guest]: we should definitely do a complete

02:06:02.560 --> 02:06:03.560
[Guest]: separate issue, an episode on

02:06:03.560 --> 02:06:05.560
[Guest]: federalism, right? Because I think given

02:06:05.560 --> 02:06:07.560
[Guest]: my work in the states, what I see is one

02:06:07.560 --> 02:06:09.560
[Guest]: of the other problems of these

02:06:09.560 --> 02:06:11.560
[Guest]: overbearing centrally sponsored schemes

02:06:11.560 --> 02:06:13.560
[Guest]: is that over the years, it has

02:06:13.560 --> 02:06:16.560
[Guest]: essentially atrophied the policymaking

02:06:16.560 --> 02:06:18.560
[Guest]: muscles at the state level, right? Because

02:06:18.560 --> 02:06:20.560
[Guest]: you go to the, you know, even state

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:22.560
[Guest]: departments, education departments, health

02:06:22.560 --> 02:06:23.560
[Guest]: departments, and better functioning

02:06:23.560 --> 02:06:25.560
[Guest]: states like Tamil Nadu, like, or Maharashtra,

02:06:25.560 --> 02:06:27.560
[Guest]: and, you know, often the default is like,

02:06:27.560 --> 02:06:29.560
[Guest]: okay, but is it in the central guideline or not?

02:06:29.560 --> 02:06:30.560
[Guest]: Okay, because if it's in the central

02:06:30.560 --> 02:06:32.560
[Guest]: guideline, it means the money will flow.

02:06:32.560 --> 02:06:34.560
[Guest]: Whereas, if you have to come up with your

02:06:34.560 --> 02:06:36.560
[Guest]: own policies, you need to argue for that

02:06:36.560 --> 02:06:38.560
[Guest]: case with your finance ministry. And

02:06:38.560 --> 02:06:39.560
[Guest]: that's why where the lack of

02:06:39.560 --> 02:06:41.560
[Guest]: intellectual kind of machinery to do

02:06:41.560 --> 02:06:43.560
[Guest]: this comes in. So, you know, it's a very

02:06:43.560 --> 02:06:45.560
[Guest]: fraught problem, right? And so there's a

02:06:45.560 --> 02:06:47.560
[Guest]: very big literature on decentralization

02:06:47.560 --> 02:06:49.560
[Guest]: that says that one of the problems with

02:06:49.560 --> 02:06:51.560
[Guest]: kind of decentralizing too much is then

02:06:51.560 --> 02:06:52.560
[Guest]: the technical capacity and state

02:06:52.560 --> 02:06:54.560
[Guest]: capacity doesn't exist. And that kind of

02:06:54.560 --> 02:06:56.560
[Guest]: because there's economies of scale in

02:06:56.560 --> 02:06:57.560
[Guest]: terms of designing some of these

02:06:57.560 --> 02:06:59.560
[Guest]: architectures of policy, right? So you

02:06:59.560 --> 02:07:00.560
[Guest]: don't kind of have that necessarily at

02:07:00.560 --> 02:07:02.560
[Guest]: the level of every district. So, which is

02:07:02.560 --> 02:07:03.560
[Guest]: why I do think we should do a separate

02:07:03.560 --> 02:07:05.560
[Guest]: issue in federalism and go through the

02:07:05.560 --> 02:07:06.560
[Guest]: first principles of what kind of, you

02:07:06.560 --> 02:07:08.560
[Guest]: know, functions sit at different parts

02:07:08.560 --> 02:07:11.560
[Guest]: and how would we structure a national

02:07:11.560 --> 02:07:14.560
[Guest]: policy framework that also maximizes

02:07:14.560 --> 02:07:16.560
[Guest]: our chances of getting it done, given

02:07:16.560 --> 02:07:18.560
[Guest]: our limitations of state and

02:07:18.560 --> 02:07:20.560
[Guest]: administrative capacity. But I think

02:07:20.560 --> 02:07:22.560
[Guest]: it's very hard for a policy document to

02:07:22.560 --> 02:07:24.560
[Guest]: explicitly talk about that because you

02:07:24.560 --> 02:07:27.560
[Guest]: can maybe acknowledge that constraint

02:07:27.560 --> 02:07:28.560
[Guest]: and, you know, and I haven't read it

02:07:28.560 --> 02:07:30.560
[Guest]: word to word, maybe that's even there

02:07:30.560 --> 02:07:32.560
[Guest]: somewhere. But the constraint is very,

02:07:32.560 --> 02:07:33.560
[Amit Varma]: very real.

