02:49:58.400 --> 02:50:01.360
[Guest]: Okay, so and they attended a private school of their choice in the village and attended

02:50:01.360 --> 02:50:06.520
[Guest]: for up to four years that at the end of four years, surprisingly, so first, let me talk

02:50:06.520 --> 02:50:12.080
[Guest]: about the processes, right. So the private schools are poorer on observable measures

02:50:12.080 --> 02:50:17.440
[Guest]: of input, but do better on every measure of effort. Okay, so they have the teachers are

02:50:17.440 --> 02:50:21.640
[Guest]: less educated, they are less qualified, they're less trained, they're paid much lower salaries,

02:50:21.640 --> 02:50:27.080
[Guest]: right. So in an RTE framework, private schools look miserable, because on inputs, they are

02:50:27.080 --> 02:50:31.160
[Guest]: actually way inferior to the government school. But once you kind of go measure effort, you'll

02:50:31.160 --> 02:50:35.320
[Guest]: see that the private schools do better on every measure of effort, right. So lower teacher

02:50:35.320 --> 02:50:39.960
[Guest]: absence, higher time on task, longer school year, longer school day. And we also have

02:50:39.960 --> 02:50:43.920
[Guest]: like a module that measures management practices. And in fact, that's a new working paper which

02:50:43.920 --> 02:50:47.660
[Guest]: will release in the next couple of weeks. And you see that on even concrete measures

02:50:47.660 --> 02:50:52.800
[Guest]: of management practices, the private schools do much, much better. Okay, so, but, but,

02:50:52.800 --> 02:50:57.120
[Guest]: but this kind of the stupefying result is even though the observable characteristics

02:50:57.120 --> 02:51:00.680
[Guest]: of the private schools are so much better. At the end of four years of this, we find

02:51:00.680 --> 02:51:04.680
[Guest]: that the kids who went to the private school did not do any better, okay, on either maths

02:51:04.680 --> 02:51:10.000
[Guest]: or Telugu, which was because this was in Unified Andhra. And so you know, what this tells you

02:51:10.000 --> 02:51:14.100
[Guest]: is that, you know, at one level, the critics of the private schools that say that most

02:51:14.100 --> 02:51:18.440
[Guest]: of what the private schools are doing is functioning on the selection margin, as opposed to the

02:51:18.440 --> 02:51:22.920
[Guest]: education margin is actually correct, right, which is, there is a selection aspect of both

02:51:22.920 --> 02:51:27.480
[Guest]: the better, relatively better off as well as private schools trying to screen out children

02:51:27.480 --> 02:51:32.480
[Guest]: who might, you know, be slow learners or disabled or whatever. Okay, so in that sense, there

02:51:32.480 --> 02:51:37.600
[Guest]: was enough in the results to kind of, you know, put a note of caution to the kind of

02:51:37.600 --> 02:51:41.560
[Guest]: blind voucher walas, right? Like I'm saying, acha voucher karo, private kar dekha, because

02:51:41.560 --> 02:51:46.500
[Guest]: there's nothing. But on the other hand, what we see is that the private schools are actually

02:51:46.500 --> 02:51:51.000
[Guest]: delivering the same output at one third the cost, right? So the cost per child is actually

02:51:51.000 --> 02:51:53.960
[Guest]: much, much lower. So if you look at the cost per child in the public schools, it's much

02:51:53.960 --> 02:51:57.440
[Guest]: higher. And because the private school has to compete in the market, they are much more

02:51:57.440 --> 02:52:01.320
[Guest]: cost effective. The other subtle thing that's going on with the private schools, and this

02:52:01.320 --> 02:52:06.040
[Guest]: is what makes education research so vexing, right, which is that it, you know, so what

02:52:06.040 --> 02:52:09.440
[Guest]: we did is we went and looked at the timetable. So what you saw is that the private schools

02:52:09.440 --> 02:52:14.520
[Guest]: actually spend much less time teaching Telugu and math. And they use that extra time to

02:52:14.520 --> 02:52:18.400
[Guest]: teach other subjects that are not in the government school. So they were teaching more English,

02:52:18.400 --> 02:52:22.100
[Guest]: teaching more Hindi, okay. And so this makes it very difficult, because now it's not an

02:52:22.100 --> 02:52:26.520
[Guest]: apples to apples comparison. So even though the level of learning is the same, it was

02:52:26.520 --> 02:52:30.400
[Guest]: being achieved with much less instructional time, right? So the productivity in the private

02:52:30.400 --> 02:52:34.640
[Guest]: school was higher. And we see that the test score results are higher in English and Hindi.

02:52:34.640 --> 02:52:40.800
[Guest]: And now, but even there, you can have difference of opinion as to, should you aggregate these

02:52:40.800 --> 02:52:45.720
[Guest]: results and saying that the private schools do better? Or is the problem that, you know,

02:52:45.720 --> 02:52:48.560
[Guest]: and Abhijit Banerjee himself told me this, he said, like, you know, what is the point

02:52:48.560 --> 02:52:51.720
[Guest]: in not being able to read in three languages, right? Like, you know, you're not able to

02:52:51.720 --> 02:52:55.720
[Guest]: read even in your mother tongue, so that you're diversifying your curriculum, and part of

02:52:55.720 --> 02:53:00.560
[Guest]: what's happening. And if you look at the private school curriculum choice, there is one view

02:53:00.560 --> 02:53:04.640
[Guest]: that says these guys are being incredibly forward thinking, because the labor market

02:53:04.640 --> 02:53:08.200
[Guest]: returns to English and Hindi are going to be higher than if you're in Andhra Pradesh,

02:53:08.200 --> 02:53:12.120
[Guest]: Hindi gives you access to a national labor market, right? So just given the amount of

02:53:12.120 --> 02:53:17.040
[Guest]: internal migration, say workers from Bihar and UP coming to AP, if you are, if you are

02:53:17.040 --> 02:53:21.200
[Guest]: a Hindi speaker, maybe that increases the chances of being a factory foreman, and so

02:53:21.200 --> 02:53:25.160
[Guest]: and supervising these workers. And so the returns in the labor market may be higher.

02:53:25.160 --> 02:53:27.840
[Guest]: And you know, even if you can't speak English, okay, so one view is these guys are being

02:53:27.840 --> 02:53:32.560
[Guest]: very, very farsighted. The other view is that no, there is isomorphic mimicry, even in the

02:53:32.560 --> 02:53:36.920
[Guest]: private schools that they're just like mechanically copying the curricula of elite private schools.

02:53:36.920 --> 02:53:40.560
[Guest]: And because elite private schools do multiple languages, they do that. And even though that

02:53:40.560 --> 02:53:45.600
[Guest]: may not in fact be optimal for these voucher kids, okay, so, so I think, basically, the

02:53:45.600 --> 02:53:49.440
[Guest]: school choice argument relies on two pieces, it relies on kind of there's a productivity

02:53:49.440 --> 02:53:53.760
[Guest]: argument and there is a choice argument. And I think the challenge here is that the market

02:53:53.760 --> 02:53:58.960
[Guest]: metaphors break down for multiple reasons, because choice and assessing school quality

02:53:58.960 --> 02:54:02.840
[Guest]: is an incredibly challenging problem. I have a PhD in economics from Harvard, and I have

02:54:02.840 --> 02:54:06.960
[Guest]: no idea what's going on in my child's preschool, right? Like, you know, so you only have some

02:54:06.960 --> 02:54:11.960
[Guest]: proximate measures of quality. And so it's very, very hard. Okay. So the punchline from

02:54:11.960 --> 02:54:16.440
[Guest]: all the results is to say that, listen, the private schools are more productive, but it

02:54:16.440 --> 02:54:21.580
[Guest]: is not obvious that expanding a voucher system in the current status quo will by itself give

02:54:21.580 --> 02:54:25.680
[Guest]: you better learning outcomes, it might give you better value for money. But that is not

02:54:25.680 --> 02:54:30.320
[Guest]: the same. And which is why when I look at the global research on education, there is

02:54:30.320 --> 02:54:34.520
[Guest]: a different model, right? Like, you know, so what are the problems even with vouchers?

02:54:34.520 --> 02:54:38.600
[Guest]: And I think is that when kids have the freedom, parents have freedom, it's very attractive.

02:54:38.600 --> 02:54:41.680
[Guest]: But there is no guarantee that the school has to accept you, right? So that goes back

02:54:41.680 --> 02:54:44.920
[Guest]: to the Harvard point I made in the beginning, right? Like, you know, you can afford it,

02:54:44.920 --> 02:54:48.400
