02:55:25.040 --> 02:55:29.320
[Guest]: we need to be cognisant of. Now, there's another part of the choice argument where voucher

02:55:29.320 --> 02:55:33.680
[Guest]: studies have shown, you know, need for caution, which is that parents often pick aspirational

02:55:33.680 --> 02:55:37.640
[Guest]: schools, right? You pick schools that you think are aspirational and look good. But

02:55:37.640 --> 02:55:41.080
[Guest]: going back to this curriculum mismatch issue that I highlighted, that if you're picking

02:55:41.080 --> 02:55:45.760
[Guest]: a school where the curriculum is so far ahead of where your child is, there is a real sense

02:55:45.760 --> 02:55:51.040
[Guest]: in which this could backfire. Okay. And so there's an alternative model of saying, how

02:55:51.040 --> 02:55:56.760
[Guest]: do you bring the efficiency of private management while kind of minimising some of these pathologies

02:55:56.760 --> 02:56:00.080
[Guest]: in private schools? Okay. And that's basically what the idea of charter schools is, right?

02:56:00.080 --> 02:56:04.760
[Guest]: So the idea of a charter school is that you maintain the public characteristic of a school,

02:56:04.760 --> 02:56:09.520
[Guest]: but you basically provide a management contract, right? Like you lean to a private entity that

02:56:09.520 --> 02:56:13.320
[Guest]: says I will, yeah, okay, sorry, before I get there, maybe just get your quick reactance

02:56:13.320 --> 02:56:17.160
[Amit Varma]: to the research. Yeah, yeah. Before we get to private schools, my quick reaction is first

02:56:17.160 --> 02:56:21.240
[Amit Varma]: of all, you know, I'm familiar with your study. And I've also read the responses by Gita Gandhi

02:56:21.240 --> 02:56:25.080
[Amit Varma]: Kingdom and James Truly, where they pointed out the Telugu angle that you're pointing

02:56:25.080 --> 02:56:29.960
[Amit Varma]: out now, my, my, my sense of it is that, you know, and they've also done studies and, you

02:56:29.960 --> 02:56:33.520
[Amit Varma]: know, there are other studies we showed that, you know, private schools give better outcomes

02:56:33.520 --> 02:56:37.720
[Amit Varma]: and so on. But leaving that aside, just kind of focusing on this issue, my sense of this

02:56:37.720 --> 02:56:43.560
[Amit Varma]: was that leaving the choice angle aside, just on the productivity angle, that one, yes,

02:56:43.560 --> 02:56:48.120
[Amit Varma]: they got, you know, outcomes at much cheaper, so better value for money, that's a sight.

02:56:48.120 --> 02:56:51.600
[Amit Varma]: But also, they didn't get worse outcomes on any margin, exactly. Even if they were the

02:56:51.600 --> 02:56:55.360
[Amit Varma]: same, if they're getting it cheaper, and they're learning a couple of extra things, that's

02:56:55.360 --> 02:56:59.480
[Amit Varma]: okay. The second thing that sort of struck me was that I think that choice argument is

02:56:59.480 --> 02:57:04.920
[Amit Varma]: actually enough on its own, because I think who are we, you know, if a choice has to be

02:57:04.920 --> 02:57:08.840
[Amit Varma]: made for the child, it's very condescending to say that the parent does not have the ability

02:57:08.840 --> 02:57:13.320
[Amit Varma]: to make that choice. It is only the parent who should make that choice. And, you know,

02:57:13.320 --> 02:57:17.160
[Amit Varma]: my view, and what I would say is that, like you pointed out in your paper as well, like

02:57:17.160 --> 02:57:21.280
[Amit Varma]: your 2018 paper, which you sent me was quite nuanced on this issue, where you pointed out

02:57:21.280 --> 02:57:24.920
[Amit Varma]: all these different sides. And there, you pointed out that, you know, even if parents

02:57:24.920 --> 02:57:29.120
[Amit Varma]: may make a mistake, sending their kid to a place where the main medium of instruction

02:57:29.120 --> 02:57:33.240
[Amit Varma]: is English rather than Telugu, because studies have shown that learning happens at that early

02:57:33.240 --> 02:57:38.680
[Amit Varma]: age much better in the mother tongue, despite that, that could be offset by a later premium

02:57:38.680 --> 02:57:42.560
[Amit Varma]: that they get for having gone to an English medium school later on in the labor market.

02:57:42.560 --> 02:57:48.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, as you said, it's too complex for anybody to judge. And therefore, morally, the choice

02:57:48.200 --> 02:57:52.840
[Amit Varma]: of where the kid go should just stay with the parents, given that there is such muddiness

02:57:52.840 --> 02:57:54.320
[Amit Varma]: of information, either way.

02:57:54.320 --> 02:57:57.800
[Guest]: And I'm very, very sympathetic to that, like, you know, and I think, I mean, the only slight

02:57:57.800 --> 02:58:02.440
[Guest]: pushback to this is, you know, and it goes back to the third goal of education systems,

02:58:02.440 --> 02:58:06.040
[Guest]: the public education systems, which we haven't spent enough time on, right? Because, you

02:58:06.040 --> 02:58:09.920
[Guest]: know, but this is very, very important. And it's important to understand that the spread

02:58:09.920 --> 02:58:13.720
[Guest]: of mass education actually had very little to do with either of the first two goals,

02:58:13.720 --> 02:58:18.360
[Guest]: right? Because the sorting goal, like, you know, could happen by kind of elite exams,

02:58:18.360 --> 02:58:21.080
[Guest]: which, you know, Chinese bureaucrats have been passing for a very long time, right?

02:58:21.080 --> 02:58:26.320
[Guest]: So where the modern state was willing to invest in mass education, in fact, my colleague at

02:58:26.320 --> 02:58:30.400
[Guest]: UCSD, Agustina Paglian, is a political scientist, and she's done some very nice work on this,

02:58:30.400 --> 02:58:35.080
[Guest]: is that the third objective of education systems, there's human development, there is sorting.

02:58:35.080 --> 02:58:40.720
[Guest]: But the third is actually creating a common shared sense of citizenship, right? So and

02:58:40.720 --> 02:58:45.680
[Guest]: what makes education inherently political, right, is that as economists, we are used

02:58:45.680 --> 02:58:51.520
[Guest]: to saying, how does a free market or free agency make choices conditional on your preferences,

02:58:51.520 --> 02:58:57.520
[Guest]: right? But we don't ask where do the preferences come from, right? And so what makes education

02:58:57.520 --> 02:59:02.840
[Guest]: inherently more political than any other market analogy, is it's because it's the place where

02:59:02.840 --> 02:59:06.840
[Guest]: you're actually forming preferences, right, that can mean of a generation. And so and

02:59:06.840 --> 02:59:10.520
[Guest]: that creates externalities. And then that's a good question about should the government

02:59:10.520 --> 02:59:14.520
[Guest]: have a say, right? And so but the language question, and again, we should do it, we could

02:59:14.520 --> 02:59:18.040
[Guest]: do an entire episode just on the vexing question of language, right? But it's an incredibly

02:59:18.040 --> 02:59:22.480
[Guest]: vexing question, right? So and it's because no language is morally superior or inferior,

02:59:22.480 --> 02:59:26.000
[Guest]: right, that can mean and then, but the market attraction of a language is a function of

02:59:26.000 --> 02:59:30.520
[Guest]: a bunch of other things. So but the larger point here is that one of the reasons public

02:59:30.520 --> 02:59:35.200
[Guest]: education systems try to kind of put their thumb with regard to language is precisely

02:59:35.200 --> 02:59:39.200
[Guest]: because there is a certain public good with regard to culture, right, that goes beyond

02:59:39.200 --> 02:59:42.680
[Guest]: the individual choice. And that's a much more nuanced discussion. That's all. So I don't

02:59:42.680 --> 02:59:46.320
[Guest]: agree with the spirit of what you said, that in the end, however complex it is, it's the

02:59:46.320 --> 02:59:51.600
[Guest]: parents and the ultimate users who should make their decisions. But even without coercion,

02:59:51.600 --> 02:59:55.120
[Guest]: you can still put your thumb on the scale as a society that says there is a collective

02:59:55.120 --> 02:59:58.600
[Guest]: good. And this is classic public externalities, right? Like, you know, there's a certain collective

02:59:58.600 --> 03:00:02.440
[Guest]: good in maintaining a language or a culture. And we find ways to put our thumb on the scale

03:00:02.440 --> 03:00:03.440
[Guest]: on that one way or the other.

03:00:03.440 --> 03:00:07.320
[Amit Varma]: What I would add to that is like, one, whenever I hear the word collective, I'm like, no,

03:00:07.320 --> 03:00:10.640
[Amit Varma]: we should think in terms of individuals, not collectives. But whatever, that's just me.

03:00:10.640 --> 03:00:14.880
[Guest]: But hang on, but let me pause there, right? Because I think there is a limit to kind of

03:00:14.880 --> 03:00:18.200
[Guest]: the extreme individualism, which we kind of see in the US with kind of the disaster and

03:00:18.200 --> 03:00:21.740
[Guest]: masking right now, right? Like, you know, so when you build this kind of myth of kind

03:00:21.740 --> 03:00:25.560
[Guest]: of the frontier man, like, you know, who's out there on his own doing things, then when

03:00:25.560 --> 03:00:29.520
[Guest]: you need the public good of wearing a mask, not for yourself, but for the public good,

03:00:29.520 --> 03:00:32.920
[Guest]: you find it very hard to do that. So again, there's a balance.

03:00:32.920 --> 03:00:36.240
[Amit Varma]: On that issue, I agree with you entirely. But the point is that if you look at the negative

03:00:36.240 --> 03:00:41.460
[Amit Varma]: externalities of how this Indian state has messed up education, they are disastrous,

03:00:41.460 --> 03:00:45.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, and my point there would be that earlier, we were talking about how both of

03:00:45.360 --> 03:00:49.600
[Amit Varma]: us, of course, support democracy, because you want every individual, every citizen in

03:00:49.600 --> 03:00:54.240
[Amit Varma]: a democracy to in a nation to feel empowered and democracy gives you that. And similarly,

03:00:54.240 --> 03:00:58.520
[Amit Varma]: I'd say that the current education system is actually the opposite of that it is an

03:00:58.520 --> 03:01:02.520
[Amit Varma]: authoritarian system where you are building a model. And yes, some experts like you are

03:01:02.520 --> 03:01:06.120
[Amit Varma]: having some input into the model model, and hopefully the model will be improved on the

03:01:06.120 --> 03:01:10.400
[Amit Varma]: margins. But it is one model being imposed on everyone. And what would be nice is to

03:01:10.400 --> 03:01:14.200
[Amit Varma]: see many, many models flourish. One way of doing that, of course, which we will discuss

03:01:14.200 --> 03:01:18.800
[Amit Varma]: in our next episode, which will hopefully be even longer than this is the federalism

03:01:18.800 --> 03:01:22.400
[Amit Varma]: model where you have so much local governance that you have different models coming out

03:01:22.400 --> 03:01:28.360
[Amit Varma]: locally. But another model would be that just let entrepreneurship flourish in this field

03:01:28.360 --> 03:01:32.320
[Amit Varma]: unleash the market, you know, society will solve its own problems that doesn't happen.

03:01:32.320 --> 03:01:37.120
[Amit Varma]: But we only have a few minutes and it would be a travesty if I do not let you speak about

03:01:37.120 --> 03:01:40.760
[Amit Varma]: charter schools, because you've been very insightful and eloquent on that as well. So

03:01:40.760 --> 03:01:46.120
[Guest]: on private school policy, let me say two things, right. So there is one set of policies that

03:01:46.120 --> 03:01:51.560
[Guest]: matter where you say unleash the private sector regardless of your ability, even if you don't

03:01:51.560 --> 03:01:56.440
[Guest]: cater to the poor, okay. And because that's kind of the status quo anyway, right? 50%

03:01:56.440 --> 03:02:01.280
[Guest]: 60% are doing that. Okay. So on that, I think my biggest policy thrust, which I think you

03:02:01.280 --> 03:02:06.320
[Guest]: will also agree with is to say, you regulate based on disclosure as opposed to mandates.

03:02:06.320 --> 03:02:11.160
[Guest]: Okay, so you still need some regulation, because you know, there are problems of asymmetric

03:02:11.160 --> 03:02:14.640
[Guest]: information, there are problems of you know, safety, public goods, etc. But what do you

03:02:14.640 --> 03:02:19.000
[Guest]: say is, listen, you know, if a qualified teacher truly matters, let the market decide, like,

03:02:19.000 --> 03:02:22.440
[Guest]: you know, where the parents are willing to pay for that. And if a school decides that

03:02:22.440 --> 03:02:26.320
[Guest]: I can provide better education by hiring for teaching assistants, the 10 standard paths

03:02:26.320 --> 03:02:29.800
[Guest]: were able to provide small group instruction, let them have the freedom to do that. And

03:02:29.800 --> 03:02:34.080
[Guest]: the only requirement is that they so basically, it goes back to my point about admin data

03:02:34.080 --> 03:02:38.400
[Guest]: integrity, right? Like, so my basic approach to say regulate based on disclosure is, if

03:02:38.400 --> 03:02:42.160
[Guest]: you lie, I will shut you down. Okay, like I mean, but as long as you're telling the

03:02:42.160 --> 03:02:45.320
[Amit Varma]: truth, you can do whatever you want, right? Let me quote you on this. Since you brought

03:02:45.320 --> 03:02:49.000
[Amit Varma]: up regulation, let me quote you on this, because I like this quote, and which is why I sort

03:02:49.000 --> 03:02:54.040
[Amit Varma]: of copy pasted it into my notes. Quote, while these reasons for regulation make sense in

03:02:54.040 --> 03:02:57.520
[Amit Varma]: theory earlier, you've basically given reasons for regulating private schools, one, there

03:02:57.520 --> 03:03:01.400
[Amit Varma]: are public spaces to there is information, asymmetry in the sense, you know, parents

03:03:01.400 --> 03:03:04.300
[Amit Varma]: have no way of knowing schools are so complex, like you said, you don't know what's happening

03:03:04.300 --> 03:03:08.360
[Amit Varma]: in your kids play school. And then there is a symmetry of power that private schools can

03:03:08.360 --> 03:03:13.960
[Amit Varma]: arbitrarily do whatever and parents have no power. So on these, you say, quote, while

03:03:13.960 --> 03:03:17.680
[Amit Varma]: these reasons for regulation make sense in theory, the Indian approach to regulation

03:03:17.680 --> 03:03:22.840
[Amit Varma]: of private schools has in practice been heavy handed and arbitrarily enforced. In particular,

03:03:22.840 --> 03:03:26.440
[Amit Varma]: the approach has placed a lot of power in the hands of school inspectors who can shut

03:03:26.440 --> 03:03:30.600
[Amit Varma]: down schools for a wide variety of reasons, and extort bribes from school management to

03:03:30.600 --> 03:03:35.920
[Amit Varma]: overlook regulatory violations. Further, this problem has worsened since blah, blah, blah.

03:03:35.920 --> 03:03:39.280
[Amit Varma]: And then you talk about the right to education act, very eloquent. I don't want to, I don't

03:03:39.280 --> 03:03:42.440
[Amit Varma]: want to take up your time, but I agree with you entirely. And your solution, as you were

03:03:42.440 --> 03:03:47.240
[Amit Varma]: saying is that rather than make them comply with a whole bunch of these things, and then

03:03:47.240 --> 03:03:52.040
[Amit Varma]: inspectors will come to test it and they'll have to be bribed and everything goes haywire.

03:03:52.040 --> 03:03:56.920
[Amit Varma]: You let them disclose everything. And then if you find they happen to lie about something,

03:03:56.920 --> 03:04:00.720
[Amit Varma]: then you take them to task, but otherwise you reduce the regulatory burden.

03:04:00.720 --> 03:04:04.760
[Guest]: Exactly. I think, you know, and the status quo is particularly kind of corrosive, right?

03:04:04.760 --> 03:04:09.960
[Guest]: Because what happens is the burdens are so onerous that kind of very few legitimate operators

03:04:09.960 --> 03:04:13.920
[Guest]: can in fact meet them, right? So you kind of get negative selection that the good guys

03:04:13.920 --> 03:04:16.960
[Guest]: don't participate. And the only people who will participate are the ones who are willing

03:04:16.960 --> 03:04:21.680
[Guest]: to pay the bribes to kind of get, so you get this corrosive equilibrium where you cannot

03:04:21.680 --> 03:04:25.000
[Guest]: meet this. And so the good guys go out and the ones who are there are the ones who are

03:04:25.000 --> 03:04:28.280
[Guest]: willing to kind of, you know, bribe their way through the inspection certificates. And

03:04:28.280 --> 03:04:31.960
[Guest]: of course, I mean, and that's a status quo that benefits like obviously the inspectors.

03:04:31.960 --> 03:04:36.920
[Guest]: And it also goes back to this kind of cognitive dissonance that I think the government finds

03:04:36.920 --> 03:04:41.240
[Guest]: it incredibly hard to separate its roles as policymaker, regulator, and provider, right?

03:04:41.240 --> 03:04:44.760
[Guest]: And so those are three very different functions that require different approaches to the private

03:04:44.760 --> 03:04:49.200
[Guest]: sector. So on the policy side, that's basically all I would do, right? Now, there's a second

03:04:49.200 --> 03:04:53.360
[Guest]: part of the policy side on private schools, which is, I think there is a case for saying,

03:04:53.360 --> 03:04:58.760
[Guest]: how do you harness the creative energies of the private sector? And going back to something

03:04:58.760 --> 03:05:02.920
[Guest]: I said at the very beginning, right? That if the problem with the market, the democratic

03:05:02.920 --> 03:05:07.840
[Guest]: ideal is one person, one vote, okay? The market ends up doing one rupee, one vote, okay? So

03:05:07.840 --> 03:05:12.280
[Guest]: what would kind of a left libertarian do is you say, you equalize the playing field or

03:05:12.280 --> 03:05:15.800
[Guest]: reduce the inequality by putting purchasing power in the hands of the poor, and then let

03:05:15.800 --> 03:05:19.200
[Guest]: the market cater to them, right? Which is kind of exactly the voucher idea. And I think

03:05:19.200 --> 03:05:22.480
[Guest]: we're all in sync with that. And in fact, to connect back to, you know, so that your

03:05:22.480 --> 03:05:25.720
[Guest]: listeners understand that first one hour was not a long ramble of different things, but

03:05:25.720 --> 03:05:30.320
[Guest]: everything is connected, right? Through those principles. So going back to why this is consistent

03:05:30.320 --> 03:05:35.000
[Guest]: with Amartya Sen, right? Because the Sen point is that providing purchasing power and then

03:05:35.000 --> 03:05:38.480
[Guest]: letting the market provide the food was in fact a better approach than trying to actually

03:05:38.480 --> 03:05:42.480
[Guest]: send food into the famine hit areas, right? So similarly, you know, the voucher of providing

03:05:42.480 --> 03:05:46.320
[Guest]: the purchasing power would do that. Now, I think that the limitation with vouchers is

03:05:46.320 --> 03:05:51.320
[Guest]: not the conceptual point of empowering parents and letting them choose. It is the challenge

03:05:51.320 --> 03:05:56.800
[Guest]: that we have seen evidence in multiple settings that because parents perceive school quality

03:05:56.800 --> 03:06:01.920
[Guest]: based on the level of achievement and not on the value addition, it creates incentives

03:06:01.920 --> 03:06:07.120
[Guest]: on the school side to basically focus on selection as opposed to value addition, right? And so

03:06:07.120 --> 03:06:12.240
[Guest]: the question is, how do you harness the energies of the private sector and kind of architect

03:06:12.240 --> 03:06:16.880
[Guest]: a system that harnesses that for the public good? So the idea of a charter school is very

03:06:16.880 --> 03:06:20.680
[Guest]: simple, right? Which is you basically say this is still a public school, but you award

03:06:20.680 --> 03:06:25.800
[Guest]: management contracts to kind of qualified private school operators, and they get reimbursed

03:06:25.800 --> 03:06:30.480
[Guest]: on a per-child basis. And the only two restrictions are that you cannot do selective admissions.

03:06:30.480 --> 03:06:34.680
[Guest]: So any child who applies to this school with public funding should be admitted. And if

03:06:34.680 --> 03:06:38.760
[Guest]: you have excess demand, then you run a lottery. And the second is that you're not allowed

03:06:38.760 --> 03:06:43.160
[Guest]: to charge top-up fees because then that again creates a gradient based on ability to pay,

03:06:43.160 --> 03:06:47.440
[Guest]: right? But subject to that, you run the charter. And what the evidence in the US shows is that

03:06:47.440 --> 03:06:51.280
[Guest]: the charter schools have been much more effective than the vouchers. And the main reason, and

03:06:51.280 --> 03:06:55.800
[Guest]: this goes back to pedagogy, right, is that because the charter schools are often set

03:06:55.800 --> 03:07:01.360
[Guest]: up in low-income communities, the entire pedagogy in the school is optimized for a context where

03:07:01.360 --> 03:07:05.480
[Guest]: children don't have the kind of home support that is envisaged by a typical private school.

03:07:05.480 --> 03:07:08.800
[Guest]: So a typical private school will assume that the parents can do this and parents can do

03:07:08.800 --> 03:07:12.640
[Guest]: this and parents can do that. And a lot of your, in fact, what we see even in our own

03:07:12.640 --> 03:07:16.440
[Guest]: AP data is if you look at the value adds, the typical child who goes to the private

03:07:16.440 --> 03:07:20.040
[Guest]: school actually does much better gains than the typical child going to the government

03:07:20.040 --> 03:07:23.720
[Guest]: school, right? It's the voucher child who doesn't disproportionately benefit. And that's

03:07:23.720 --> 03:07:28.480
[Guest]: partly because they are much lower SES and starting at close to 0.8 standard deviations

03:07:28.480 --> 03:07:32.040
[Guest]: below, which means that teaching at the right level problem is probably applying, right?

03:07:32.040 --> 03:07:37.040
[Guest]: So what the charters have been doing is optimizing pedagogy for low-income settings, making sure

03:07:37.040 --> 03:07:40.720
[Guest]: that you have extra time to complete homework because your parents are not able to support

03:07:40.720 --> 03:07:45.240
[Guest]: you, right? So there's a bunch of additional pedagogical innovations that are optimized

03:07:45.240 --> 03:07:48.960
[Guest]: around how do you improve learning outcomes. So the way I would think about our policy

03:07:48.960 --> 03:07:52.680
[Guest]: framework for India for leveraging charter schools is almost to say, let's set a grand

03:07:52.680 --> 03:07:56.720
[Guest]: challenge, right? Where we say as a grand challenge, the truth is we actually have not

03:07:56.720 --> 03:08:02.000
[Guest]: yet cracked the problem of how do you deliver learning outcomes at scale to first generation

03:08:02.000 --> 03:08:06.400
[Guest]: learners. I mean, this is an incredibly hard, wicked problem. We've thrown a lot of money.

03:08:06.400 --> 03:08:09.840
[Guest]: We've tried all kinds of approaches. I have talked about a foundational literacy and humanism

03:08:09.840 --> 03:08:13.440
[Guest]: mission, the certain principles, but there's no guarantee that will succeed, right? So

03:08:13.440 --> 03:08:17.800
[Guest]: maybe a better approach would be to say that here is the budget per child, right? I'm going

03:08:17.800 --> 03:08:21.480
[Guest]: to open up a bunch of schools to these charter kind of private management. And what you're

03:08:21.480 --> 03:08:25.360
[Guest]: seeing already in India is that there are a bunch of these education providers who have

03:08:25.360 --> 03:08:29.520
[Guest]: come to exactly the same realization that they would like to serve low-income communities,

03:08:29.520 --> 03:08:34.160
[Guest]: but that they would like to have management autonomy on schools. And so there are nonprofits,

03:08:34.160 --> 03:08:38.040
[Guest]: I think people, Akanksha, Madhi, you know, the bunch of people who are actually doing

03:08:38.040 --> 03:08:42.680
[Guest]: this. The problem today is that the government is allowing them in, but they are raising

03:08:42.680 --> 03:08:47.080
[Guest]: their money from CSR, right? And so the government is not kind of reimbursing that. And so that

03:08:47.080 --> 03:08:51.520
[Guest]: gets us to, you know, Manish Sabharwal's wonderful quote of the impossible trilemma in service

03:08:51.520 --> 03:08:55.980
[Guest]: delivery here, right? Which is that the government has an execution deficit. The private sector

03:08:55.980 --> 03:09:00.280
[Guest]: has a trust deficit and civil society has a scale deficit, right? Because civil society

03:09:00.280 --> 03:09:06.740
[Guest]: has both intentions and ability to deliver, but is limited by kind of its fundraising.

03:09:06.740 --> 03:09:11.040
[Guest]: Government has scale and legitimacy, but can't execute to save its life. The private sector

03:09:11.040 --> 03:09:15.760
[Guest]: can execute at scale. So, you know, in all my years of fieldwork in rural India, the

03:09:15.760 --> 03:09:19.080
[Guest]: time when I started getting drinking water was when then like Coke and Pepsi started

03:09:19.080 --> 03:09:23.520
[Guest]: having Kinley and Aquafina. So their kind of logistics and delivery networks would reach

03:09:23.520 --> 03:09:28.920
[Guest]: the hinterland way before like any government yajna would reach, right? So in that sense,

03:09:28.920 --> 03:09:33.560
[Guest]: the private sector can deliver at scale. The problem is that, and this is where it gets

03:09:33.560 --> 03:09:37.520
[Guest]: so difficult when we think about private sector and health and education, which is there is

03:09:37.520 --> 03:09:42.600
[Guest]: a point up to which you can improve outcomes by squeezing inefficiency out of the system.

03:09:42.600 --> 03:09:46.360
[Guest]: But beyond that, even the private player also becomes a rent seeker, right? Like, you know,

03:09:46.360 --> 03:09:50.840
[Guest]: I mean, partly by excluding difficult children. You know, so there's a bunch of aspects of

03:09:50.840 --> 03:09:55.160
[Guest]: schools and public spaces, which kind of limits the unbridled use of the private analogy,

03:09:55.160 --> 03:09:59.280
[Guest]: right? So what's nice about charters is you're saying you're maintaining a couple of essential

03:09:59.280 --> 03:10:03.120
[Guest]: characteristics of public education, which is non-discriminatory admission and no top

03:10:03.120 --> 03:10:07.560
[Guest]: up fees, but you then have the autonomy and kind of come in and bring all your ideas here

03:10:07.560 --> 03:10:11.000
[Guest]: to solve this grand challenge of how are we going to improve learning outcomes at scale.

03:10:11.000 --> 03:10:14.800
[Guest]: Now there's a bunch of other complications with regard to procurement, with regard to

03:10:14.800 --> 03:10:18.040
[Guest]: the fact that there's this wonderful study in Liberia published in the American Economic

03:10:18.040 --> 03:10:22.440
[Guest]: Review recently that was done by my own former student that looked at a charter school experiment

03:10:22.440 --> 03:10:25.960
[Guest]: like this. And what it found was that there were eight different providers, but there

03:10:25.960 --> 03:10:29.680
[Guest]: is enormous variation even among the providers. So there are some who are very good and some

03:10:29.680 --> 03:10:33.400
[Guest]: who are worse than the public schools, right? So a naive sense of private versus public

03:10:33.400 --> 03:10:37.760
[Guest]: is also misguided because you need the heterogeneity, but which I think is, again, consistent with

03:10:37.760 --> 03:10:42.160
[Guest]: your view that over time, if you had a well-functioning market, the poor guys would be weeded out.

03:10:42.160 --> 03:10:47.280
[Guest]: But I think the last point I want to leave with on this is this requires incredibly nuanced

03:10:47.280 --> 03:10:51.480
[Guest]: view to architecture of service delivery, right? I mean, that recognizes that public

03:10:51.480 --> 03:10:56.320
[Guest]: and private both have their weaknesses and you want to design systems and make the two

03:10:56.320 --> 03:11:00.400
[Guest]: as complements and not substitutes because we should do a separate episode on health.

03:11:00.400 --> 03:11:03.400
[Guest]: But to give you a headline of one of these recent papers that we just published is that

03:11:03.400 --> 03:11:07.680
[Guest]: what we see is that improving public systems is actually highly correlated with the quality

03:11:07.680 --> 03:11:11.560
[Guest]: of private quality because the private has to compete with the public. And so that forces

03:11:11.560 --> 03:11:15.520
[Guest]: out the left tail of the private distribution as well, right? So it's like when we think

03:11:15.520 --> 03:11:19.840
[Guest]: about education in India, there's this old joke about two guys in a jungle being chased

03:11:19.840 --> 03:11:23.680
[Guest]: by a bear. And the first guy says, like, you know, I need, oh, we need to outrun the bear.

03:11:23.680 --> 03:11:27.640
[Guest]: And the second guy says, no, I just have to outrun you. And that's basically the story

03:11:27.640 --> 03:11:31.880
[Guest]: of service delivery in India, right? The private sector in absolute terms, the quality is nothing

03:11:31.880 --> 03:11:36.960
[Guest]: to shout out about, but it is epsilon better than the government. And that's enough, like,

03:11:36.960 --> 03:11:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, but it's not going to prevent this kind of the bear of illiteracy that has been

03:11:41.000 --> 03:11:45.760
[Guest]: kind of laying waste to generation after generation is not going to be solved by private schools

03:11:45.760 --> 03:11:49.960
[Guest]: in their current form. It's going to take a mission mode and system architecture of

03:11:49.960 --> 03:11:54.080
[Guest]: how do you harness the creativity of the private sector to come and crack this problem? And

03:11:54.080 --> 03:11:57.880
[Guest]: you know, that's what I hope like well-designed charter pilots might allow us to start doing.

03:11:57.880 --> 03:12:01.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I agree with all of that. And we shall have further episodes coming up on, let me

03:12:01.600 --> 03:12:05.920
[Amit Varma]: see number one, federalism, number two health, number three, we will actually, I'll let my

03:12:05.920 --> 03:12:11.560
[Amit Varma]: listeners know we were actually going to do an episode on COVID before we decided that,

03:12:11.560 --> 03:12:16.600
[Amit Varma]: hey, the education policy is out. And I think very kindly offered to educate me and all

03:12:16.600 --> 03:12:21.400
[Amit Varma]: of you on the state of Indian education, which has been very enlightening. We have two minutes

03:12:21.400 --> 03:12:28.520
[Amit Varma]: to go before your heart heart stops. So a quick final question, which is that, you know,

03:12:28.520 --> 03:12:33.680
[Amit Varma]: one sense that I get from looking at your work over the past few decades is clearly

03:12:33.680 --> 03:12:38.800
[Amit Varma]: that this is not the most profitable thing you could have done in terms of, you know,

03:12:38.800 --> 03:12:42.040
[Amit Varma]: your material ends. I mean, had you just stayed in the private sector, when you worked in

03:12:42.040 --> 03:12:45.920
[Amit Varma]: Singapore, you could have been a hotshot CEO somewhere. And even within academics, I'm

03:12:45.920 --> 03:12:51.120
[Amit Varma]: sure there are many interesting options, which all constitute an opportunity cost for your

03:12:51.120 --> 03:12:55.320
[Amit Varma]: passion for Indian education and solving these specific problems and working with the state

03:12:55.320 --> 03:12:59.280
[Amit Varma]: and working with state governments and getting your ass out there in village after village

03:12:59.280 --> 03:13:03.800
[Amit Varma]: and figuring, you know, actually looking at all of these problems so closely. So when

03:13:03.800 --> 03:13:08.200
[Amit Varma]: you look back on this journey, how does it kind of feel like? Do you feel a sense of

03:13:08.200 --> 03:13:12.320
[Amit Varma]: satisfaction at the fact that you've been able to make a difference on the margins?

03:13:12.320 --> 03:13:17.560
[Amit Varma]: Is it frustrating that the differences are so small and that by and large, most of the

03:13:17.560 --> 03:13:22.080
[Amit Varma]: fault lines still remain? You know, what motivates you? What keeps you going? It's very fascinating

03:13:22.080 --> 03:13:26.280
[Amit Varma]: to me, because on one hand, you are a professional, you're right, you're a professional academic,

03:13:26.280 --> 03:13:30.320
[Amit Varma]: you're a researcher, you're all of these things. But on the other hand, it often seems to me

03:13:30.320 --> 03:13:34.680
[Amit Varma]: that and not just you, I've had other people on the show, like you who are doing things

03:13:34.680 --> 03:13:38.400
[Amit Varma]: they don't need to do. And yet they're doing it out of the sense of mission. So you know,

03:13:38.400 --> 03:13:40.920
[Amit Varma]: what keeps you going? What's what's your private juice?

03:13:40.920 --> 03:13:44.600
[Guest]: So the quick answer is, I think I have the best job in the world, right? You know, because

03:13:44.600 --> 03:13:48.720
[Guest]: the and one way of knowing that I have the best job in the world is, you know, if tomorrow

03:13:48.720 --> 03:13:52.120
[Guest]: I had many millions more in my bank account, I would do exactly what I do, I wouldn't change

03:13:52.120 --> 03:13:56.280
[Guest]: a single thing of what I do, right. So in that sense, I think, you know, it was very

03:13:56.280 --> 03:14:00.840
[Guest]: clear to me in the private sector, my two years that there's no shortage of incentives

03:14:00.840 --> 03:14:05.280
[Guest]: for talent to be in the private sector. But, you know, what I wanted was to kind of take

03:14:05.280 --> 03:14:09.560
[Guest]: that level of understanding and apply those insights and whatever kind of opportunities

03:14:09.560 --> 03:14:13.120
[Guest]: I've had in the largest good, right. So and I think, but I'm not unique in that I don't

03:14:13.120 --> 03:14:16.720
[Guest]: think I deserve any special moral kudos for that. I think that's a whole range of people

03:14:16.720 --> 03:14:20.600
[Guest]: who are very public spirited. And I think we all just need to find the ways in which

03:14:20.600 --> 03:14:24.000
[Guest]: you can contribute. And so I think, you know, if you look at the studies on happiness, what

03:14:24.000 --> 03:14:28.680
[Guest]: the studies on happiness will say is that if you kind of obsess about a long term goal

03:14:28.680 --> 03:14:32.560
[Guest]: without enjoying the journey, then that doesn't make for a satisfied life. I want to be CEO,

03:14:32.560 --> 03:14:35.480
[Guest]: I want to be this, you get there and think like, what's the big deal? Because I've slaved

03:14:35.480 --> 03:14:38.720
[Guest]: away 25 years and there's it all gone, right. On the other hand, like, you know, if you

03:14:38.720 --> 03:14:41.720
[Guest]: kind of keep living for the moment, then you can go drift from pleasure to pleasure, like,

03:14:41.720 --> 03:14:45.240
[Guest]: you know, without any concrete achievement at the end of this. So where I feel incredibly

03:14:45.240 --> 03:14:50.880
[Guest]: fortunate is that I kind of love the day to day craft of the research and kind of there's

03:14:50.880 --> 03:14:55.240
[Guest]: an artistic element of what, you know, high quality research is, right. So in fact, when

03:14:55.240 --> 03:14:59.560
[Guest]: I was in Italy a few years ago, I think the, you know, what people don't see is the amount

03:14:59.560 --> 03:15:03.360
[Guest]: of blood, sweat and toil that goes into every one of these papers, right. That's published

03:15:03.360 --> 03:15:08.760
[Guest]: in a top journal, it's like 6, 8, 10 years, right. So, you know, there's the, I felt the

03:15:08.760 --> 03:15:12.760
[Guest]: highest affinity with sculptors, right, because each paper kind of feels the same way, right.

03:15:12.760 --> 03:15:15.880
[Guest]: That you start with a block of an idea, you have some idea of how this is going to look

03:15:15.880 --> 03:15:19.560
[Guest]: like. And then you carve and you carve and you chisel and you chisel to the point of

03:15:19.560 --> 03:15:23.440
[Guest]: then, you know, you're writing. And maybe my need for your writing course is the opposite,

03:15:23.440 --> 03:15:27.760
[Guest]: right, which is how do I, you know, not spend so much time and it's diminishing returns

03:15:27.760 --> 03:15:31.480
[Guest]: of kind of micro tuning every word of what I'm writing, right. But there is almost an

03:15:31.480 --> 03:15:36.320
[Guest]: artistic process in that that just gives me intrinsic joy for its own worth, right. But

03:15:36.320 --> 03:15:40.480
[Guest]: at the same time, you know, the motivation for everything I do has always been from the

03:15:40.480 --> 03:15:45.800
[Guest]: beginning about affecting the larger good. So, I feel incredibly privileged, right, that

03:15:45.800 --> 03:15:49.800
[Guest]: I have a day-to-day vocation that allows me to interact with some of the smartest people

03:15:49.800 --> 03:15:53.960
[Guest]: in the world. And the interaction with the students keeps me forever young. I think Pata

03:15:53.960 --> 03:15:57.840
[Guest]: Dasgupta once famously said that God made PhD students to keep tenured faculty honest,

03:15:57.840 --> 03:16:02.120
[Guest]: right, because, you know, you can't wing it, right. And so, the moment you leave that academic

03:16:02.120 --> 03:16:06.280
[Guest]: research life and become a talking head on TV, you know, your shelf life is maybe three

03:16:06.280 --> 03:16:09.840
[Guest]: years. And then after that, like, you know, I mean, you've lost that edge. So, it being

03:16:09.840 --> 03:16:13.680
[Guest]: an academia, being with the students is kind of what keeps that technical side of me active

03:16:13.680 --> 03:16:17.920
[Guest]: and alive. And so, I enjoy the day-to-day basis. But it's also true that if the only

03:16:17.920 --> 03:16:21.640
[Guest]: thing I cared about was publishing papers, I could have published a bit more. But I don't

03:16:21.640 --> 03:16:26.840
[Guest]: think like I'm particularly regretting, you know, that aspect of it. And it's also true

03:16:26.840 --> 03:16:31.360
[Guest]: sometimes that the academic economics profession doesn't fully value the amount of time I spend

03:16:31.360 --> 03:16:34.840
[Guest]: with policymakers, you know, the amount of chai I drink with secretaries to then kind

03:16:34.840 --> 03:16:38.920
[Guest]: of make things happen, right. But, you know, again, I go back to my advisor, Michael Kramer,

03:16:38.920 --> 03:16:42.440
[Guest]: and one of the most important things he said to me was, he's like, never apologize for

03:16:42.440 --> 03:16:45.960
[Guest]: the fact that your fundamental motivation is to make sure that 200 million kids in India

03:16:45.960 --> 03:16:49.600
[Guest]: have a better education, and that economics is a tool to get you there, right. It's a

03:16:49.600 --> 03:16:53.800
[Guest]: very powerful tool, but it's not an end in itself, right. So, in that sense, I feel super

03:16:53.800 --> 03:17:00.240
[Guest]: privileged at having, you know, a kind of a perch that keeps me constantly mentally

03:17:00.240 --> 03:17:05.360
[Guest]: agile with the freedom to do high quality work. And so, my trifecta is rigor, relevance

03:17:05.360 --> 03:17:09.080
[Guest]: and impact, right. So, where the rigor is measured by publishing the work in the very

03:17:09.080 --> 03:17:13.920
[Guest]: best journals and passing the technical scrutiny of the top, you know, scholars in the world.

03:17:13.920 --> 03:17:17.840
[Guest]: The relevance is that I'm not publishing on obscure topics, right. Like, you know, so

03:17:17.840 --> 03:17:22.160
[Guest]: I work on my rule of thumb is I work on topics of at least 10,000 crores a year of annual

03:17:22.160 --> 03:17:27.040
[Guest]: expenditure. So, if you're improving it by 1%, then that's kind of enough ROI on my time

03:17:27.040 --> 03:17:31.040
[Guest]: invested. And then the last part is impact, which then requires me to spend the time I

03:17:31.040 --> 03:17:35.480
[Guest]: do, right, like, you know, doing the work I do with governments. So, yeah, so I feel

03:17:35.480 --> 03:17:39.600
[Guest]: very, very contented. I think there is a lot of schizophrenia in my life about the balance

03:17:39.600 --> 03:17:43.040
[Guest]: between US and India. This is something I struggle with a lot. There's many, many times

03:17:43.040 --> 03:17:46.240
[Guest]: I feel like picking up my bags and just coming back because, you know, the karma bhumi for

03:17:46.240 --> 03:17:49.680
[Guest]: everything I do is India, right. Like, you know, I've got one project in Indonesia,

03:17:49.680 --> 03:17:53.400
[Guest]: one in Tanzania, but other than that, everything is India. So, the motivation of all my work

03:17:53.400 --> 03:17:57.480
[Guest]: is unapologetically Indian. And in a way, that may have actually limited some of my

03:17:57.480 --> 03:18:03.600
[Guest]: academic success because there is a fetishizing of insights to be more general in pure academia

03:18:03.600 --> 03:18:08.400
[Guest]: as opposed to contextual, right. And so, there are papers of mine that would get rejected

03:18:08.400 --> 03:18:11.320
[Guest]: from the very top journals saying that, oh, this is only about India, right. Like, you

03:18:11.320 --> 03:18:15.840
[Guest]: know, whereas if I was working on something kind of more general, then you get more narrow

03:18:15.840 --> 03:18:20.240
[Guest]: success in the academic sense, right. So, but on the other hand, it's, I would be not

03:18:20.240 --> 03:18:24.440
[Guest]: true to my journey and my motivation because it's kind of improving things in India that

03:18:24.440 --> 03:18:27.800
[Guest]: have been everything. So, and right now the balance is I spend nine months a year in the

03:18:27.800 --> 03:18:30.760
[Guest]: US, three months in India. But, you know, post COVID starting next year, I may even

03:18:30.760 --> 03:18:34.240
[Guest]: switch that. I may kind of start spending much more time in India, taking sabbaticals

03:18:34.240 --> 03:18:38.440
[Guest]: and coming here and teaching. And particularly as I'm building CJIS and trying to do much

03:18:38.440 --> 03:18:42.280
[Guest]: more detailed work with states, right. My pivot, you know, I might just in the second

03:18:42.280 --> 03:18:46.240
[Guest]: half of my life, pivot that to have a lot more time in India. So, I do hope you spend

03:18:46.240 --> 03:18:50.800
[Amit Varma]: more time in India because we can actually meet in person and, you know, fight in some

03:18:50.800 --> 03:18:55.920
[Amit Varma]: cafe somewhere while arguing about state coercion. You know, Karthik, you're so inspiring. Thank

03:18:55.920 --> 03:19:00.040
[Amit Varma]: you so much for sharing your insights on the show. I've had an incredible time talking

